IfcLiquidTerminal.Definition: A liquid terminal is a terminating or origination point for the transfer of liquid between distribution system(s). this is the point where the liquid distribution system interacts with the external environment. An example of this is a loading arm for the transfer of liquid from a docked vessel.
IfcLiquidTerminal.Name: Liquid Terminal

IfcLiquidTerminalType.Definition: The LiquidTerminalType provides the type information for LiquidTerminal occurrences.; A liquid terminal is a terminating or origination point for the transfer of liquid between distribution system(s). this is the point where the liquid distribution system interacts with the external environment. An example of this is a loading arm for the transfer of liquid from a docked vessel.
IfcLiquidTerminalType.Name: Liquid Terminal Type

IfcMarineFacility.Definition: A marine facility represents any major structure or entity that is specific to the ports and waterways domain. examples of this include quays, jetties, shipyards, breakwaters etc.
IfcMarineFacility.Name: Marine Facility

BerthCargoWeight.Name: Berth Cargo Weight
BerthCargoWeight.Definition: Total cargo weight of berths within the facility

Berths.Name: Berths
Berths.Definition: Number of standard berths within the facility

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcMooringDevice.Definition: A mooring device is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to participate in the mooring of a vessel, this could be in the form of a bollard used as an attachment point for lines or active equipment such as quick release hooks.
IfcMooringDevice.Name: Mooring Device

MaximumLineCount.Name: Maximum Line Count
MaximumLineCount.Definition: Maximum number of lines that may be secured to the mooring device.

MaximumLineSlope.Name: Maximum Line Slope
MaximumLineSlope.Definition: Maximum allowable line angle in degrees (negative if below horizontal from quay)

MinumumLineSlope.Name: Minumum Line Slope
MinumumLineSlope.Definition: Minimum allowable line angle in degrees (negative if below horizontal from quay)

IfcMooringDeviceType.Definition: The IfcMooringDeviceType provides the type information for IfcMooringDevice occurrences.; A mooring device is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to participate in the mooring of a vessel, this could be in the form of a bollard used as an attachment point for lines or active equipment such as quick release hooks.
IfcMooringDeviceType.Name: Mooring Device Type

IfcNavigationElement.Definition: A navigation element is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to provide navigational instructions and warnings to vessels, this could be in the form of a floating buoy, a fixed beacon.; Navigation elements can aggregate other components and elements to form the entire structure. this might include a frame structure to form the body, instances of IfcSign for signage or instances of IfcSignal for supplementary lights an/or sound signals.
IfcNavigationElement.Name: Navigation Element

IfcNavigationElementType.Definition: The IfcNavigationElementType provides the type information for IfcNavigationElement occurrences.; A navigation element is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to provide navigational instructions and warnings to vessels, this could be in the form of a floating buoy, a fixed beacon or sound signal.
IfcNavigationElementType.Name: Qto_Vehicle Base Quantities

IfcEvent.Definition: An IfcEvent is something that happens that triggers an action or response.
IfcEvent.Name: Event

EventTriggerType.Definition: Identifies the predefined types of event trigger from which the type required may be set.

UserDefinedEventTriggerType.Name: User Defined Event Trigger Type
UserDefinedEventTriggerType.Definition: A user defined event trigger type, the value of which is asserted when the value of an event trigger type is declared as USERDEFINED.

IfcProcedure.Definition: An IfcProcedure is a logical set of actions to be taken in response to an event or to cause an event to occur.
IfcProcedure.Name: Procedure

IfcRelSequence.Definition: IfcRelSequence is a sequential relationship between processes where one process must occur before the other in time and where the timing of the relationship may be described as a type of sequence. The relating process (IfcRelSequence.RelatingProcess) is considered to be the predecessor in the relationship (has precedence) whilst the related process (IfcRelSequence.RelatedProcess) is the successor.IfcRelSequence is defined as one-to-one relationship; therefore it assigns one predecessor to one successor.
IfcRelSequence.Name: Rel Sequence

SequenceType.Definition: The way in which the time lag applies to the sequence.

UserDefinedSequenceType.Name: User Defined Sequence Type
UserDefinedSequenceType.Definition: Allows for specification of user defined type of the sequence beyond the enumeration values (START_START, START_FINISH FINISH_START, FINISH_FINISH) provided by SequenceType attribute of type IfcSequenceEnum. When a value is provided for attribute UserDefinedSequenceType in parallel the attribute SequenceType shall have enumeration value USERDEFINED.

IfcTask.Definition: An IfcTask is an identifiable unit of work to be carried out in a construction project.A task is typically used to describe an activity for the construction or installation of products, but is not limited to these types. For example it might be used to describe design processes, move operations and other design, construction and operation related activities as well.Quantities of resources consumed by the task are dealt with by defining the IfcElementQuantity for the resource and not at the instance of IfcTask.
IfcTask.Name: Task

IsMilestone.Name: Is Milestone
IsMilestone.Definition: Identifies whether a task is a milestone task (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE).

Values.Description: Identifies whether a task is a milestone task (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)
Identifies whether a task is a milestone task (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)

Priority.Name: Priority
Priority.Definition: A value that indicates the relative priority of the task (in comparison to the priorities of other tasks).

Status.Name: Status
Status.Definition: Current status of the task.

WorkMethod.Name: Work Method
WorkMethod.Definition: The method of work used in carrying out a task.

IfcTaskType.Definition: An IfcTaskType defines a particular type of task that may be specified for use within a work control.
IfcTaskType.Name: Task Type

IfcWorkCalendar.Definition: An IfcWorkCalendar defines working and non-working time periods for tasks and resources. It enables to define both specific time periods, such as from 7: 00 till 12: 00 on 25th August 2009, as well as repetitive time periods based on frequently used recurrence patterns, such as each Monday from 7: 00 till 12: 00 between 1st March 2009 and 31st December 2009.
IfcWorkCalendar.Name: Work Calendar

IfcWorkControl.Definition: An IfcWorkControl is an abstract supertype which captures information that is common to both IfcWorkPlan and IfcWorkSchedule.
IfcWorkControl.Name: Work Control

WorkDayDuration.Name: Work Day Duration
WorkDayDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based day. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display IfcTask durations in work days where IfcTaskTime.DurationType=WORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 24 hours (an elapsed day); if omitted then 8 hours is assumed.

WorkFinishTime.Name: Work Finish Time
WorkFinishTime.Definition: The default time of day a task is scheduled to finish. For presentation purposes, if the finish time of a task matches the WorkFinishTime, then applications may choose to display the date only. Conversely when entering dates without specifying time, applications may automatically append the WorkFinishTime.

WorkMonthDuration.Name: Work Month Duration
WorkMonthDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based month. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display IfcTask durations in work months where IfcTaskTime.DurationType=WORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 744 hours (an elapsed month of 31 days); if omitted then 160 hours is assumed.

WorkStartTime.Name: Work Start Time
WorkStartTime.Definition: The default time of day a task is scheduled to start. For presentation purposes, if the start time of a task matches the WorkStartTime, then applications may choose to display the date only. Conversely when entering dates without specifying time, applications may automatically append the WorkStartTime.

WorkWeekDuration.Name: Work Week Duration
WorkWeekDuration.Definition: The elapsed time within a worktime-based week. For presentation purposes, applications may choose to display IfcTask durations in work weeks where IfcTaskTime.DurationType=WORKTIME. This value must be less than or equal to 168 hours (an elapsed week); if omitted then 40 hours is assumed.

CreationDate.Name: Creation Date
CreationDate.Definition: The date that the plan is created.

Duration.Name: Duration
Duration.Definition: The total duration of the entire work schedule.

FinishTime.Name: Finish Time
FinishTime.Definition: The finish time of the schedule.

Purpose.Name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: A description of the purpose of the work schedule.

StartTime.Name: Start Time
StartTime.Definition: The start time of the schedule.

TotalFloat.Name: Total Float
TotalFloat.Definition: The total time float of the entire work schedule.

IfcWorkPlan.Definition: An IfcWorkPlan represents work plans in a construction or a facilities management project.
IfcWorkPlan.Name: Work Plan

IfcWorkSchedule.Definition: An IfcWorkSchedule represents a task schedule of a work plan, which in turn can contain a set of schedules for different purposes.
IfcWorkSchedule.Name: Work Control Common

IfcAlignment.Definition: For the purposes of IFC the English term "alignment" defines three separate but closely interconnected concepts.definition of a reference system for linear positioning; safeguarding and optimization of the movement of vehicles - kinematic perspective; geometric construction of roads, railway tracks or other linear infrastructureReference system for linear positioningAn alignment is used to define a reference system to position elements mainly for linear construction works, such as roads, rails, bridges, and others. The relative positioning along the alignment is defined by the linear referencing methodology.
IfcAlignment.Name: Alignment

LRMConstraint.Name: Lrmconstraint
LRMConstraint.Definition: Allows for the specification of constraints imposed by this Linear Referencing Method. For example, a Reference Post Linear Referencing Method may specify that referents be of type reference marker.

LRMName.Name: Lrmname
LRMName.Definition: Gives the name of this Linear Referencing Method, such as kilometre-point.

LRMType.Name: Lrmtype
LRMType.Definition: Gives the type of this Linear Referencing Method.

Values.Description: In this Pset this is handled by adding the enumeration constant LRM_USERDEFINED and the additional property UserDefinedLRMType

LRMUnit.Name: Lrmunit
LRMUnit.Definition: Specifies the units of measure used by this Linear Referencing Method for measures along the linear element being measured.

UserDefinedLRMType.Name: User Defined Lrmtype
UserDefinedLRMType.Definition: Gives the user defined type of this Linear Referencing Method when property LRMType is LRM_USERDEFINED.

IfcAlignmentCant.Definition: An IfcAlignmentCant is a lateral inclination profile defined along the horizontal alignment. All points defined in this profile have two coordinate values. The first value is the distance along the horizontal alignment, and the second value is the height relative to the projection of the point along vertical alignment.Cant as a railway specificity
IfcAlignmentCant.Name: Alignment Cant

RailHeadDistance.Name: Rail Head Distance
RailHeadDistance.Definition: Length measured as distance between the nominal centre points of the two contact patches of a wheelset and rails.

IfcAlignmentHorizontal.Definition: An IfcAlignmentHorizontal is a linear reference projected onto the horizontal x/y plane. Points along a horizontal alignment have two coordinate values, x and y in the local Cartesian engineering system.The horizontal alignment is defined by segments that are connected end-to-start. The transition at the segment connection is not enforced to be tangential, if the tangential continuity flag is set to false, otherwise a tangential continuity shall be preserved. Based on the context of the project, they are geo-referenced and convertible into Northing and Easting values.
IfcAlignmentHorizontal.Name: Alignment Horizontal

IfcAlignmentSegment.Definition: An IfcAlignmentSegment is a segment of an IfcAlignment where either the vertical or horizontal direction or cant (in the case of trackdesign) obey a unique mathematical description as a function of the horizontal projection segment length of the alignment.
IfcAlignmentSegment.Name: Alignment Segment

CantDeficiency.Name: Cant Deficiency
CantDeficiency.Definition: Difference between applied cant and a higher equilibrium cant.

CantEquilibrium.Name: Cant Equilibrium
CantEquilibrium.Definition: Cant at a particular speed at which the vehicle will have a resultant force perpendicular to the running plane.

EndSmoothingLength.Name: End Smoothing Length
EndSmoothingLength.Definition: Length for the circular transition change of curvature at the end of the cant segment, measured from the start of the circular transition change of curvature to the end of the cant segment.

StartSmoothingLength.Name: Start Smoothing Length
StartSmoothingLength.Definition: Length for the circular transition change of curvature at the start of the cant segment, measured from the start of the cant segment to the end of the circular transition change of curvature.

EndElevation.Name: End Elevation
EndElevation.Definition: Elevation of the end point relative to the mean sea level.

StartElevation.Name: Start Elevation
StartElevation.Definition: Elevation of the start point relative to the mean sea level.

IfcAlignmentVertical.Definition: An IfcAlignmentVertical is a height profile along the horizontal alignment. Points along a vertical alignment have two coordinate values. The first value is the distance along the horizontal alignment, the second value is the height according to the project engineering coordinate system. Based on the context of the project, they are georeferenced and the height value is convertible into orthogonal height above/below the vertical datum.
IfcAlignmentVertical.Name: Alignment Vertical

IfcAnnotation.Definition: An annotation is an information element within the geometric (and spatial) context of a project, that adds a note or meaning to the objects which constitutes the project model. Annotations include additional points, curves, text, dimensioning, hatching and other forms of graphical notes. It also includes virtual or symbolic representations of additional model components, not representing products or spatial structures, such as survey points and lines, contour lines or similar.
IfcAnnotation.Name: Annotation

RoadVisibleDistanceLeft.Name: Road Visible Distance Left
RoadVisibleDistanceLeft.Definition: Distance visible to the left of the access.

RoadVisibleDistanceRight.Name: Road Visible Distance Right
RoadVisibleDistanceRight.Definition: Distance visible to the right of the access.

SetbackDistance.Name: Setback Distance
SetbackDistance.Definition: Setback distance from the point of connection on the major element along the axis of the minor element (e.g. distance from a public road at which the line of sigfht is measured.

VisibleAngleLeft.Name: Visible Angle Left
VisibleAngleLeft.Definition: Angle of visibility to the left of the access.

VisibleAngleRight.Name: Visible Angle Right
VisibleAngleRight.Definition: Angle of visibility to the right of the access.

SoundFrequency.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SoundFrequency.Name: Sound Frequency
SoundFrequency.Definition: List of nominal sound frequencies, correlated to the SoundPressure time series values (IfcTimeSeries.ListValues)

SoundPressure.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SoundPressure.Name: Sound Pressure
SoundPressure.Definition: A time series of sound pressure values measured in decibels at a reference pressure of 20 microPascals for the referenced octave band frequency. Each value in IfcTimeSeries.ListValues is correlated to the sound frequency at the same position within SoundFrequencies.

SoundScale.Name: Sound Scale
SoundScale.Definition: The reference sound scale.DBA: Decibels in an A-weighted scale; DBB: Decibels in an B-weighted scale; DBC: Decibels in an C-weighted scale; NC: Noise criteria; NR: Noise rating

Values.Description:
DBA: Decibels in an A-weighted scale
DBB: Decibels in an B-weighted scale
DBC: Decibels in an C-weighted scale
NC: Noise criteria
NR: Noise rating

DBA: Decibels in an A-weighted scale
DBB: Decibels in an B-weighted scale
DBC: Decibels in an C-weighted scale
NC: Noise criteria
NR: Noise rating

DBA: Decibels in an A-weighted scale
DBB: Decibels in an B-weighted scale
DBC: Decibels in an C-weighted scale
NC: Noise criteria
NR: Noise rating

DBA: Decibels in an A-weighted scale
DBB: Decibels in an B-weighted scale
DBC: Decibels in an C-weighted scale
NC: Noise criteria
NR: Noise rating

IfcBridge.Definition: A Bridge is a civil engineering work that affords passage to pedestrians, animals, vehicles, and services above obstacles or between two points at a height above ground.
IfcBridge.Name: Bridge

StructureIndicator.Name: Structure Indicator
StructureIndicator.Definition: The type of bridge structure (composite, coated, homogeneous or other)

IfcBuilding.Definition: A building represents a structure that provides shelter for its occupants or contents and stands in one place. The building is also used to provide a basic element within the spatial structure hierarchy for the components of a building project (together with site, storey, and space).
IfcBuilding.Name: Building

AddressLines.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AddressLines.Name: Address Lines

Country.Name: Country
Country.Definition: The two letter country code (from ISO 3166).

ElectronicMailAddresses.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ElectronicMailAddresses.Name: Electronic Mail Addresses
ElectronicMailAddresses.Definition: The list of Email addresses at which Email messages may be received.

FacsimileNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FacsimileNumbers.Name: Facsimile Numbers
FacsimileNumbers.Definition: The list of fax numbers at which fax messages may be received.

InternalLocation.Name: Internal Location
InternalLocation.Definition: An organization defined address for internal mail delivery.

MessagingIDs.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MessagingIDs.Name: Messaging Ids
MessagingIDs.Definition: IDs or addresses for any other means of telecommunication, for example instant messaging, voice-over-IP, or file transfer protocols. The communication protocol is indicated by the URI value with scheme designations such as irc: , sip: , or ftp: .

PagerNumber.Name: Pager Number
PagerNumber.Definition: The pager number at which paging messages may be received.

PostalBox.Name: Postal Box
PostalBox.Definition: An address that is implied by an identifiable mail drop.

PostalCode.Name: Postal Code
PostalCode.Definition: The code that is used by the country's postal service.

Purpose.Name: Purpose
Purpose.Definition: Indication of the purpose of this object

TelephoneNumbers.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TelephoneNumbers.Name: Telephone Numbers
TelephoneNumbers.Definition: The list of telephone numbers at which telephone messages may be received.

UserDefinedPurpose.Name: User Defined Purpose
UserDefinedPurpose.Definition: Allows for specification of user specific purpose of the address beyond the enumeration values provided by Purpose attribute of type IfcAddressTypeEnum. When a value is provided for attribute UserDefinedPurpose, in parallel the attribute Purpose shall have enumeration value USERDEFINED.

WWWHomePageURL.Name: Wwwhome Page Url
WWWHomePageURL.Definition: The world wide web address at which the preliminary page of information for the person or organization can be located.

BuildingID.Name: Building Id
BuildingID.Definition: A unique identifier assigned to a building. A temporary identifier is initially assigned at the time of making a planning application. This temporary identifier is changed to a permanent identifier when the building is registered into a statutory buildings and properties database.

ConstructionMethod.Name: Construction Method
ConstructionMethod.Definition: The type of construction action to the object, e.g. new construction, renovation, refurbishment, etc.

ElevationOfRefHeight.Name: Elevation of Ref Height
ElevationOfRefHeight.Definition: Elevation above sea level of the reference height used for all storey elevation measures, equals to height 0.0. It is usually the ground floor level.

ElevationOfTerrain.Name: Elevation of Terrain
ElevationOfTerrain.Definition: Elevation above the minimal terrain level around the foot print of the building, given in elevation above sea level.

FireProtectionClass.Name: Fire Protection Class
FireProtectionClass.Definition: Main fire protection class for the building which is assigned from the fire protection classification table as given by the relevant national building code.

GrossPlannedArea.Name: Gross Planned Area
GrossPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned gross area of the spatial structure element. Used for programming the spatial structure element.

IsLandmarked.Name: Is Landmarked
IsLandmarked.Definition: This builing is listed as a historic building (TRUE), or not (FALSE), or unknown.

Values.Description: This builing is listed as a historic building (TRUE)

IsPermanentID.Name: Is Permanent Id
IsPermanentID.Definition: Indicates whether the identity assigned to the object is permanent (= TRUE) or temporary (=FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the identity assigned to the object is permanent (= TRUE) or temporary (=FALSE)
Indicates whether the identity assigned to the object is permanent (= TRUE) or temporary (=FALSE)

NetPlannedArea.Name: Net Planned Area
NetPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned net area of the object. Used for programming the object.

NumberOfStoreys.Name: Number of Storeys
NumberOfStoreys.Definition: The number of storeys within a building.; Captured for those cases where the IfcBuildingStorey entity is not used. Note that if IfcBuildingStorey is asserted and the number of storeys in a building can be determined from it, then this approach should be used in preference to setting a property for the number of storeys.

OccupancyType.Name: Occupancy Type
OccupancyType.Definition: Occupancy type for this object.; It is defined according to the presiding national building code.

SprinklerProtection.Name: Sprinkler Protection
SprinklerProtection.Definition: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Name: Sprinkler Protection Automatic
SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Definition: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE).; It should only be given, if the property "SprinklerProtection" is set to TRUE.

Values.Description: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

YearOfConstruction.Name: Year of Construction
YearOfConstruction.Definition: Year of construction of this building, including expected year of completion.

YearOfLastRefurbishment.Name: Year of Last Refurbishment
YearOfLastRefurbishment.Definition: Year of last major refurbishment, or reconstruction, of the building (applies to reconstruction works).

MarketCategory.Name: Market Category
MarketCategory.Definition: Category of use e.g. residential, commercial, recreation etc.

MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.Name: Market Sub Categories Available Future
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableFuture.Definition: A list of the sub categories of property that are expected to be available in the future expressed in terms of IfcLabel.

MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.Name: Market Sub Categories Available Now
MarketSubCategoriesAvailableNow.Definition: A list of the sub categories of property that are currently available expressed in terms of IfcLabel.

MarketSubCategory.Name: Market Sub Category
MarketSubCategory.Definition: Subset of category of use e.g. multi-family, 2 bedroom, low rise.

NarrativeText.Name: Narrative Text
NarrativeText.Definition: Added information relating to the adjacent building use that is not appropriate to the general descriptive text associated with an entity through the inherited IfcRoot.Description.

PlanningControlStatus.Name: Planning Control Status
PlanningControlStatus.Definition: Label of zoning category or class, or planning control category for the site or facility.

RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.Name: Rental Rates In Category Future
RentalRatesInCategoryFuture.Definition: Range of the cost rates for property expected to be available in the future in the required category.

RentalRatesInCategoryNow.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RentalRatesInCategoryNow.Name: Rental Rates In Category Now
RentalRatesInCategoryNow.Definition: Range of the cost rates for property currently available in the required category.

TenureModesAvailableFuture.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TenureModesAvailableFuture.Name: Tenure Modes Available Future
TenureModesAvailableFuture.Definition: A list of the tenure modes that are expected to be available in the future expressed in terms of IfcLabel.

TenureModesAvailableNow.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TenureModesAvailableNow.Name: Tenure Modes Available Now
TenureModesAvailableNow.Definition: A list of the tenure modes that are currently available expressed in terms of IfcLabel.

VacancyRateInCategoryFuture.Name: Vacancy Rate In Category Future
VacancyRateInCategoryFuture.Definition: Percentage of vacancy found in the particular category expected in the future.

VacancyRateInCategoryNow.Name: Vacancy Rate In Category Now
VacancyRateInCategoryNow.Definition: Percentage of vacancy found in the particular category currently.

MarketCategory.Name: Market Category
MarketCategory.Definition: Category of use e.g. residential, commercial, recreation etc.

MarketSubCategory.Name: Market Sub Category
MarketSubCategory.Definition: Subset of category of use e.g. multi-family, 2 bedroom, low rise.

NarrativeText.Name: Narrative Text
NarrativeText.Definition: Added information relating to the adjacent building use that is not appropriate to the general descriptive text associated with an entity through the inherited IfcRoot.Description.

PlanningControlStatus.Name: Planning Control Status
PlanningControlStatus.Definition: Label of zoning category or class, or planning control category for the site or facility.

EavesHeight.Name: Eaves Height
EavesHeight.Definition: Standard net height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the bottom surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

FootPrintArea.Name: Foot Print Area
FootPrintArea.Definition: Gross area of the site covered by the building(s).

GrossFloorArea.Name: Gross Floor Area
GrossFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all gross floor areas within the spatial structure element.

GrossVolume.Name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

NetFloorArea.Name: Net Floor Area
NetFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all net usable floor areas.

NetVolume.Name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-out's, etc.) or openings and recesses.

BuildingThermalExposure.Name: Building Thermal Exposure
BuildingThermalExposure.Definition: The thermal exposure expected by the building based on surrounding site conditions.

CoolingDesignDay.Name: Cooling Design Day
CoolingDesignDay.Definition: The month, day and time that has been selected for the cooling design calculations.

CoolingDryBulb.Name: Cooling Dry Bulb
CoolingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature, usually for for cooling design.

CoolingWetBulb.Name: Cooling Wet Bulb
CoolingWetBulb.Definition: Outside wet bulb temperature for cooling design.

HeatingDesignDay.Name: Heating Design Day
HeatingDesignDay.Definition: The month, day and time that has been selected for the heating design calculations.

HeatingDryBulb.Name: Heating Dry Bulb
HeatingDryBulb.Definition: Dry bulb temperature for heating design.

HeatingWetBulb.Name: Heating Wet Bulb
HeatingWetBulb.Definition: Outside wet bulb temperature for heating design.

PrevailingWindDirection.Name: Prevailing Wind Direction
PrevailingWindDirection.Definition: The prevailing wind angle direction measured from True North (0 degrees) in a clockwise direction.

PrevailingWindVelocity.Name: Prevailing Wind Velocity
PrevailingWindVelocity.Definition: The design wind velocity coming from the direction specified by the PrevailingWindDirection attribute.

WeatherDataDate.Name: Weather Data Date
WeatherDataDate.Definition: The date for which the weather data was gathered.

WeatherDataStation.Name: Weather Data Station
WeatherDataStation.Definition: The site weather data station description or reference to the data source from which weather data was obtained for use in calculations.

Electricity.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Electricity.Name: Electricity
Electricity.Definition: The amount of electricity consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Fuel.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Fuel.Name: Fuel
Fuel.Definition: The amount of fuel consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Heat.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Heat.Name: Heat
Heat.Definition: The amount of heat energy consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Steam.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Steam.Name: Steam
Steam.Definition: The amount of steam consumed during the period specified in the time series.

Water.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Water.Name: Water
Water.Definition: The amount of water consumed during the period specified in the time series.

IfcBuildingStorey.Definition: The building storey has an elevation and typically represents a (nearly) horizontal aggregation of spaces that are vertically bound.
IfcBuildingStorey.Name: Building Storey

AboveGround.Name: Above Ground
AboveGround.Definition: Indication whether this building storey is fully above ground (TRUE), or below ground (FALSE), or partially above and below ground (UNKNOWN) - as in sloped terrain.

Values.Description: Indication whether this building storey is fully above ground (TRUE)
or partially above and below ground (UNKNOWN) - as in sloped terrain

ElevationOfFFLRelative.Name: Elevation of Fflrelative
ElevationOfFFLRelative.Definition: Elevation of the top surface of the finished floor level given in elevation above the local zero height. If the level varies and there is no significantly more prominent elevation, then this property may be omitted. In case of any inconsistency with the geometric positioning of the top surface, the geometric representation takes precedence.

ElevationOfSSLRelative.Name: Elevation of Sslrelative
ElevationOfSSLRelative.Definition: Elevation of the top surface of the structural slab level given in elevation above the local zero height. If the level varies and there is no significantly more prominent elevation, then this property may be omitted. In case of any inconsistency with the geometric positioning of the top surface, the geometric representation takes precedence.

EntranceLevel.Name: Entrance Level
EntranceLevel.Definition: Indication whether this building storey is an entrance level to the building (TRUE), or (FALSE) if otherwise.

Values.Description: Indication whether this building storey is an entrance level to the building (TRUE)

GrossPlannedArea.Name: Gross Planned Area
GrossPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned gross area of the spatial structure element. Used for programming the spatial structure element.

LoadBearingCapacity.Name: Load Bearing Capacity
LoadBearingCapacity.Definition: Maximum load bearing capacity of the floor structure throughtout the storey as designed.

NetPlannedArea.Name: Net Planned Area
NetPlannedArea.Definition: Total planned net area of the object. Used for programming the object.

SprinklerProtection.Name: Sprinkler Protection
SprinklerProtection.Definition: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether this object is sprinkler protected (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Name: Sprinkler Protection Automatic
SprinklerProtectionAutomatic.Definition: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE).; It should only be given, if the property "SprinklerProtection" is set to TRUE.

Values.Description: Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether this object has an automatic sprinkler protection (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

GrossFloorArea.Name: Gross Floor Area
GrossFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all gross floor areas within the spatial structure element.

GrossHeight.Name: Gross Height
GrossHeight.Definition: Standard gross height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the top surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

GrossPerimeter.Name: Gross Perimeter
GrossPerimeter.Definition: Gross perimeter at the outer contour of the object.

GrossVolume.Name: Gross Volume
GrossVolume.Definition: Total gross volume of the object. Openings, recesses, enclosed objects and projections are not taken into account.

NetFloorArea.Name: Net Floor Area
NetFloorArea.Definition: Sum of all net usable floor areas.

NetHeight.Name: Net Height
NetHeight.Definition: Standard net height of this storey, from the top surface of the construction floor, to the bottom surface of the construction floor or roof above. Only provided is there is a constant height.

NetVolume.Name: Net Volume
NetVolume.Definition: Total net volume of the object, taking into account possible processing features (cut-out's, etc.) or openings and recesses.

IfcBuiltElement.Definition: The built element comprises all elements that are primarily part of the construction of a built facility, i.e., its structural and space separating system. Built elements are all physically existent and tangible things.This IfcBuiltElement is a generalization of all elements that are major functional parts of the structural or space separation system of a built facility. Typical examples of IfcBuiltElement entities are (among others): built elements within a space separation system; built elements within an enclosure system (such as a facade); built elements within a fenestration system; built elements within a load bearing system; built elements within a foundation system; built elements within an infrastructure facility
IfcBuiltElement.Name: Built Element

IfcBuiltElementType.Definition: The IfcBuiltElementType provides the type information for IfcBuiltElement occurrences.
IfcBuiltElementType.Name: Built Element Type

IfcBuiltSystem.Definition: A built system is a group by which built elements are grouped according to a common function within the facility.The group IfcBuiltSystem defines the occurrence of a specialized system for use within the context of a facilities physical or finishing fabric. Important functionalities for the description of a built system are derived from supertypes: From IfcSystem it inherits the ability to couple the built system via IfcRelReferencedInSpatialStructure to one or more IfcSpatialElement subtypes as necessary.; From IfcGroup it inherits the inverse attribute IsGroupedBy, pointing to the relationship class IfcRelAssignsToGroup . This allows the grouping of built elements (instances of IfcBuiltElement subtypes, IfcFurnishingElement subtypes, IfcElementAssembly and IfcTransportElement).; From IfcObjectDefinition it inherits the inverse attribute IsDecomposedBy pointing to the relationship class IfcRelAggregates. It provides the hierarchy between the separate (partial) building systems.
IfcBuiltSystem.Name: Built System

DownstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
DownstreamConnections.Name: Downstream Connections
DownstreamConnections.Definition: Names of downstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

ProcessCapacity.Name: Process Capacity
ProcessCapacity.Definition: The number of units that can be processed in the time defined in ProcessPerformance

ProcessItem.Name: Process Item
ProcessItem.Definition: The type of item (and its measurement method) being modelled within a process. This can be cargo, passengers or vehicles that pass through the system.

Values.Description: passengers or vehicles that pass through the system
passengers or vehicles that pass through the system

ProcessPerformance.Name: Process Performance
ProcessPerformance.Definition: Minimum time to accept or dispatch the entire item capacity.

UpstreamConnections.Description: This property in IFC takes list as its value. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
UpstreamConnections.Name: Upstream Connections
UpstreamConnections.Definition: Names of upstream connected equipment and spaces, if not otherwise represented

LongName.Name: Long Name
LongName.Definition: Long name for a built system, used for informal purposes. It should be used, if available, in conjunction with the inherited Name attribute.;

IfcDistributionElement.Definition: IfcDistributionElement is a generalization of all elements that participate in a distribution system. Typical examples of IfcDistributionElement entities are (among others): building service elements within a heating system; building service elements within a cooling system; building service elements within a ventilation system; building service elements within a plumbing system; building service elements within a drainage system; electrical elements; building service elements within a communication network; building service elements within a sensor (monitoring) networkThe IfcDistributionElement is further specialized in the IFC specification. Direct instantiation of IfcDistributionElement without an assigned subtype of IfcDistributionElementType provides the meaning of a distribution element proxy.
IfcDistributionElement.Name: Distribution Element

ConductorFunction.Name: Conductor Function
ConductorFunction.Definition: Indicates function of the conductors to which the load is connected. Where L1, L2 and L3 represent the phase lines according to IEC 60446 notation (sometimes phase lines may be referenced by color [Red, Blue, Yellow] or by number [1, 2, 3] etc). Protective Earth is sometimes also known as CPC or common protective conductor. Note that for an electrical device, a set of line conductor functions may be applied.

EarthingStyle.Name: Earthing Style
EarthingStyle.Definition: Indicates the earthing style of the electric device.

HasProtectiveEarth.Name: Has Protective Earth
HasProtectiveEarth.Definition: Indicates whether the object has a protective earth connection (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the object has a protective earth connection (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE)
Indicates whether the object has a protective earth connection (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE)

HeatDissipation.Name: Heat Dissipation
HeatDissipation.Definition: Indicates the heat dissipation of the electric device measured in power.

IK_Code.Name: Ik_Code
IK_Code.Definition: IK Code according to IEC 62262 (2002) is a numeric classification for the degree of protection provided by enclosures for electrical equipment against external mechanical impacts.

InsulationStandardClass.Name: Insulation Standard Class
InsulationStandardClass.Definition: Insulation standard classes provides basic protection information against electric shock. Defines levels of insulation required in terms of constructional requirements (creepage and clearance distances) and electrical requirements (compliance with electric strength tests). Basic insulation is considered to be shorted under single fault conditions. The actual values required depend on the working voltage to which the insulation is subjected, as well as other factors. Also indicates whether the electrical device has a protective earth connection.

IP_Code.Name: Ip_Code
IP_Code.Definition: IP Code, the International Protection Marking, IEC 60529), classifies and rates the degree of protection provided against intrusion.

NominalFrequencyRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NominalFrequencyRange.Name: Nominal Frequency Range
NominalFrequencyRange.Definition: The upper and lower limits of frequency for which the operation of the device is certified.

NumberOfPoles.Name: Number of Poles
NumberOfPoles.Definition: Number of poles that the object would affect.

NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.Name: Number of Power Supply Ports
NumberOfPowerSupplyPorts.Definition: Indicates the number of power supply ports of the electric device.

Power.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Power.Name: Power
Power.Definition: The actual power and operable range.

RatedCurrent.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RatedCurrent.Name: Rated Current
RatedCurrent.Definition: The current that a device is designed to handle.

RatedVoltage.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RatedVoltage.Name: Rated Voltage
RatedVoltage.Definition: The range of allowed voltage that a device is certified to handle. The upper bound of this value is the maximum.

EnergyConversionEfficiency.Name: Energy Conversion Efficiency
EnergyConversionEfficiency.Definition: Measure of the efficiency of conversion of fuel energy to mechanical energy

EnergySourceLabel.Name: Energy Source Label
EnergySourceLabel.Definition: Type of energy source e.g. Electricity, Diesel, LPG etc. utilised by the element.

CarbonDioxideEmissions.Name: Carbon Dioxide Emissions
CarbonDioxideEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of carbon dioxide

NitrogenOxidesEmissions.Name: Nitrogen Oxides Emissions
NitrogenOxidesEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of nitrogen oxides

ParticulateMatterEmissions.Name: Particulate Matter Emissions
ParticulateMatterEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of particulate matter

SulphurDioxideEmissions.Name: Sulphur Dioxide Emissions
SulphurDioxideEmissions.Definition: Rate of emission of sulphur dioxide

ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.Name: Electro Magnetic Standards Compliance
ElectroMagneticStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to electro magnetic related standards.

ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.Name: Explosive Atmosphere Standards Compliance
ExplosiveAtmosphereStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to explosive atmosphere related standards.

FireProofingStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FireProofingStandardsCompliance.Name: Fire Proofing Standards Compliance
FireProofingStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to fire proofing related standards.

LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.Name: Lightning Protection Standards Compliance
LightningProtectionStandardsCompliance.Definition: Information about compliance with regard to lightning protection related standards.

IfcDistributionElementType.Definition: The IfcDistributionElementType defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcDistributionElementType.Name: Distribution Element Type

IfcElement.Definition: An element is a generalization of all components that make up a facility.Elements are physically existent objects, although they might be void elements, such as holes. Elements either remain permanently in the facility, or only temporarily, as formwork does. Elements can be either assembled on site or pre-manufactured and built in on site.
IfcElement.Name: Element

AtmosphericAcidificationPerUnit.Name: Atmospheric Acidification Per Unit
AtmosphericAcidificationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of gases responsible for the atmospheric acidification calculated in equivalent SO2

ClimateChangePerUnit.Name: Climate Change Per Unit
ClimateChangePerUnit.Definition: Quantity of greenhouse gases emitted calculated in equivalent CO2

EutrophicationPerUnit.Name: Eutrophication Per Unit
EutrophicationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of eutrophicating compounds calculated in equivalent PO4

FunctionalUnitReference.Name: Functional Unit Reference
FunctionalUnitReference.Definition: Reference to a database or a classification

IndicatorsUnit.Name: Indicators Unit
IndicatorsUnit.Definition: The unit of the quantity the environmental indicators values are related with.

LifeCyclePhase.Name: Life Cycle Phase
LifeCyclePhase.Definition: The whole life cycle or only a given phase from which environmental data are valid.

NonHazardousWastePerUnit.Name: Non Hazardous Waste Per Unit
NonHazardousWastePerUnit.Definition: Quantity of non hazardous waste generated

NonRenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Name: Non Renewable Energy Consumption Per Unit
NonRenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of non-renewable energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007

PhotochemicalOzoneFormationPerUnit.Name: Photochemical Ozone Formation Per Unit
PhotochemicalOzoneFormationPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of gases creating the photochemical ozone calculated in equivalent ethylene

RenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Name: Renewable Energy Consumption Per Unit
RenewableEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of renewable energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007

ResourceDepletionPerUnit.Name: Resource Depletion Per Unit
ResourceDepletionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of resources used calculated in equivalent antimony

StratosphericOzoneLayerDestructionPerUni.Name: Stratospheric Ozone Layer Destruction Per Unit
StratosphericOzoneLayerDestructionPerUni.Definition: Quantity of gases destroying the stratospheric ozone layer calculated in equivalent CFC-R11

TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Name: Total Primary Energy Consumption Per Unit
TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumptionPerUnit.Definition: Quantity of energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007.

AtmosphericAcidification.Name: Atmospheric Acidification
AtmosphericAcidification.Definition: Quantity of gases responsible for the atmospheric acidification calculated in equivalent SO2.

ClimateChange.Name: Climate Change
ClimateChange.Definition: Quantity of greenhouse gases emitted calculated in equivalent CO2.

Eutrophication.Name: Eutrophication
Eutrophication.Definition: Quantity of eutrophicating compounds calculated in equivalent PO4.

LeadInTime.Name: Lead In Time
LeadInTime.Definition: Lead in time before start of process.

LeadOutTime.Name: Lead Out Time
LeadOutTime.Definition: Lead out time after end of process.

NonHazardousWaste.Name: Non Hazardous Waste
NonHazardousWaste.Definition: Quantity of non hazardous waste generated.

NonRenewableEnergyConsumption.Name: Non Renewable Energy Consumption
NonRenewableEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of non-renewable energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007

PhotochemicalOzoneFormation.Name: Photochemical Ozone Formation
PhotochemicalOzoneFormation.Definition: Quantity of gases creating the photochemical ozone calculated in equivalent ethylene.

RenewableEnergyConsumption.Name: Renewable Energy Consumption
RenewableEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of renewable energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007

ResourceDepletion.Name: Resource Depletion
ResourceDepletion.Definition: Quantity of resources used calculated in equivalent antimony.

StratosphericOzoneLayerDestruction.Name: Stratospheric Ozone Layer Destruction
StratosphericOzoneLayerDestruction.Definition: Quantity of gases destroying the stratospheric ozone layer calculated in equivalent CFC-R11.

TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumption.Name: Total Primary Energy Consumption
TotalPrimaryEnergyConsumption.Definition: Quantity of energy used as defined in ISO21930: 2007.

MaximumAtmosphericPressure.Name: Maximum Atmospheric Pressure
MaximumAtmosphericPressure.Definition: Maximum level of atmospheric pressure that the equipment can operate effectively in.

MaximumRainIntensity.Name: Maximum Rain Intensity
MaximumRainIntensity.Definition: Maximum level of rain intensity that the equipment can operate effectively in. It is usually measured in millimeter per hour (mm/h).

MaximumSolarRadiation.Name: Maximum Solar Radiation
MaximumSolarRadiation.Definition: Maximum level of solar irradiance that the equipment can operate effectively in. This is usually tested and measured by a national or international standard. The value indicates power density measured in watt per square meter (w/m2).

MaximumWindSpeed.Name: Maximum Wind Speed
MaximumWindSpeed.Definition: Maximum resistance to wind load exposure.

OperationalTemperatureRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
OperationalTemperatureRange.Name: Operational Temperature Range
OperationalTemperatureRange.Definition: The temperature range in which the device operates normally.

ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.Name: Reference Air Relative Humidity
ReferenceAirRelativeHumidity.Definition: Measurement of the ratio of water vapor in the air.

ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.Name: Reference Environment Temperature

SaltMistLevel.Name: Salt Mist Level
SaltMistLevel.Definition: Maximum level of salt mist that the equipment can operate effectively in. It is provided according to an international or national standard.

SeismicResistance.Name: Seismic Resistance
SeismicResistance.Definition: Maximum magnitude of earthquake that the equipment complies with. The value indicates earthquake intensity measured in Richter scale.

SmokeLevel.Name: Smoke Level
SmokeLevel.Definition: Maximum level of smoke that the equipment complies with. It is provided according to an international or national standard.

StorageTemperatureRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
StorageTemperatureRange.Name: Storage Temperature Range
StorageTemperatureRange.Definition: Allowed storage temperature range that the element complies with.

AcceptanceDate.Name: Acceptance Date
AcceptanceDate.Definition: Date on which the element is accepted by the manager or administrator.

InstallationDate.Name: Installation Date
InstallationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is installed.

PutIntoOperationDate.Name: Put Into Operation Date
PutIntoOperationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is put into operation.

RepairContent.Name: Repair Content
RepairContent.Definition: Content of repair, reason and nature can be given, e.g. display faults, communication failure, display exchange.

RepairDate.Name: Repair Date
RepairDate.Definition: Date on which the last repair is done on the asset.

AssessmentCondition.Name: Assessment Condition
AssessmentCondition.Definition: The overall condition of a product based on an assessment of the contributions to the overall condition made by the various criteria considered. The meanings given to the values of assessed condition should be agreed and documented by local agreements. For instance, is overall condition measured on a scale of 1 - 10 or by assigning names such as Good, OK, Poor.

AssessmentDate.Name: Assessment Date
AssessmentDate.Definition: Date on which the overall condition is assessed

AssessmentFrequency.Name: Assessment Frequency
AssessmentFrequency.Definition: Indicates how often the equipment should be assessed, to have a clear estimation on its working state, based on which the maintenance staff can decide whether it requires maintenance or requires to be updated or replaced.

AssessmentMethod.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AssessmentMethod.Name: Assessment Method
AssessmentMethod.Definition: External reference to assessment method or application used to perform the assessment.

AssessmentType.Name: Assessment Type
AssessmentType.Definition: Category of latest condition assessment report of the asset.

LastAssessmentReport.Name: Last Assessment Report
LastAssessmentReport.Definition: Reference to latest condition (state of health) report.

ProcurementMethod.Name: Procurement Method
ProcurementMethod.Definition: The method by which an IfcProductType/IfcProduct is acquired and installed. The value provided shall be one of the following four character acronyms: CFCI (meaning Contractor Furnished Contractor Installed), OFCI (meaning Owner Furnished Contractor Installed), or OFOI (meaning Owner Furnished Owner Installed).

SpecificationSectionNumber.Name: Specification Section Number
SpecificationSectionNumber.Definition: A reference number to an external contract technical specification section describing either (a) minimum performance requirements of a given IfcProductType/IfcProduct or (b) a preselection for a specific IfcProductType/IfcProduct made for this project.

SubmittalIdentifer.Name: Submittal Identifer
SubmittalIdentifer.Definition: The reference number to an external construction administration submittal used by the construction contractor and/or subcontractor to verify that the referenced IfcProductType/IfcProduct selection conforms with the requirements found in the referenced SpecificationSectionNumber.

AssetIdentifier.Name: Asset Identifier
AssetIdentifier.Definition: A unique identification assigned to an asset that enables its differentiation from other assets.

InstallationDate.Name: Installation Date
InstallationDate.Definition: Date on which the element is installed.

ModelNumber.Name: Model Number
ModelNumber.Definition: The model number and/or unit designator assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

AccidentResponse.Name: Accident Response
AccidentResponse.Definition: Accident response chosen for the asset

AssetCriticality.Name: Asset Criticality
AssetCriticality.Definition: Rating of the asset's criticality to the operation of the facility

AssetFrailty.Name: Asset Frailty
AssetFrailty.Definition: Rating of the asset's frailty to breakage or deterioration

AssetPriority.Name: Asset Priority
AssetPriority.Definition: Combined criticality and frailty rating indicating the operational and maintenance priority of the asset

MonitoringType.Name: Monitoring Type
MonitoringType.Definition: Monitoring strategy chosen for the asset

ConditionDisposalLevel.Name: Condition Disposal Level
ConditionDisposalLevel.Definition: Condition that will trigger a disposal process

ConditionReplacementLevel.Name: Condition Replacement Level
ConditionReplacementLevel.Definition: Condition that will trigger a replacement process

DurationDisposalLevel.Name: Duration Disposal Level
DurationDisposalLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which disposal is performed

DurationMaintenanceLevel.Name: Duration Maintenance Level
DurationMaintenanceLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which maintenance is performed

DurationReplacementLevel.Name: Duration Replacement Level
DurationReplacementLevel.Definition: Duration interval at which replacement is performed

DurationTargetPerformance.Name: Duration Target Performance
DurationTargetPerformance.Definition: Target time to failure of the asset

DisposalLevel.Name: Disposal Level
DisposalLevel.Definition: Performance level at which disposal takes place

PerformanceMaintenanceLevel.Name: Performance Maintenance Level
PerformanceMaintenanceLevel.Definition: Performance level at which maintenance takes place

ReplacementLevel.Name: Replacement Level
ReplacementLevel.Definition: Performance level at which replacement takes place

TargetPerformance.Name: Target Performance
TargetPerformance.Definition: Target capacity or performance of the asset. Units of the performance value are specified through the propertyValue units attribute.

AcquisitionDate.Name: Acquisition Date
AcquisitionDate.Definition: The date that the manufactured item was purchased.

AssemblyPlace.Name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

Values.Description: other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site

BarCode.Name: Bar Code
BarCode.Definition: The identity of the bar code given to an occurrence of the product.

BatchReference.Name: Batch Reference
BatchReference.Definition: The identity of the batch reference from which an occurrence of a product is taken.

ManufacturingDate.Name: Manufacturing Date
ManufacturingDate.Definition: Date on which the element was manufactured.

SerialNumber.Name: Serial Number
SerialNumber.Definition: The manufacturer's serial number assigned to an occurrence of a product.

ArticleNumber.Name: Article Number
ArticleNumber.Definition: Article number or reference that is be applied to a configured product according to a standard scheme for article number definition as defined by the manufacturer. It is often used as the purchasing number.

AssemblyPlace.Name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

Values.Description: other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site

GlobalTradeItemNumber.Name: Global Trade Item Number
GlobalTradeItemNumber.Definition: The Global Trade Item Number (GTIN) is an identifier for trade items developed by GS1 (www.gs1.org).

Manufacturer.Name: Manufacturer
Manufacturer.Definition: The organization that manufactured and/or assembled the item.

ModelLabel.Name: Model Label
ModelLabel.Definition: The descriptive model name of the product model (or product line) as assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

ModelReference.Name: Model Reference
ModelReference.Definition: The model number or designator of the product model (or product line) as assigned by the manufacturer of the manufactured item.

OperationalDocument.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
OperationalDocument.Name: Operational Document

PerformanceCertificate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
PerformanceCertificate.Name: Performance Certificate

ProductionYear.Name: Production Year
ProductionYear.Definition: The year of production of the manufactured item.

SafetyDocument.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
SafetyDocument.Name: Safety Document

MeanTimeBetweenFailure.Name: Mean Time Between Failure
MeanTimeBetweenFailure.Definition: The average time duration between instances of failure of a product.

ServiceLifeDuration.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ServiceLifeDuration.Name: Service Life Duration
ServiceLifeDuration.Definition: The length or duration of a service life.The lower bound indicates pessimistic service life, the upper bound indicates optimistic service life, and the setpoint indicates the typical service life.

Exclusions.Name: Exclusions
Exclusions.Definition: Items, conditions or actions that may be excluded from the warranty or that may cause the warranty to become void.

IsExtendedWarranty.Name: Is Extended Warranty
IsExtendedWarranty.Definition: Indication of whether this is an extended warranty whose duration is greater than that normally assigned to an artefact (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE).

Values.Description: Indication of whether this is an extended warranty whose duration is greater than that normally assigned to an artefact (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE)
Indication of whether this is an extended warranty whose duration is greater than that normally assigned to an artefact (=TRUE) or not (= FALSE)

PointOfContact.Name: Point of Contact
PointOfContact.Definition: The organization that should be contacted for action under the terms of the warranty. Note that the role of the organization (manufacturer, supplier, installer etc.) is determined by the IfcActorRole attribute of IfcOrganization.

WarrantyIdentifier.Name: Warranty Identifier
WarrantyIdentifier.Definition: The identifier assigned to a warranty.

WarrantyPeriod.Name: Warranty Period
WarrantyPeriod.Definition: The time duration during which a manufacturer or supplier guarantees or warrants the performance of an artefact.

WarrantyStartDate.Name: Warranty Start Date
WarrantyStartDate.Definition: The date on which the warranty commences.

CyclicPath.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
CyclicPath.Name: Cyclic Path
CyclicPath.Definition: Represents the time: angle table of the kinematic behaviour.

CyclicRange.Name: Cyclic Range
CyclicRange.Definition: Identifies the angular range of the kinematic behaviour

LinearPath.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
LinearPath.Name: Linear Path
LinearPath.Definition: Represents the time: distance table of the kinematic behaviour.

LinearRange.Name: Linear Range
LinearRange.Definition: Identifies the linear range of the kinematic behaviour.

MaximumAngularVelocity.Name: Maximum Angular Velocity
MaximumAngularVelocity.Definition: Identifies the maximum angular velocity of the kinematic behaviour.

MaximumConstantSpeed.Name: Maximum Constant Speed
MaximumConstantSpeed.Definition: Identifies the maximum constant speed over the kinematic path.

MinimumTime.Name: Minimum Time
MinimumTime.Definition: Identifies the minimum time for the kinematic behaviour.

Tag.Name: Tag
Tag.Definition: The tag (or label) identifier at the particular instance of a product, e.g. the serial number, or the position number. It is the identifier at the occurrence level.

ElementType.Name: Element Type
ElementType.Definition: The type denotes a particular type that indicates the object further. The use has to be established at the level of instantiable subtypes. In particular it holds the user defined type, if the enumeration of the attribute 'PredefinedType' is set to USERDEFINED.

IfcElementAssembly.Definition: The IfcElementAssembly represents complex element assemblies aggregated from several elements, such as discrete elements, building elements, or other elements.
IfcElementAssembly.Name: Element Assembly

Status.Name: Status
Status.Definition: Status of the element, predominately used in renovation or retrofitting projects. The status can be assigned to as "New" - element designed as new addition, "Existing" - element exists and remains, "Demolish" - element existed but is to be demolished, "Temporary" - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure).

Values.Description: "Demolish" - element existed but is to be demolished
The status can be assigned to as "New" - element designed as new addition
"Temporary" - element will exists only temporary (like a temporary support structure)

AssemblyPlace.Definition: A designation of where the assembly is intended to take place defined by an Enum.

IfcElementAssemblyType.Definition: The IfcElementAssemblyType defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcElementAssemblyType.Name: Element Assembly Type

IfcElementQuantity.Definition: An IfcElementQuantity defines a set of derived measures of an element's physical property. Elements could be spatial structure elements (like buildings, storeys, or spaces) or building elements (like walls, slabs, finishes). The IfcElementQuantity gets assigned to the element by using the IfcRelDefinesByProperties relationship.The optional MethodOfMeasurement attribute defines the code, e.g. from a standard method of measurement, which had been used to calculate the element quantity.
IfcElementQuantity.Name: Element Quantity

MethodOfMeasurement.Name: Method of Measurement
MethodOfMeasurement.Definition: Name of the method of measurement used to calculate the element quantity. The method of measurement attribute has to be made recognizable by further agreements.

IfcElementType.Definition: IfcElementType defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcElementType.Name: Element Type

IfcExternalSpatialElement.Definition: The external spatial element defines external regions at the building site. Those regions can be defined: logically - for example, an instance of IfcExternalSpatialElement could represent the air space around the building without having an own shape representation, or; physically - for example, an instance of IfcExternalSpatialElement could represent the sloping ground around the building to identify the part of the external building envelop that is below ground.
IfcExternalSpatialElement.Name: External Spatial Element

IfcExternalSpatialStructureElement.Definition: The external spatial structure element is an abstract entity provided for different kind of external spaces, regions, and volumes.
IfcExternalSpatialStructureElement.Name: External Spatial Structure Element

IfcFacility.Definition: A Facility (derived from IfcSpatialStructureElement) may be an IfcBuilding, an IfcBridge, an IfcRailway, an IfcRoad, an IfcMarineFacility (or any other type of built facility defined in the future, such as IfcTunnel).
IfcFacility.Name: Facility

IfcFacilityPart.Definition: IfcFacilityPart provides for spatial breakdown of built facilities. It may be further specialised according to the type of facility being broken down.
IfcFacilityPart.Name: Facility Part

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

UsageType.Definition: Defines the convention used to subdivide or decompose the facility.

IfcFacilityPartCommon.Definition: A part that is not clearly part of one domain but is a hybrid and has shared responsibilities in multiple domains.For example 'Level crossing', 'junctions', etc. ; See the enums for more examples.
IfcFacilityPartCommon.Name: Facility Part Common

IfcFeatureElement.Definition: A feature element is a generalization of all existence dependent elements which modify the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The IfcFeatureElement offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model.
IfcFeatureElement.Name: Feature Element

IfcFeatureElementAddition.Definition: A feature element addition is a specialization of the general feature element, that represents an existence dependent element which modifies the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The IfcFeatureElementAddition offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model that add to the shape of the master element.The IfcFeatureElementAddition is associated to its master element by virtue of the objectified relationship IfcRelProjectsElement. This relationship implies a Boolean 'union' operation between the shape of the master element and the shape of the addition feature.The local placement for IfcFeatureElementAddition is defined in its supertype IfcProduct. It is defined by the IfcLocalPlacement, which defines the local coordinate system that is referenced by all geometric representations. The local placement is always defined in relation to the local placement of the element to which the feature element is added: The PlacementRelTo attribute of IfcObjectPlacement shall point (if given) to the object placement of the IfcElement, which is used in the ProjectsElements.RelatingElement inverse attribute (the parent element of the feature).
IfcFeatureElementAddition.Name: Feature Element Addition

IfcFeatureElementSubtraction.Definition: The IfcFeatureElementSubtraction is specialization of the general feature element, that represents an existence dependent element which modifies the shape and appearance of the associated master element. The IfcFeatureElementSubtraction offers the ability to handle shape modifiers as semantic objects within the IFC object model that subtract from the shape of the master element.
IfcFeatureElementSubtraction.Name: Feature Element Subtraction

IfcFurnishingElement.Definition: A furnishing element is a generalization of all furniture related objects. Furnishing objects are characterized as beingpre-manufactured and assembled on-site, or; manufactured on-site (built-in)Thus furnishing elements can either be movable, or not (as the built-ins).
IfcFurnishingElement.Name: Furnishing Element

IfcFurnishingElementType.Definition: IfcFurnishingElementType defines a list of commonly shared property set definitions of an element and an optional set of product representations. It is used to define an element specification (the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type).
IfcFurnishingElementType.Name: Furnishing Element Type

IfcGeographicElement.Definition: An IfcGeographicElement is a generalization of all elements within a geographical landscape. It includes occurrences of typical geographical elements, often referred to as features, such as trees or terrain. Common type information behind several occurrences of IfcGeographicElement is provided by the IfcGeographicElementType.
IfcGeographicElement.Name: Geographic Element

IfcGeographicElementType.Definition: An IfcGeographicElementType is used to define an element specification of a geographic element (i.e. the specific product information, that is common to all occurrences of that product type). Geographic element types include for different types of element that may be used to represent information within a geographical landscape external to a building. Within the world of geographic information they are referred to generally as 'features'. IfcGeographicElementType's include: point features such as seating, bus shelters, signage, trees;; linear features such as layby's;; area features such as ponds, lakes, woods and forests;; drainage such as catchment, reserver or outfall.The specification of the specific types are given by the inherited attribute IfcElementType.ElementType given as an IfcLabel.Geographic element types are frequently identified in feature catalogs that are produced for particular purposes. The IfcGeographicElementType entity enables the continued use of existing feature catalogs through capture of their identity and attributes.Information from feature catalogs might be captured in various ways: via property sets, some of which will be specifically defined within the IFC property set catalog whilst others will be created for local use; this is the form of capture that is expected to be most widely used; through use of the IFC classification model whereby features might be identified through an IfcClassificationReference with additional description; in which case, any further attributes required would still need to be captured in property sets.
IfcGeographicElementType.Name: Geographic Element Type

IfcGrid.Definition: IfcGrid ia a planar design grid defined in 3D space used as an aid in locating structural and design elements.
