IfcElectricFlowTreatmentDevice.ELECTRONI.Definition: Linear two-port device designed to transmit spectral components of the input quantity according to a specified law, generally in order to pass the components in certain frequency bands and to attenuate those in other bands
IfcElectricFlowTreatmentDevice.ELECTRONI.Name: Electronic Filter

NominalCurrent.Name: Nominal Current
NominalCurrent.Definition: The nominal current that is designed to be measured.

NominalPower.Name: Nominal Power
NominalPower.Definition: A conventional value of apparent power determining a value of the rated current that may be carried with rated voltage applied, under specified conditions. ( IEV ref 421-04-04)

PrimaryFrequency.Name: Primary Frequency
PrimaryFrequency.Definition: The frequency that is going to be transformed and that runs into the transformer on the primary side.

RatedVoltage.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
RatedVoltage.Name: Rated Voltage
RatedVoltage.Definition: The range of allowed voltage that a device is certified to handle. The upper bound of this value is the maximum.

SecondaryFrequency.Name: Secondary Frequency
SecondaryFrequency.Definition: The frequency that has been transformed and is running out of the transformer on the secondary side.

IfcElectricGenerator.CHP.Definition: Combined heat and power supply, used not only as a source of electric energy but also as a heating source for the building. It may therefore be not only part of an electrical system but also of a heating system.
IfcElectricGenerator.CHP.Name: CHP

IfcElectricGenerator.ENGINEGENERATOR.Definition: Electrical generator with a fuel-driven engine, for example a diesel-driven emergency power supply.
IfcElectricGenerator.ENGINEGENERATOR.Name: Engine Generator

IfcElectricGenerator.STANDALONE.Definition: Electrical generator which does not include its source of kinetic energy, that is, a motor, engine, or turbine are all modeled separately.
IfcElectricGenerator.STANDALONE.Name: Standalone

IfcElectricMotor.DC.Definition: A motor using either generated or rectified Direct Current (DC) power.
IfcElectricMotor.DC.Name: DC

IfcElectricMotor.INDUCTION.Definition: An alternating current motor in which the primary winding on one member (usually the stator) is connected to the power source and a secondary winding or a squirrel-cage secondary winding on the other member (usually the rotor) carries the induced current. There is no physical electrical connection to the secondary winding, its current is induced.
IfcElectricMotor.INDUCTION.Name: Induction

IfcElectricMotor.POLYPHASE.Definition: A two or three-phase induction motor in which the windings, one for each phase, are evenly divided by the same number of electrical degrees.
IfcElectricMotor.POLYPHASE.Name: Polyphase

IfcElectricMotor.RELUCTANCESYNCHRONOUS.Definition: A synchronous motor with a special rotor design which directly lines the rotor up with the rotating magnetic field of the stator, allowing for no slip under load.
IfcElectricMotor.RELUCTANCESYNCHRONOUS.Name: Reluctance Synchronous

IfcElectricMotor.SYNCHRONOUS.Definition: A motor that operates at a constant speed up to full load. The rotor speed is equal to the speed of the rotating magnetic field of the stator; there is no slip.
IfcElectricMotor.SYNCHRONOUS.Name: Synchronous

IfcElectricTimeControl.RELAY.Definition: Electromagnetically operated contactor for making or breaking a control circuit.
IfcElectricTimeControl.RELAY.Name: Relay

IfcElectricTimeControl.TIMECLOCK.Definition: A control that causes action to occur at set times.
IfcElectricTimeControl.TIMECLOCK.Name: Time Clock

IfcElectricTimeControl.TIMEDELAY.Definition: A control that causes action to occur following a set duration.
IfcElectricTimeControl.TIMEDELAY.Name: Time Delay

IfcJunctionBox.DATA.Definition: Contains cables, outlets, and/or switches for communications use.
IfcJunctionBox.DATA.Name: Data

DataConnectionType.Name: Data Connection Type
DataConnectionType.Definition: Indicates the data connection type of the junction box e.g. copper pair, fiber or others.

NumberOfBranches.Name: Number of Branches
NumberOfBranches.Definition: Indicates the number of branches that can be supported by the optical splitter.

NumberOfInterfaces.Definition: Indicates the types of interfaces and their number in the device.

IfcJunctionBox.POWER.Definition: Contains cables, outlets, and/or switches for electrical power.
IfcJunctionBox.POWER.Name: Power

IfcLamp.COMPACTFLUORESCENT.Definition: A fluorescent lamp having a compact form factor produced by shaping the tube.
IfcLamp.COMPACTFLUORESCENT.Name: Compactfluorescent

IfcLamp.FLUORESCENT.Definition: A typically tubular discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by one or several layers of phosphors excited by ultraviolet radiation from the discharge.
IfcLamp.FLUORESCENT.Name: Fluorescent

IfcLamp.HALOGEN.Definition: An incandescent lamp in which a tungsten filament is sealed into a compact transport envelope filled with an inert gas and a small amount of halogen such as iodine or bromine.
IfcLamp.HALOGEN.Name: Halogen

IfcLamp.HIGHPRESSUREMERCURY.Definition: A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting mercury at high pressure.
IfcLamp.HIGHPRESSUREMERCURY.Name: High Pressure Mercury

IfcLamp.HIGHPRESSURESODIUM.Definition: A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting sodium at high pressure.
IfcLamp.HIGHPRESSURESODIUM.Name: High Pressure Sodium

IfcLamp.LED.Definition: A solid state lamp that uses light-emitting diodes as the source of light.
IfcLamp.LED.Name: LED

IfcLamp.METALHALIDE.Definition: A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting a metal halide.
IfcLamp.METALHALIDE.Name: Metalhalide

IfcLamp.OLED.Definition: A solid state lamp that uses light-emitting diodes as the source of light whose emissive electroluminescent layer is composed of a film of organic compounds.
IfcLamp.OLED.Name: OLED

IfcLamp.TUNGSTENFILAMENT.Definition: A lamp that emits light by passing an electrical current through a tungsten wire filament in a near vacuum.
IfcLamp.TUNGSTENFILAMENT.Name: Tungstenfilament

IfcLightFixture.DIRECTIONSOURCE.Definition: A light fixture that is considered to have a length or surface area from which it emits light in a direction. A light fixture containing one or more fluorescent lamps is an example of a direction source.
IfcLightFixture.DIRECTIONSOURCE.Name: Direct Ionsource

IfcLightFixture.POINTSOURCE.Definition: A light fixture that is considered to have negligible area and that emit light with approximately equal intensity in all directions. A light fixture containing a tungsten, halogen or similar bulb is an example of a point source.
IfcLightFixture.POINTSOURCE.Name: Point Source

IfcLightFixture.SECURITYLIGHTING.Definition: A light fixture having specific purpose of directing occupants in an emergency, such as an illuminated exit sign or emergency flood light.
IfcLightFixture.SECURITYLIGHTING.Name: Security Light Ing

BackupSupplySystem.Name: Backup Supply System
BackupSupplySystem.Definition: The type of backup supply system.

FixtureHeight.Name: Fixture Height
FixtureHeight.Definition: The height of the fixture, such as the text height of an exit sign.

SelfTestFunction.Name: Self Test Function
SelfTestFunction.Definition: The type of self test function.

IfcMobileTelecommunicationsAppliance.ACC.Definition: An access point is a device that allows wireless devices to connect to a wired network.
IfcMobileTelecommunicationsAppliance.ACC.Name: Access Point

DataEncryptionType.Name: Data Encryption Type

DataExchangeRate.Name: Data Exchange Rate
DataExchangeRate.Definition: Indicates the data transfer rate of the access point in bit per second (bps).

MaximumNumberOfConnectedRUs.Definition: Indicates the maximum number of remote units (RUs) which can be connected to the master unit.

IfcMobileTelecommunicationsAppliance.MOB.Definition: The mobile switching centre (MSC) constitutes the interface between the radio system and the fixed networks. It is an exchange which performs all the switching and signalling functions for mobile station located in a geographical area designated as the MSC area. It consists of a MSC server and a media gateway.

MaximumNumberOfManagedBSCs.Name: Maximum Number of Managed Bscs
MaximumNumberOfManagedBSCs.Definition: Indicates the maximum number of base station controller (BSC) that can be managed simultaneously by the mobile switching center (MSC).

IfcMobileTelecommunicationsAppliance.MSC.Definition: The MSC server mainly comprises the call control (CC) and mobility control parts of a mobile switching center (MSC). An MSC server and a media gateway make up the full functionality of an MSC.

IfcMobileTelecommunicationsAppliance.REM.Definition: A remote radio unit is a component of a distributed base transceiver station that converts digital baseband signals into high-frequency (rf) signals and sends high-frequency (rf) signals to the antenna for radiation.

(IEC 441-14-425)
StarDelta: A starter for a 3 phase induction motor such that in the starting position the stator windings are connected in star and in the final running position they are connected in delta

IfcSwitchingDevice.START_AND_STOP_EQUIPM.Definition: A switch for alternatively closing and opening one or more electric circuits.
IfcSwitchingDevice.START_AND_STOP_EQUIPM.Name: Start and Stop Equipment

IfcSwitchingDevice.SWITCHDISCONNECTOR.Definition: A switch disconnector is a switch which in the open position satisfies the isolating requirements specified for a disconnector.
IfcSwitchingDevice.SWITCHDISCONNECTOR.Name: Switch Disconnector

LoadDisconnectionType.Name: Load Disconnection Type
LoadDisconnectionType.Definition: A list of the available types of load disconnection from which that required may be selected.

SwitchDisconnectorType.Name: Switch Disconnector Type
SwitchDisconnectorType.Definition: A list of the available types of switch disconnector from which that required may be selected where: CenterBreak: A disconnector in which both contacts of each pole are movable and engage at a point substantially midway between their supports. (IEC 441-14-08); DividedSupport: A disconnector in which the fixed and moving contacts of each pole are not supported by a common base or frame. (IEC 441-14-06); DoubleBreak: A disconnector that opens a circuit at two points. (IEC 441-14-09); EarthingSwitch: A disconnector in which the fixed and moving contacts of each pole are not supported by a common base or frame. (IEC 441-14-07); Isolator: A disconnector which in the open position satisfies isolating requirements. (IEC 441-14-12)

Values.Description: A list of the available types of switch disconnector from which that required may be selected where:CenterBreak: A disconnector in which both contacts of each pole are movable and engage at a point substantially midway between their supports

(IEC 441-14-08)
DividedSupport: A disconnector in which the fixed and moving contacts of each pole are not supported by a common base or frame

(IEC 441-14-06)
DoubleBreak: A disconnector that opens a circuit at two points

(IEC 441-14-09)
EarthingSwitch: A disconnector in which the fixed and moving contacts of each pole are not supported by a common base or frame

(IEC 441-14-07)
Isolator: A disconnector which in the open position satisfies isolating requirements

IfcSwitchingDevice.TOGGLESWITCH.Definition: A toggle switch has two positions, and may enable or isolate electrical power or other setting (according to the switched port type).
IfcSwitchingDevice.TOGGLESWITCH.Name: Toggleswitch

SwitchActivation.Name: Switch Activation
SwitchActivation.Definition: A list of the available activations for switches from which that required may be selected.

SwitchUsage.Name: Switch Usage
SwitchUsage.Definition: A list of the available usages for switches from which that required may be selected.

ToggleSwitchType.Name: Toggle Switch Type
ToggleSwitchType.Definition: A list of the available types of toggle switch from which that required may be selected.

IfcTransformer.CHOPPER.Definition: A chopper is an electronic power DC convertor without an intermediate AC link giving a variable output voltage by varying the periods of conduction and non-conduction in an adjustable ratio.
IfcTransformer.CHOPPER.Name: Chopper

IfcTransformer.COMBINED.Definition: A transformer that changes different quantities between circuits.
IfcTransformer.COMBINED.Name: Combined

IfcTransformer.CURRENT.Definition: A transformer that changes the current between circuits.
IfcTransformer.CURRENT.Name: Current

IfcTransformer.FREQUENCY.Definition: A transformer that changes the frequency between circuits.
IfcTransformer.FREQUENCY.Name: Frequency

IfcTransformer.INVERTER.Definition: A transformer that converts from direct current (DC) to alternating current (AC).
IfcTransformer.INVERTER.Name: Inverter

IfcTransformer.RECTIFIER.Definition: A transformer that converts from alternating current (AC) to direct current (DC).
IfcTransformer.RECTIFIER.Name: Rectifier

IfcTransformer.VOLTAGE.Definition: A transformer that changes the voltage between circuits.
IfcTransformer.VOLTAGE.Name: Voltage

IfcAirTerminal.DIFFUSER.Definition: An outlet discharging supply air in various directions and planes.
IfcAirTerminal.DIFFUSER.Name: Diffuser

IfcAirTerminal.GRILLE.Definition: A covering for any area through which air passes.
IfcAirTerminal.GRILLE.Name: Grille

IfcAirTerminal.REGISTER.Definition: A grille typically equipped with a damper or control valve.
IfcAirTerminal.REGISTER.Name: Register

IfcAirTerminalBox.CONSTANTFLOW.Definition: Terminal box does not include a means to reset the volume automatically to an outside signal such as thermostat.
IfcAirTerminalBox.CONSTANTFLOW.Name: Constant Flow

IfcAirTerminalBox.VARIABLEFLOWPRESSUREDE.Definition: Terminal box includes a means to reset the volume automatically to a different control point in response to an outside signal such as thermostat: air-flow rate depends on supply pressure.
IfcAirTerminalBox.VARIABLEFLOWPRESSUREDE.Name: Variable Flow Pressure Dependant

IfcAirTerminalBox.VARIABLEFLOWPRESSUREIN.Definition: Terminal box includes a means to reset the volume automatically to a different control point in response to an outside signal such as thermostat: air-flow rate is independent of supply pressure.
IfcAirTerminalBox.VARIABLEFLOWPRESSUREIN.Name: Variable Flow Pressure Independant

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATECOUNTE.Definition: Heat exchanger with moving parts and alternate layers of plates, separated and sealed from the exhaust and supply air stream passages with primary air entering at secondary air outlet location and exiting at secondary air inlet location.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATECOUNTE.Name: Fixed Plate Counter Flow Exchanger

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATECROSSF.Definition: Heat exchanger with moving parts and alternate layers of plates, separated and sealed from the exhaust and supply air stream passages with secondary air flow in the direction perpendicular to primary air flow.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATECROSSF.Name: Fixed Plate Cross Flow Exchanger

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATEPARALL.Definition: Heat exchanger with moving parts and alternate layers of plates, separated and sealed from the exhaust and supply air stream passages with primary air entering at secondary air inlet location and exiting at secondary air outlet location.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.FIXEDPLATEPARALL.Name: Fixed Plate Parallel Flow Exchanger

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.HEATPIPE.Definition: A passive energy recovery device with a heat pipe divided into evaporator and condenser sections.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.HEATPIPE.Name: Heatpipe

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.ROTARYWHEEL.Definition: A heat wheel with a revolving cylinder filled with an air-permeable medium having a large internal surface area.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.ROTARYWHEEL.Name: Rotary Wheel

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.RUNAROUNDCOILLOO.Definition: A typical coil energy recovery loop places extended surface, finned tube water coils in the supply and exhaust airstreams of a building.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.RUNAROUNDCOILLOO.Name: Runaround Coil Loop

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.THERMOSIPHONCOIL.Definition: Sealed systems that consist of an evaporator, a condenser, interconnecting piping, and an intermediate working fluid that is present in both liquid and vapor phases where the evaporator and condensor coils are installed independently in the ducts and are interconnected by the working fluid piping.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.THERMOSIPHONCOIL.Name: Thermosiphon Coil Typeheat Exchangers

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.THERMOSIPHONSEAL.Definition: Sealed systems that consist of an evaporator, a condenser, interconnecting piping, and an intermediate working fluid that is present in both liquid and vapor phases where the evaporator and the condenser are usually at opposite ends of a bundle of straight, individual thermosiphon tubes and the exhaust and supply ducts are adjacent to each other.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.THERMOSIPHONSEAL.Name: Thermosiphonsealed Tube Heat Exchangers

IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.TWINTOWERENTHALP.Definition: An air-to-liquid, liquid-to-air enthalpy recovery system with a sorbent liquid circulates continuously between supply and exhaust airstreams, alternately contacting both airstreams directly in contactor towers.
IfcAirToAirHeatRecovery.TWINTOWERENTHALP.Name: Twin Tower Enthalpyre Cover Y Loops

HeatOutput.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
HeatOutput.Name: Heat Output
HeatOutput.Definition: Total nominal heat output as listed by the Boiler manufacturer.

NominalEfficiencyTable.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NominalEfficiencyTable.Name: Nominal Efficiency Table
NominalEfficiencyTable.Definition: The nominal efficiency of the boiler as defined by the manufacturer. For steam boilers, a function of inlet temperature versus steam pressure. Note: as two variables are used, DefiningValues and DefinedValues are null, and values are stored in IfcTable in the following order: InletTemperature(IfcThermodynamicTemperatureMeasure) and OutletTemperature(IfcThermodynamicTemperatureMeasure) in DefiningValues, and NominalEfficiency(IfcNormalisedRatioMeasure) in DefinedValues. For example, DefininfValues(InletTemp, OutletTemp), DefinedValues(null, NominalEfficiency). The IfcTable is related to IfcPropertyTableValue using IfcMetric and IfcResourceConstraintRelationship.

HeatOutput.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
HeatOutput.Name: Heat Output
HeatOutput.Definition: Total nominal heat output as listed by the Boiler manufacturer.

NominalEfficiency.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
NominalEfficiency.Name: Nominal Efficiency
NominalEfficiency.Definition: Nominal object efficiency under nominal conditions.

IfcCoil.DXCOOLINGCOIL.Definition: Cooling coil using a refrigerant to cool the air stream directly.
IfcCoil.DXCOOLINGCOIL.Name: Dxcooling Coil

IfcCoil.ELECTRICHEATINGCOIL.Definition: Heating coil using electricity as a heating source.
IfcCoil.ELECTRICHEATINGCOIL.Name: Electric Heating Coil

IfcCoil.GASHEATINGCOIL.Definition: Heating coil using gas as a heating source.
IfcCoil.GASHEATINGCOIL.Name: Gas Heating Coil

IfcCoil.HYDRONICCOIL.Definition: Cooling or Heating coil that uses a hydronic fluid as a cooling or heating source.
IfcCoil.HYDRONICCOIL.Name: Hydronic Coil

IfcCoil.STEAMHEATINGCOIL.Definition: Heating coil using steam as heating source.
IfcCoil.STEAMHEATINGCOIL.Name: Steam Heating Coil

IfcCoil.WATERCOOLINGCOIL.Definition: Cooling coil using chilled water. HYDRONICCOIL supercedes this enumerator.
IfcCoil.WATERCOOLINGCOIL.Name: Water Cooling Coil

IfcCoil.WATERHEATINGCOIL.Definition: Heating coil using hot water as a heating source. HYDRONICCOIL supercedes this enumerator.
IfcCoil.WATERHEATINGCOIL.Name: Water Heating Coil

IfcCompressor.BOOSTER.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where pressure is increased by a booster.
IfcCompressor.BOOSTER.Name: Booster

IfcCompressor.DYNAMIC.Definition: The pressure of refrigerant vapor is increased by a continuous transfer of angular momentum from a rotating member to the vapor followed by conversion of this momentum into static pressure.
IfcCompressor.DYNAMIC.Name: Dynamic

IfcCompressor.HERMETIC.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where the motor and compressor are contained within the same housing, with the motor shaft integral with the compressor crankshaft and the motor in contact with refrigerant.
IfcCompressor.HERMETIC.Name: Hermetic

IfcCompressor.OPENTYPE.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where the shaft extends through a seal in the crankcase for an external drive.
IfcCompressor.OPENTYPE.Name: Open Type

IfcCompressor.RECIPROCATING.Definition: Positive-displacement compressor using a piston driven by a connecting rod from a crankshaft.
IfcCompressor.RECIPROCATING.Name: Reciprocating

IfcCompressor.ROLLINGPISTON.Definition: Positive-displacement rotary compressor using a roller mounted on the eccentric of a shaft with a single vane in the nonrotating cylindrical housing.
IfcCompressor.ROLLINGPISTON.Name: Rolling Piston

IfcCompressor.ROTARY.Definition: Positive-displacement compressor using a roller or rotor device.
IfcCompressor.ROTARY.Name: Rotary

IfcCompressor.ROTARYVANE.Definition: Positive-displacement rotary compressor using a roller mounted on the eccentric of a shaft with multiple vanes in the nontotating cylindrical housing.
IfcCompressor.ROTARYVANE.Name: Rotaryvane

IfcCompressor.SCROLL.Definition: Positive-displacement compressor using two inter-fitting, spiral-shaped scroll members.
IfcCompressor.SCROLL.Name: Scroll

IfcCompressor.SEMIHERMETIC.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where the hermetic compressors use bolted construction amenable to field repair.
IfcCompressor.SEMIHERMETIC.Name: Semihermetic

IfcCompressor.SINGLESCREW.Definition: Positive-displacement rotary compressor using a single cylindrical main rotor that works with a pair of gate rotors.
IfcCompressor.SINGLESCREW.Name: Single Screw

IfcCompressor.SINGLESTAGE.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where vapor is compressed in a single stage.
IfcCompressor.SINGLESTAGE.Name: Single Stage

IfcCompressor.TROCHOIDAL.Definition: Positive-displacement compressor using a rolling motion of one circle outside or inside the circumference of a basic circle and produce either epitrochoids or hypotrochoids.
IfcCompressor.TROCHOIDAL.Name: Trochoidal

IfcCompressor.TWINSCREW.Definition: Positive-displacement rotary compressor using two mating helically grooved rotors, male (lobes) and female (flutes) in a stationary housing with inlet and outlet gas ports.
IfcCompressor.TWINSCREW.Name: Twin Screw

IfcCompressor.WELDEDSHELLHERMETIC.Definition: Positive-displacement reciprocating compressor where the motor compressor is mounted inside a steel shell, which, in turn is sealed by welding.
IfcCompressor.WELDEDSHELLHERMETIC.Name: Welded Shell Hermetic

IfcCondenser.AIRCOOLED.Definition: A condenser in which heat is transferred to an air-stream.
IfcCondenser.AIRCOOLED.Name: Air Cooled

IfcCondenser.EVAPORATIVECOOLED.Definition: A condenser that is cooled evaporatively.
IfcCondenser.EVAPORATIVECOOLED.Name: Evaporative Cooled

IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDBRAZEDPLATE.Definition: Water-cooled condenser with plates brazed together to form an assembly of separate channels.
IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDBRAZEDPLATE.Name: Water Cooled Brazed Plate

IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDSHELLCOIL.Definition: Water-cooled condenser with cooling water circulated through one or more continuous or assembled coils contained within the shell.
IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDSHELLCOIL.Name: Water Cooled Shell Coil

IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDSHELLTUBE.Definition: Water-cooled condenser with cooling water circulated through one or more tubes contained within the shell.
IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDSHELLTUBE.Name: Water Cooled Shell Tube

IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDTUBEINTUBE.Definition: Water-cooled condenser consisting of one or more assemblies of two tubes, one within the other.
IfcCondenser.WATERCOOLEDTUBEINTUBE.Name: Water Cooled Tube In Tube

IfcCooledBeam.ACTIVE.Definition: An active or ventilated cooled beam provides cooling (and heating) but can also function as an air terminal in a ventilation system.
IfcCooledBeam.ACTIVE.Name: Active

AirFlowRate.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AirFlowRate.Name: Air Flow Rate

AirPressureDropCurves.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AirPressureDropCurves.Name: Air Pressure Drop Curves
AirPressureDropCurves.Definition: Air pressure drop as function of air flow rate.

Throw.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
Throw.Name: Throw
Throw.Definition: Distance cooled beam throws the air.

AirFlowConfiguration.Name: Air Flow Configuration
AirFlowConfiguration.Definition: Air flow configuration type of cooled beam.

AirFlowRateRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AirFlowRateRange.Name: Air Flow Rate Range
AirFlowRateRange.Definition: Possible range of airflow that can be delivered.

ConnectionSize.Name: Connection Size
ConnectionSize.Definition: The connection size of the object.

SupplyAirConnectionType.Name: Supply Air Connection Type
SupplyAirConnectionType.Definition: The manner in which the pipe connection is made to the cooled beam.

IfcCooledBeam.PASSIVE.Definition: A passive or static cooled beam provides cooling (and heating) to a room or zone.
IfcCooledBeam.PASSIVE.Name: Passive

IfcCoolingTower.MECHANICALFORCEDDRAFT.Definition: Air flow is produced by a mechanical device, typically one or more fans, located on the inlet air side of the cooling tower.
IfcCoolingTower.MECHANICALFORCEDDRAFT.Name: Mechanical Forced Draft

IfcCoolingTower.MECHANICALINDUCEDDRAFT.Definition: Air flow is produced by a mechanical device, typically one or more fans, located on the air outlet side of the cooling tower.
IfcCoolingTower.MECHANICALINDUCEDDRAFT.Name: Mechanical Induced Draft

IfcDamper.BACKDRAFTDAMPER.Definition: Damper used for purposes of manually balancing pressure differences. Commonly operated by mechanical adjustment.
IfcDamper.BACKDRAFTDAMPER.Name: Back Draft Damper

IfcDamper.BALANCINGDAMPER.Definition: Backdraft damper used to restrict the movement of air in one direction. Commonly operated by mechanical spring.
IfcDamper.BALANCINGDAMPER.Name: Balancingdamper

IfcDamper.BLASTDAMPER.Definition: Blast damper used to prevent protect occupants and equipment against overpressures resultant of an explosion. Commonly operated by mechanical spring.
IfcDamper.BLASTDAMPER.Name: Blastdamper

IfcDamper.CONTROLDAMPER.Definition: Control damper used to modulate the flow of air by adjusting the position of the blades. Commonly operated by an actuator of a building automation system.
IfcDamper.CONTROLDAMPER.Name: Control Damper

ControlDamperOperation.Name: Control Damper Operation
ControlDamperOperation.Definition: The inherent characteristic of the control damper operation.

TorqueRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TorqueRange.Name: Torque Range
TorqueRange.Definition: Torque range: minimum operational torque to maximum allowable torque.

IfcDamper.FIREDAMPER.Definition: Fire damper used to prevent the spread of fire for a specified duration. Commonly operated by fusable link that melts above a certain temperature.
IfcDamper.FIREDAMPER.Name: Fire Damper

ActuationType.Name: Actuation Type
ActuationType.Definition: Enumeration that identifies the different types of dampers.

ClosureRatingEnum.Name: Closure Rating Enum
ClosureRatingEnum.Definition: Enumeration that identifies the closure rating for the damper.

FireResistanceRating.Name: Fire Resistance Rating
FireResistanceRating.Definition: Measure of the fire resistance rating in hours (e.g., 1.5 hours, 2 hours, etc.).

FusibleLinkTemperature.Name: Fusible Link Temperature
FusibleLinkTemperature.Definition: The temperature that the fusible link melts.

IfcDamper.FIRESMOKEDAMPER.Definition: Combination fire and smoke damper used to prevent the spread of fire and smoke. Commonly operated by a fusable link and a smoke detector.
IfcDamper.FIRESMOKEDAMPER.Name: Fire Smokedamper

ActuationType.Name: Actuation Type
ActuationType.Definition: Enumeration that identifies the different types of dampers.

ClosureRatingEnum.Name: Closure Rating Enum
ClosureRatingEnum.Definition: Enumeration that identifies the closure rating for the damper.

DamperControlType.Name: Damper Control Type
DamperControlType.Definition: The type of control used to operate the damper (e.g., Open/Closed Indicator, Resettable Temperature Sensor, Temperature Override, etc.).

FireResistanceRating.Name: Fire Resistance Rating
FireResistanceRating.Definition: Measure of the fire resistance rating in hours (e.g., 1.5 hours, 2 hours, etc.).

FusibleLinkTemperature.Name: Fusible Link Temperature
FusibleLinkTemperature.Definition: The temperature that the fusible link melts.

IfcDamper.FUMEHOODEXHAUST.Definition: Fume hood exhaust damper. Commonly operated by actuator.
IfcDamper.FUMEHOODEXHAUST.Name: Fumehood Exhaust

IfcDamper.GRAVITYDAMPER.Definition: Gravity damper closes from the force of gravity. Commonly operated by gravitational weight.
IfcDamper.GRAVITYDAMPER.Name: Gravitydamper

IfcDamper.GRAVITYRELIEFDAMPER.Definition: Gravity-relief damper used to allow air to move upon a buildup of enough pressure to overcome the gravitational force exerted upon the damper blades. Commonly operated by gravitational weight.
IfcDamper.GRAVITYRELIEFDAMPER.Name: Gravity Relief Damper

IfcDamper.RELIEFDAMPER.Definition: Relief damper used to allow air to move upon a buildup of a specified pressure differential. Commonly operated by mechanical spring.
IfcDamper.RELIEFDAMPER.Name: Relief Damper

IfcDamper.SMOKEDAMPER.Definition: Smoke damper used to prevent the spread of smoke. Commonly operated by a smoke detector of a building automation system.
IfcDamper.SMOKEDAMPER.Name: Smokedamper

ControlType.Name: Control Type
ControlType.Definition: The type controller, signal modification effected and applicable ports

IfcDuctFitting.BEND.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
IfcDuctFitting.BEND.Name: Bend

BendAngle.Name: Bend Angle
BendAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow.

BendRadius.Name: Bend Radius
BendRadius.Definition: The radius of bending if circular arc or zero if sharp bend.

IfcDuctFitting.CONNECTOR.Definition: Connector fitting, typically used to join two ports together within a flow distribution system (e.g., a coupling used to join two duct segments).
IfcDuctFitting.CONNECTOR.Name: Connector

IfcDuctFitting.ENTRY.Definition: Entry fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., an outside air duct system intake opening).
IfcDuctFitting.ENTRY.Name: Entry

IfcDuctFitting.EXIT.Definition: Exit fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., an exhaust air discharge opening).
IfcDuctFitting.EXIT.Name: Exit

IfcDuctFitting.JUNCTION.Definition: A fitting with typically more than two ports used to redistribute flow among the ports and/or to change the direction of flow between connected elements (e.g, tee, cross, wye, etc.).
IfcDuctFitting.JUNCTION.Name: Junction

JunctionLeftAngle.Name: Junction Left Angle
JunctionLeftAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow for the left junction.

JunctionLeftRadius.Name: Junction Left Radius
JunctionLeftRadius.Definition: The radius of bending for the left junction.

JunctionRightAngle.Name: Junction Right Angle
JunctionRightAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow for the right junction where 0 indicates straight segment.

JunctionRightRadius.Name: Junction Right Radius
JunctionRightRadius.Definition: The radius of bending for the right junction where 0 indicates sharp bend.

JunctionType.Name: Junction Type
JunctionType.Definition: The type of junction. TEE=3 ports, CROSS = 4 ports.

IfcDuctFitting.OBSTRUCTION.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports used to obstruct or restrict flow between the connected elements (e.g., screen, perforated plate, etc.).
IfcDuctFitting.OBSTRUCTION.Name: Obstruction

IfcDuctFitting.TRANSITION.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports having different shapes or sizes. Can also be used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
IfcDuctFitting.TRANSITION.Name: Transition

EccentricityInY.Name: Eccentricity In Y
EccentricityInY.Definition: Distance in y direction between the two points (or vertex points) engaged in the point connection.

EccentricityInZ.Name: Eccentricity In Z
EccentricityInZ.Definition: Distance in z direction between the two points (or vertex points) engaged in the point connection.

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcDuctSegment.FLEXIBLESEGMENT.Definition: A flexible segment is a continuous non-linear segment of duct that can be deformed and change the direction of flow.
IfcDuctSegment.FLEXIBLESEGMENT.Name: Flexible Segment

IfcDuctSegment.RIGIDSEGMENT.Definition: A rigid segment is a continuous linear segment of duct that cannot be deformed.
IfcDuctSegment.RIGIDSEGMENT.Name: Rigid Segment

IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVEAI.Definition: Direct evaporative air washer: Cools the air stream by evaporating water dircectly into the air stream using coolers with spray-type air washer consist of a chamber or casing containing spray nozzles, and tank for collecting spray water, and an eliminator section for removing entrained drops of water from the air.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVEAI.Name: Direct Evaporative Air Washer

IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVEPA.Definition: Direct evaporative packaged rotary air cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water dircectly into the air stream using coolers that wet and wash the evaporative pad by rotating it through a water bath.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVEPA.Name: Direct Evaporative Packaged Rotary Air Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVERA.Definition: Direct evaporative random media air cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water dircectly into the air stream using coolers with evaporative pads, usually of aspen wood or plastic fiber/foam.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVERA.Name: Direct Evaporative Random Media Air Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVERI.Definition: Direct evaporative rigid media air cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water dircectly into the air stream using coolers with sheets of rigid, corrugated material as the wetted surface.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVERI.Name: Direct Evaporative Rigid Media Air Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVESL.Definition: Direct evaporative slingers packaged air cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water dircectly into the air stream using coolers with a water slinger in an evaporative cooling section and a fan section.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.DIRECTEVAPORATIVESL.Name: Direct Evaporative Slingers Packaged Air Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTDIRECTCOMBI.Definition: Indirect/Direct combination: Cools the air stream by evaporating water indirectly and without adding moisture into the air stream using a two-stage cooler with a first-stage indirect evaporative cooler and second-stage direct evaporative cooler.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTDIRECTCOMBI.Name: Indirect Directcombination

IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Definition: Indirect evaporative cooling tower or coil cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water indirectly and without adding moisture into the air stream using a combination of a cooling tower or other evaporative water cooler with a water-to-air heat exchanger coil and water circulating pump.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Name: Indirect Evaporative Cooling Tower or Coil Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Definition: Indirect evaporative package air cooler: Cools the air stream by evaporating water indirectly and without adding moisture into the air stream. On one side of the heat exchanger, the secondary air stream is cooled by evaporation, while on the other side of heat exchanger, the primary air stream (conditioned air to be supplied to the room) is sensibly cooled by the heat exchanger surfaces.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Name: Indirect Evaporative Package Air Cooler

IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Definition: Indirect evaporative wet coil: Cools the air stream by evaporating water indirectly and without adding moisture into the air stream. Water is sprayed directly on the tubes of the heat exchanger where latent cooling takes place and the vaporization of the water on the outside of the heat exchanger tubes allows the simultaneous heat and mass transfer which removes heat from the supply air on the tube side.
IfcEvaporativeCooler.INDIRECTEVAPORATIVE.Name: Indirect Evaporative Wet Coil

IfcEvaporator.DIRECTEXPANSIONBRAZEDPLATE.Definition: Direct-expansion evaporator where a refrigerant evaporates inside plates brazed or welded together to make up an assembly of separate channels.
IfcEvaporator.DIRECTEXPANSIONBRAZEDPLATE.Name: Direct Expansion Brazed Plate

IfcEvaporator.DIRECTEXPANSIONSHELLANDTUB.Definition: Direct-expansion evaporator where a refrigerant evaporates inside a series of baffles that channel the fluid throughout the shell side.
IfcEvaporator.DIRECTEXPANSIONSHELLANDTUB.Name: Direct Expansion Shell and Tube

IfcEvaporator.FLOODEDSHELLANDTUBE.Definition: Evaporator in which refrigerant evaporates outside tubes.

IfcEvaporator.SHELLANDCOIL.Definition: Evaporator in which refrigerant evaporates inside a simple coiled tube immersed in the fluid to be cooled.
IfcEvaporator.SHELLANDCOIL.Name: Shell and Coil

IfcFilter.AIRPARTICLEFILTER.Definition: A filter used to remove particulates from air.
IfcFilter.AIRPARTICLEFILTER.Name: Air Particle Filter

AirParticleFilterType.Name: Air Particle Filter Type
AirParticleFilterType.Definition: A panel dry type extended surface filter is a dry-type air filter with random fiber mats or blankets in the forms of pockets, V-shaped or radial pleats, and include the following: CoarseFilter: Filter with a efficiency lower than 30% for atmosphere dust-spot.; CoarseMetalScreen: Filter made of metal screen.; CoarseCellFoams: Filter made of cell foams.; CoarseSpunGlass: Filter made of spun glass.; MediumFilter: Filter with an efficiency between 30-98% for atmosphere dust-spot.; MediumElectretFilter: Filter with fine electret synthetic fibers.; MediumNaturalFiberFilter: Filter with natural fibers.; HEPAFilter: High efficiency particulate air filter.; ULPAFilter: Ultra low penetration air filter.; MembraneFilters: Filter made of membrane for certain pore diameters in flat sheet and pleated form.; A renewable media with a moving curtain viscous filter are random-fiber media coated with viscous substance in roll form or curtain where fresh media is fed across the face of the filter and the dirty media is rewound onto a roll at the bottom or to into a reservoir: ; RollForm: Viscous filter used in roll form.; AdhesiveReservoir: Viscous filter used in moving curtain form.; A renewable moving curtain dry media filter is a random-fiber dry media of relatively high porosity used in moving-curtain(roll) filters.; An electrical filter uses electrostatic precipitation to remove and collect particulate contaminants.

Values.Description: AdhesiveReservoir: Viscous filter used in moving curtain form
CoarseCellFoams: Filter made of cell foams
CoarseMetalScreen: Filter made of metal screen
CoarseSpunGlass: Filter made of spun glass
HEPAFilter: High efficiency particulate air filter
MediumElectretFilter: Filter with fine electret synthetic fibers
MembraneFilters: Filter made of membrane for certain pore diameters in flat sheet and pleated form

A renewable media with a moving curtain viscous filter are random-fiber media coated with viscous substance in roll form or curtain where fresh media is fed across the face of the filter and the dirty media is rewound onto a roll at the bottom or to into a reservoir:
RollForm: Viscous filter used in roll form
ULPAFilter: Ultra low penetration air filter

CountedEfficiencyCurve.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
CountedEfficiencyCurve.Name: Counted Efficiency Curve
CountedEfficiencyCurve.Definition: Counted efficiency curve as a function of dust holding weight, efficiency = f (dust holding weight).

FrameMaterial.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FrameMaterial.Name: Frame Material

NominalCountedEfficiency.Name: Nominal Counted Efficiency
NominalCountedEfficiency.Definition: Nominal filter efficiency based the particle count concentration before and after the filter against particles with a certain size distribution.

NominalWeightedEfficiency.Name: Nominal Weighted Efficiency
NominalWeightedEfficiency.Definition: Nominal filter efficiency based the particle weight concentration before and after the filter against particles with a certain size distribution.

PressureDropCurve.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
PressureDropCurve.Name: Pressure Drop Curve
PressureDropCurve.Definition: Under certain dust holding weight, DelPressure = f (fluidflowRate)

SeparationType.Name: Separation Type
SeparationType.Definition: Air particulate filter media separation type.

WeightedEfficiencyCurve.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
WeightedEfficiencyCurve.Name: Weighted Efficiency Curve
WeightedEfficiencyCurve.Definition: Weighted efficiency curve as a function of dust holding weight, efficiency = f (dust holding weight).

IfcFilter.COMPRESSEDAIRFILTER.Definition: A filter used to remove particulates from compressed air.
IfcFilter.COMPRESSEDAIRFILTER.Name: Compressed Air Filter

AutomaticCondensateDischarge.Name: Automatic Condensate Discharge
AutomaticCondensateDischarge.Definition: Whether or not the condensing water or oil is discharged automatically from the filter.

CloggingIndicator.Name: Clogging Indicator
CloggingIndicator.Definition: Whether the filter has an indicator to display the degree of clogging of the filter.

CompressedAirFilterType.Name: Compressed Air Filter Type
CompressedAirFilterType.Definition: ACTIVATEDCARBON: absorbs oil vapor and odor; PARTICLE_FILTER: used to absorb solid particles of medium size; COALESCENSE_FILTER: used to absorb fine solid, oil, and water particles, also called micro filter

Values.Description: ACTIVATEDCARBON: absorbs oil vapor and odor
COALESCENSE_FILTER: used to absorb fine solid
PARTICLE_FILTER: used to absorb solid particles of medium size

OperationPressureMax.Name: Operation Pressure Max
OperationPressureMax.Definition: Maximum pressure under normal operating conditions.

ParticleAbsorptionCurve.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ParticleAbsorptionCurve.Name: Particle Absorption Curve
ParticleAbsorptionCurve.Definition: Ratio of particles that are removed by the filter. Each entry describes the ratio of particles absorbed greater than equal to the specified size and less than the next specified size. For example, given for 3 significant particle sizes >= 0,1 micro m, >= 1 micro m, >= 5 micro m

IfcFilter.ODORFILTER.Definition: A filter used to remove odors from air.
IfcFilter.ODORFILTER.Name: Odor Filter

IfcFilter.OILFILTER.Definition: A filter used to remove particulates from oil.
IfcFilter.OILFILTER.Name: Oil Filter

IfcFilter.STRAINER.Definition: A filter used to remove particulates from a fluid.
IfcFilter.STRAINER.Name: Strainer

IfcFilter.WATERFILTER.Definition: A filter used to remove particulates from water.
IfcFilter.WATERFILTER.Name: Water Filter

WaterFilterType.Name: Water Filter Type
WaterFilterType.Definition: Further qualifies the type of water filter. Filtration removes undissolved matter; Purification removes dissolved matter; Softening replaces dissolved matter.

IfcFlowMeter.ENERGYMETER.Definition: An electric meter or energy meter is a device that measures the amount of electrical energy supplied to or produced by a residence, business or machine.
IfcFlowMeter.ENERGYMETER.Name: Energy Meter

MaximumCurrent.Name: Maximum Current
MaximumCurrent.Definition: The maximum allowed current that a device is certified to handle.

MultipleTarriff.Name: Multiple Tarriff
MultipleTarriff.Definition: Indicates whether meter has built-in support for multiple tarriffs (variable energy cost rates).

NominalCurrent.Name: Nominal Current
NominalCurrent.Definition: The nominal current that is designed to be measured.

IfcFlowMeter.GASMETER.Definition: A device that measures the quantity of a gas or fuel.
IfcFlowMeter.GASMETER.Name: Gas Meter

ConnectionSize.Name: Connection Size
ConnectionSize.Definition: The connection size of the object.

GasType.Name: Gas Type
GasType.Definition: Defines the types of gas that may be specified.

MaximumFlowRate.Name: Maximum Flow Rate
MaximumFlowRate.Definition: Maximum rate of flow which the meter is expected to pass.

MaximumPressureLoss.Name: Maximum Pressure Loss
MaximumPressureLoss.Definition: Pressure loss expected across the meter under conditions of maximum flow.

IfcFlowMeter.OILMETER.Definition: A device that measures the quantity of oil.
IfcFlowMeter.OILMETER.Name: Oil Meter

ConnectionSize.Name: Connection Size
ConnectionSize.Definition: The connection size of the object.

MaximumFlowRate.Name: Maximum Flow Rate
MaximumFlowRate.Definition: Maximum rate of flow which the meter is expected to pass.

IfcFlowMeter.WATERMETER.Definition: A device that measures the quantity of water.
IfcFlowMeter.WATERMETER.Name: Water Meter

BackflowPreventerType.Name: Backflow Preventer Type
BackflowPreventerType.Definition: Identifies the type of backflow preventer installed to prevent the backflow of contaminated or polluted water from an irrigation/reticulation system to a potable water supply.

ConnectionSize.Name: Connection Size
ConnectionSize.Definition: The connection size of the object.

MaximumFlowRate.Name: Maximum Flow Rate
MaximumFlowRate.Definition: Maximum rate of flow which the meter is expected to pass.

MaximumPressureLoss.Name: Maximum Pressure Loss
MaximumPressureLoss.Definition: Pressure loss expected across the meter under conditions of maximum flow.

Type.Name: Type
Type.Definition: Defines the allowed values for selection of the flow meter operation type.

NumberOfPlates.Name: Number of Plates
NumberOfPlates.Definition: Number of plates used by the plate heat exchanger.

IfcHeatExchanger.TURNOUTHEATING.Definition: A device used to remove snow from railways. E.g. electric heating device, gas heater
IfcHeatExchanger.TURNOUTHEATING.Name: Turnout Heating

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICAIRWASHER.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an air washing element.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICAIRWASHER.Name: Adiabatic Air Washer

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICATOMIZING.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an atomizing element.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICATOMIZING.Name: Adiabatic Atomizing

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICCOMPRESSEDAIRNOZZ.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a compressed air nozzle.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICCOMPRESSEDAIRNOZZ.Name: Adiabatic Compressed Air Nozzle

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICPAN.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a pan.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICPAN.Name: Adiabatic Pan

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICRIGIDMEDIA.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a rigid media.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICRIGIDMEDIA.Name: Adiabatic Rigid Media

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICULTRASONIC.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an ultrasonic element.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICULTRASONIC.Name: Adiabatic Ultrasonic

IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICWETTEDELEMENT.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a wetted element.
IfcHumidifier.ADIABATICWETTEDELEMENT.Name: Adiabatic Wet Tedelement

IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDBUTANE.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a butane heater.
IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDBUTANE.Name: Assisted Butane

IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDELECTRIC.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using an electric heater.
IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDELECTRIC.Name: Assisted Electric

IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDNATURALGAS.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a natural gas heater.
IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDNATURALGAS.Name: Assisted Natural Gas

IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDPROPANE.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a propane heater.
IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDPROPANE.Name: Assisted Propane

IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDSTEAM.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a steam heater.
IfcHumidifier.ASSISTEDSTEAM.Name: Assisted Steam

IfcHumidifier.STEAMINJECTION.Definition: Water vapor is added into the airstream through direct steam injection.
IfcHumidifier.STEAMINJECTION.Name: Steam Injection

IfcMedicalDevice.AIRSTATION.Definition: Device that provides purified medical air, composed of an air compressor and air treatment line.
IfcMedicalDevice.AIRSTATION.Name: Air Station

IfcMedicalDevice.FEEDAIRUNIT.Definition: Device that feeds air to an oxygen generator, composed of an air compressor, air treatment line, and an air receiver.
IfcMedicalDevice.FEEDAIRUNIT.Name: Feed Air Unit

IfcMedicalDevice.OXYGENGENERATOR.Definition: Device that generates oxygen from air.
IfcMedicalDevice.OXYGENGENERATOR.Name: Oxygen Generator

IfcMedicalDevice.OXYGENPLANT.Definition: Device that combines a feed air unit, oxygen generator, and backup oxygen cylinders.
IfcMedicalDevice.OXYGENPLANT.Name: Oxygen Plant

IfcMedicalDevice.VACUUMSTATION.Definition: Device that provides suction, composed of a vacuum pump and bacterial filtration line.
IfcMedicalDevice.VACUUMSTATION.Name: Vacuum Station

IfcPipeFitting.BEND.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
IfcPipeFitting.BEND.Name: Bend

BendAngle.Name: Bend Angle
BendAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow.

BendRadius.Name: Bend Radius
BendRadius.Definition: The radius of bending if circular arc or zero if sharp bend.

IfcPipeFitting.CONNECTOR.Definition: Connector fitting, typically used to join two ports together within a flow distribution system (e.g., a coupling used to join two pipe segments).
IfcPipeFitting.CONNECTOR.Name: Connector

IfcPipeFitting.ENTRY.Definition: Entry fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., a breeching inlet).
IfcPipeFitting.ENTRY.Name: Entry

IfcPipeFitting.EXIT.Definition: Exit fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., a hose bibb).
IfcPipeFitting.EXIT.Name: Exit

IfcPipeFitting.JUNCTION.Definition: A fitting with typically more than two ports used to redistribute flow among the ports and/or to change the direction of flow between connected elements (e.g, tee, cross, wye, etc.).
IfcPipeFitting.JUNCTION.Name: Junction

JunctionLeftAngle.Name: Junction Left Angle
JunctionLeftAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow for the left junction.

JunctionLeftRadius.Name: Junction Left Radius
JunctionLeftRadius.Definition: The radius of bending for the left junction.

JunctionRightAngle.Name: Junction Right Angle
JunctionRightAngle.Definition: The change of direction of flow for the right junction where 0 indicates straight segment.

JunctionRightRadius.Name: Junction Right Radius
JunctionRightRadius.Definition: The radius of bending for the right junction where 0 indicates sharp bend.

JunctionType.Name: Junction Type
JunctionType.Definition: The type of junction. TEE=3 ports, CROSS = 4 ports.

IfcPipeFitting.OBSTRUCTION.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports used to obstruct or restrict flow between the connected elements (e.g., screen, perforated plate, etc.).
IfcPipeFitting.OBSTRUCTION.Name: Obstruction

IfcPipeFitting.TRANSITION.Definition: A fitting with typically two ports having different shapes or sizes. Can also be used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
IfcPipeFitting.TRANSITION.Name: Transition

EccentricityInY.Name: Eccentricity In Y
EccentricityInY.Definition: Distance in y direction between the two points (or vertex points) engaged in the point connection.

EccentricityInZ.Name: Eccentricity In Z
EccentricityInZ.Definition: Distance in z direction between the two points (or vertex points) engaged in the point connection.

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcPipeSegment.CULVERT.Definition: A covered channel or large pipe that forms a watercourse below ground level, usually under a road or railway.
IfcPipeSegment.CULVERT.Name: Culvert

InternalWidth.Name: Internal Width
InternalWidth.Definition: The internal width of the culvert.

IfcPipeSegment.FLEXIBLESEGMENT.Definition: A flexible segment is a continuous non-linear segment of pipe that can be deformed and change the direction of flow.
IfcPipeSegment.FLEXIBLESEGMENT.Name: Flexible Segment

IfcPipeSegment.GUTTER.Definition: A gutter segment is a continuous open-channel segment of pipe.
IfcPipeSegment.GUTTER.Name: Gutter

Complementaryfunction.Name: Complementaryfunction
Complementaryfunction.Definition: Indicates the complementary function of the drain channel.

FlowRating.Name: Flow Rating
FlowRating.Definition: Actual flow capacity for the gutter. Value of 0.00 means this value has not been set.

IsCovered.Name: Is Covered
IsCovered.Definition: This property defines if the drain channel has a cover (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: This property defines if the drain channel has a cover (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
This property defines if the drain channel has a cover (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

IsMonitored.Name: Is Monitored
IsMonitored.Definition: This property defines if the Drain Channel is monitored (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: This property defines if the Drain Channel is monitored (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
This property defines if the Drain Channel is monitored (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

OrthometricHeight.Name: Orthometric Height
OrthometricHeight.Definition: The orthometric height is the vertical distance H along the plumb line from a point of interest to a reference surface known as the geoid, the vertical datum that approximates mean sea level.

Slope.Name: Slope
Slope.Definition: Slope angle - relative to horizontal (0.0 degrees).The shape information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the shape properties, provided in the attached property, the geometric parameters take precedence. For geometry editing applications, like CAD: this value should be write-only.

IfcPipeSegment.RIGIDSEGMENT.Definition: A rigid segment is continuous linear segment of pipe that cannot be deformed.
IfcPipeSegment.RIGIDSEGMENT.Name: Rigid Segment

IfcPipeSegment.SPOOL.Definition: A type of rigid segment that is typically shorter and used for providing connectivity within a piping network.
IfcPipeSegment.SPOOL.Name: Spool

IfcPump.CIRCULATOR.Definition: A Circulator pump is a generic low-pressure, low-capacity pump. It may have a wet rotor and may be driven by a flexible-coupled motor.
IfcPump.CIRCULATOR.Name: Circulator

IfcPump.ENDSUCTION.Definition: An End Suction pump, when mounted horizontally, has a single horizontal inlet on the impeller suction side and a vertical discharge. It may have a direct or close-coupled motor.
IfcPump.ENDSUCTION.Name: Endsuction

IfcPump.SPLITCASE.Definition: A Split Case pump, when mounted horizontally, has an inlet and outlet on each side of the impeller. The impeller can be easily accessed by removing the front of the impeller casing. It may have a direct or close-coupled motor.
IfcPump.SPLITCASE.Name: Splitcase

IfcPump.SUBMERSIBLEPUMP.Definition: A pump designed to be immersed in a fluid, typically a collection tank.
IfcPump.SUBMERSIBLEPUMP.Name: Submersiblepump

IfcPump.SUMPPUMP.Definition: A pump designed to sit above a collection tank with a suction inlet extending into the tank.
IfcPump.SUMPPUMP.Name: Sumppump

IfcPump.VERTICALINLINE.Definition: A Vertical Inline pump has the pump and motor close-coupled on the pump casing. The pump depends on the connected, horizontal piping for support, with the suction and discharge along the piping axis.
IfcPump.VERTICALINLINE.Name: Verticalinline

IfcPump.VERTICALTURBINE.Definition: A Vertical Turbine pump has a motor mounted vertically on the pump casing for either; wet-pit sump mounting or dry-well mounting.
IfcPump.VERTICALTURBINE.Name: Vertical Turbine

IfcSpaceHeater.CONVECTOR.Definition: A heat-distributing unit that operates with gravity-circulated air.
IfcSpaceHeater.CONVECTOR.Name: Convector

ConvectorType.Name: Convector Type
ConvectorType.Definition: Indicates the type of convector, whether forced air (mechanically driven) or natural (gravity).

Values.Description: whether forced air (mechanically driven) or natural (gravity)
whether forced air (mechanically driven) or natural (gravity)

IfcSpaceHeater.RADIATOR.Definition: A heat-distributing unit that operates with thermal radiation.
IfcSpaceHeater.RADIATOR.Name: Radiator

TubingLength.Name: Tubing Length
TubingLength.Definition: Water tube length inside the component.

WaterContent.Name: Water Content
WaterContent.Definition: Weight of water content within the heater.

IfcTank.BREAKPRESSURE.Definition: An open container that breaks the hydraulic pressure in a distribution system, typically located between the fluid reservoir and the fluid supply points. A typical break pressure tank allows the flow to discharge into the atmosphere, thereby reducing its hydrostatic pressure to zero.
IfcTank.BREAKPRESSURE.Name: Break Pressure

IfcTank.EXPANSION.Definition: A closed container used in a closed fluid distribution system to mitigate the effects of thermal expansion or water hammer. The tank is typically constructed with a diaphragm dividing the tank into two sections, with fluid on one side of the diaphragm and air on the other. One example application is when connected to the primary circuit of a hot water system to accommodate the increase in volume of the water when it is heated.
IfcTank.EXPANSION.Name: Expansion

ChargePressure.Name: Charge Pressure
ChargePressure.Definition: Nominal or design operating pressure of the tank.

PressureRegulatorSetting.Name: Pressure Regulator Setting
PressureRegulatorSetting.Definition: Pressure that is automatically maintained in the tank.

ReliefValveSetting.Name: Relief Valve Setting
ReliefValveSetting.Definition: Pressure at which the relief valve activates.

IfcTank.FEEDANDEXPANSION.Definition: An open tank that is used for both storage and thermal expansion. A typical example is a tank used to store make-up water at ambient pressure for supply to a hot water system, simultaneously accommodating increases in volume of the water when heated.
IfcTank.FEEDANDEXPANSION.Name: Feedand Expansion

IfcTank.OILRETENTIONTRAY.Definition: An open container for environmental protection and storage of chemical products.
IfcTank.OILRETENTIONTRAY.Name: Oil Retention Tray

IfcTank.PRESSUREVESSEL.Definition: A closed container used for storing fluids or gases at a pressure different from the ambient pressure. A pressure vessel is typically rated by an authority having jurisdiction for the operational pressure.
IfcTank.PRESSUREVESSEL.Name: Pressure Vessel

ChargePressure.Name: Charge Pressure

FlushRate.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
FlushRate.Name: Flush Rate
FlushRate.Definition: The minimum and maximum volume of water used at each flush. Where a single flush is used, the value of upper bound and lower bound should be equal. For a dual flush toilet, the lower bound should be used for the lesser flush rate and the upper bound for the greater flush rate. Where flush is achieved using mains pressure water through a flush valve, the value of upper and lower bound should be equal and should be the same as the flush rate property of the flush valve (see relevant valve property set). Alternatively, in this case, do not assert the flush rate property; refer to the flush rate of the flush valve.

Values.Description: The property enumeration Pset_FlushTypeEnum defines the types of flushing mechanism that may be specified for cisterns and sanitary terminals where:-Lever:  Flushing is achieved by twisting a lever that causes a predetermined flow of water to be passed from a cistern to the sanitary terminal
Pull:   Flushing is achieved by pulling a handle or knob vertically upwards that causes a predetermined flow of water to be passed from a cistern to the sanitary terminal

DrainSize.Name: Drain Size
DrainSize.Definition: The size of the drain outlet connection from the object.

Mounting.Name: Mounting
Mounting.Definition: The property enumeration Pset_SanitaryMountingEnum defines the forms of mounting or fixing of the sanitary terminal that may be specified within property sets used to define sanitary terminals (WCs, basins, sinks, etc.) where: -BackToWall: A pedestal mounted sanitary terminal that fits flush to the wall at the rear to cover its service connections; Pedestal: A floor mounted sanitary terminal that has an integral base; CounterTop: A sanitary terminal that is installed into a horizontal surface that is installed into a horizontal surface. Note: When applied to a wash hand basin, the term more normally used is vanity. See also Wash Hand Basin Type specification.; WallHung: A sanitary terminal cantilevered clear of the floor.Note that BackToWall, Pedestal and WallHung are allowable values for a bidet.

Values.Description: WallHung:   A sanitary terminal cantilevered clear of the floor

MountingOffset.Name: Mounting Offset
MountingOffset.Definition: For counter top mounted basins the vertical offset between the top of the sink and the counter top.

SinkType.Name: Sink Type
SinkType.Definition: Selection of the type of sink from the enumerated list of types where: -Belfast: Deep sink that has a plain edge and a weir overflow; .; Bucket: Sink at low level, with protected front edge, that facilitates filling and emptying buckets, usually with a hinged grid on which to stand them.; Cleaners: Sink, usually fixed at normal height (900mm), with protected front edge.; Combination_Left: Sink with integral drainer on left hand side; .; Combination_Right: Sink with integral drainer on right hand side; .; Combination_Double: Sink with integral drainer on both sides; .; Drip: Small sink that catches drips or flow from a faucet; .; Laboratory: Sink, of acid resisting material, with a top edge shaped to facilitate fixing to the underside of a desktop; .; London: Deep sink that has a plain edge and no overflow; .; Plaster: Sink with sediment receiver to prevent waste plaster passing into drains; .; Pot: Large metal sink, with a standing waste, for washing cooking utensils; .; Rinsing: Metal sink in which water can be heated and culinary utensils and tableware immersed at high temperature that destroys most harmful bacteria and allows subsequent self drying.; .; Shelf: Ceramic sink with an integral back shelf through which water fittings are mounted; .; VegetablePreparation: Large metal sink, with a standing waste, for washing and preparing vegetables; .

Values.Description: Selection of the type of sink from the enumerated list of types where:-Belfast:    Deep sink that has a plain edge and a weir overflow
Combination_Double:     Sink with integral drainer on both sides
Combination_Left:    Sink with integral drainer on left hand side
Combination_Right: Sink with integral drainer on right hand side
Drip: Small sink that catches drips or flow from a faucet
London: Deep sink that has a plain edge and no overflow
Plaster: Sink with sediment receiver to prevent waste plaster passing into drains
Rinsing: Metal sink in which water can be heated and culinary utensils and tableware immersed at high temperature that destroys most harmful bacteria and allows subsequent self drying
Shelf: Ceramic sink with an integral back shelf through which water fittings are mounted

ToiletPanType.Name: Toilet Pan Type
ToiletPanType.Definition: The property enumeration Pset_ToiletPanTypeEnum defines the types of toilet pan that may be specified within the property set Pset_Toilet: -Siphonic: Toilet pan in which excrement is removed by siphonage induced by the flushing water.; Squat: Toilet pan with an elongated bowl installed with its top edge at or near floor level, so that the user has to squat.; WashDown: Toilet pan in which excrement is removed by the momentum of the flushing water.; WashOut: A washdown toilet pan in which excrement falls first into a shallow water filled bowl.

ToiletType.Name: Toilet Type
ToiletType.Definition: Enumeration that defines the types of toilet (water closet) arrangements that may be specified where: -BedPanWasher: Enclosed soil appliance in which bedpans and urinal bottles are emptied and cleansed.; Chemical: Portable receptacle or soil appliance that receives and retains excrement in either an integral or a separate container, in which it is chemically treated and from which it has to be emptied periodically.; CloseCoupled: Toilet suite in which a flushing cistern is connected directly to the water closet pan.; LooseCoupled: Toilet arrangement in which a flushing cistern is connected to the water closet pan through a flushing pipe.; SlopHopper: Hopper shaped soil appliance with a flushing rim and outlet similar to those of a toilet pan, into which human excrement is emptied for disposal.

InletConnectionSize.Name: Inlet Connection Size
InletConnectionSize.Definition: Size of the inlet connection.; Note that all inlet connections are assumed to be the same size.

InletPatternType.Name: Inlet Pattern Type
InletPatternType.Definition: Identifies the pattern of inlet connections to a trap.A trap may have 0,1,2,3 or 4 inlet connections and the pattern of their arrangement may vary. The enumeration makes the convention that an outlet is either vertical or is placed at the bottom (south side) of the trap (when viewed in plan). Position 1 is to the left (west), position 2 is to the top (north), position 3 is to the right (east) and position 4 is to the bottom (south).

Values.Description: 3 or 4 inlet connections and the pattern of their arrangement may vary
3 or 4 inlet connections and the pattern of their arrangement may vary

IsForSullageWater.Name: Is for Sullage Water
IsForSullageWater.Definition: Indicates if the purpose of the floor trap is to receive sullage water, or if that is amongst its purposes (= TRUE), or not (= FALSE). Note that if TRUE, it is expected that an upstand or kerb will be placed around the floor trap to prevent the ingress of surface water runoff; the provision of the upstand or kerb is not dealt with in this property set.

Values.Description: or if that is amongst its purposes (= TRUE)

IfcConveyorSegment.BELTCONVEYOR.Name: Belt Conveyor

IfcConveyorSegment.BUCKETCONVEYOR.Definition: A conveyor in the form of connected buckets or segments that move in a continuous loop
IfcConveyorSegment.BUCKETCONVEYOR.Name: Bucket Conveyor

IfcConveyorSegment.CHUTECONVEYOR.Name: Chute Conveyor

IfcLiquidTerminal.HOSEREEL.Name: Hose Reel

IfcLiquidTerminal.LOADINGARM.Definition: A loading arm permits the transfer of liquid or liquefied gas from one system to another, through the use of an articulated arm that accounts for the movement of docked vessels.
IfcLiquidTerminal.LOADINGARM.Name: Loading Arm

IfcMarineFacility.BARRIERBEACH.Definition: a sand ridge that rises slightly above the surface of the sea and runs roughly parallel to the shore, from which it is separated by a lagoon.
IfcMarineFacility.BARRIERBEACH.Name: Barrier Beach

IfcMarineFacility.BREAKWATER.Definition: A longitudinal structure that protects a shore area, harbour, basin or estuary from waves.;
IfcMarineFacility.BREAKWATER.Name: Break Water

IfcMarineFacility.CANAL.Definition: A man-made watercourse constructed usually, to join rivers, lakes or seas and often of a size suitable for navigation.;
IfcMarineFacility.CANAL.Name: Canal

IfcMarineFacility.DRYDOCK.Definition: a Dry dock is an enclosed chamber (by gate) that allows the draining of water for the construction or repair of marine vessels.;
IfcMarineFacility.DRYDOCK.Name: Drydock

IfcMarineFacility.FLOATINGDOCK.Definition: A spatial element that encompasses a floating dry dock and supporting quay side ancillaries.
IfcMarineFacility.FLOATINGDOCK.Name: Floatingdock

IfcMarineFacility.HYDROLIFT.Definition: A type of vessel launch & recovery facility, also known as a hydraulic lift dock, where ships are lifted vertically by water impounding systems, then floated laterally across the land to berths which subsequently become dry.
IfcMarineFacility.HYDROLIFT.Name: Hydrolift

IfcMarineFacility.JETTY.Definition: A berthing structure, that extends out into the sea usually perpendicular to the coastline, primarily for the transfer of liquid bulk materials.;
IfcMarineFacility.JETTY.Name: Jetty

IfcMarineFacility.LAUNCHRECOVERY.Definition: Subset of facilities for the function of launching or recovering vessels.
IfcMarineFacility.LAUNCHRECOVERY.Name: Launchre Cover Y

IfcMarineFacility.MARINEDEFENCE.Definition: A subset of facilities with the primary function of protection or defence of a coastal or flood area.
IfcMarineFacility.MARINEDEFENCE.Name: Marine Defence

IfcMarineFacility.NAVIGATIONALCHANNEL.Definition: A natural navigable watercourse (such as a river) that needs to be managed or have improvements applied. This includes defined navigational areas in open seas and bays.;
IfcMarineFacility.NAVIGATIONALCHANNEL.Name: Navigational Channel

IfcMarineFacility.PORT.Definition: A complex/facility for shipping and marine activities, this includes cargo, people and storage of vessels (marinas & harbours).
IfcMarineFacility.PORT.Name: Port

IfcMarineFacility.QUAY.Definition: a facility for the mooring of vessels accompanied with the loading and unloading of cargo or passengers or the maintenance of vessels.
IfcMarineFacility.QUAY.Name: Quay

QuaySectionType.Name: Quay Section Type

IfcMarineFacility.REVETMENT.Definition: A marine defensive structure made from earthworks, masonry or activities, built in such a way as to absorb the energy of incoming water.
IfcMarineFacility.REVETMENT.Name: Revetment

IfcMarineFacility.SHIPLIFT.Definition: A type of vessel launch & recovery facility, where ships are lifted vertically out of the water on platforms connected to winches, then transferred horizontally to land based berths on rail, wheel or track systems.
IfcMarineFacility.SHIPLIFT.Name: Shiplift

IfcMarineFacility.SHIPLOCK.Definition: A facility used for raising and lowering boats, ships and other watercraft between stretches of water of different levels on rivers and canal waterways or between impounded basins. This is achieved via an impounded chamber of water which is filled and emptied.
IfcMarineFacility.SHIPLOCK.Name: Shiplock
