IfcSpace.EXTERNAL.Definition: A space outside of a facility.
IfcSpace.EXTERNAL.Name: External

IfcSpace.GFA.Definition: Gross Floor Area - a specific kind of space for each building story that includes all net area and construction area (also the external envelop). Provision of such a specific space is often required by regulations.
IfcSpace.GFA.Name: GFA

IfcSpace.PARKING.Definition: A space dedication for use as a parking spot for vehicles, including access, such as a parking aisle.
IfcSpace.PARKING.Name: Parking

IsAisle.Name: Is Aisle
IsAisle.Definition: Indicates that this parking zone is for accessing the parking units, i.e. an aisle (TRUE) and not a parking unit itself (FALSE)

Values.Description: an aisle (TRUE) and not a parking unit itself (FALSE)
an aisle (TRUE) and not a parking unit itself (FALSE)

IsOneWay.Name: Is One Way
IsOneWay.Definition: Indicates whether the parking aisle is designed for oneway traffic (TRUE) or twoway traffic (FALSE). Should only be provided if the property IsAisle is set to TRUE.

Values.Description: Indicates whether the parking aisle is designed for oneway traffic (TRUE) or twoway traffic (FALSE)
Indicates whether the parking aisle is designed for oneway traffic (TRUE) or twoway traffic (FALSE)

ParkingUnits.Name: Parking Units
ParkingUnits.Definition: Indicates the number of transportation units of the type specified by the property ParkingUse that may be accommodated within the space. Generally, this value should default to 1 unit. However, where the parking space is for motorcycles or bicycles, provision may be made for more than one unit in the space.

ParkingUse.Name: Parking Use
ParkingUse.Definition: Identifies the type of transportation for which the parking space is designed. Values are not predefined but might include car, compact car, motorcycle, bicycle, truck, bus etc.

IfcSpace.SPACE.Definition: Any space not falling into another category.
IfcSpace.SPACE.Name: Space

IfcSpatialZone.CONSTRUCTION.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a construction zone for the production process.
IfcSpatialZone.CONSTRUCTION.Name: Construction

IfcSpatialZone.FIRESAFETY.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a fire safety zone, or fire compartment.
IfcSpatialZone.FIRESAFETY.Name: Fire Safety

IfcSpatialZone.INTERFERENCE.Definition: The spatial zone is used to define an interference between IfcSpatialElement occurrences.
IfcSpatialZone.INTERFERENCE.Name: Interference

IfcSpatialZone.LIGHTING.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a lighting zone; a daylight zone, or an artificial lighting zone.
IfcSpatialZone.LIGHTING.Name: Light Ing

IfcSpatialZone.OCCUPANCY.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a zone of particular occupancy.
IfcSpatialZone.OCCUPANCY.Name: Occupancy

IfcSpatialZone.RESERVATION.Definition: A spatial zone that marks some sort of reservation within the project extent.
IfcSpatialZone.RESERVATION.Name: Reservation

IfcSpatialZone.SECURITY.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a zone for security planning and maintenance work.
IfcSpatialZone.SECURITY.Name: Security

IfcSpatialZone.THERMAL.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a thermal zone.
IfcSpatialZone.THERMAL.Name: Thermal

IfcSpatialZone.TRANSPORT.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent an area primarily dedicated to the movement of people or goods.
IfcSpatialZone.TRANSPORT.Name: Transport

IfcSpatialZone.VENTILATION.Definition: The spatial zone is used to represent a ventilation zone.
IfcSpatialZone.VENTILATION.Name: Ventilation

IfcTransportElement.CRANEWAY.Definition: A crane way system, normally including the crane rails, fasteners and the crane. It is primarily used to move heavy goods in a factory or other industry buildings.
IfcTransportElement.CRANEWAY.Name: Craneway

IfcTransportElement.ELEVATOR.Definition: Elevator or lift being a transport device to move people or goods vertically.
IfcTransportElement.ELEVATOR.Name: Elevator

ClearHeight.Name: Clear Height
ClearHeight.Definition: Clear height of the object (elevator).; The shape information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the shape properties, provided in the attached property, the geometric parameters take precedence.

FireFightingLift.Name: Fire Fighting Lift
FireFightingLift.Definition: Indication whether the elevator is designed to serve as a fire fighting lift the case of fire (TRUE) or not (FALSE). A fire fighting lift is used by fire fighters to access the location of fire and to evacuate people.

Values.Description: Indication whether the elevator is designed to serve as a fire fighting lift the case of fire (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether the elevator is designed to serve as a fire fighting lift the case of fire (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

IfcTransportElement.ESCALATOR.Definition: Escalator being a transport device to move people. It consists of individual linked steps that move up and down on tracks while keeping the threads horizontal.
IfcTransportElement.ESCALATOR.Name: Escalator

IfcTransportElement.HAULINGGEAR.Definition: A device used for hauling goods.
IfcTransportElement.HAULINGGEAR.Name: Hauling Gear

IfcTransportElement.LIFTINGGEAR.Definition: A device used for lifting or lowering heavy goods. It may be manually operated or electrically or pneumatically driven.
IfcTransportElement.LIFTINGGEAR.Name: Lifting Gear

IfcTransportElement.MOVINGWALKWAY.Definition: Moving walkway being a transport device to move people horizontally or on an incline. It is a slow conveyor belt that transports people.
IfcTransportElement.MOVINGWALKWAY.Name: Movingwalkway

IfcVehicle.CARGO.Definition: A mobile transport element that represents a discrete unit of cargo managed by a facility.
IfcVehicle.CARGO.Name: Cargo

AdditionalProcessing.Name: Additional Processing
AdditionalProcessing.Definition: Any additional or special processing requirements on the associated cargo.

ProcessDirection.Name: Process Direction
ProcessDirection.Definition: The direction of flow of the cargo within the process.

ProcessItem.Name: Process Item
ProcessItem.Definition: The type of item (and its measurement method) being modelled within a process. This can be cargo, passengers or vehicles that pass through the system.

Values.Description: passengers or vehicles that pass through the system
passengers or vehicles that pass through the system

IfcVehicle.ROLLINGSTOCK.Definition: Refers to railway vehicles, including both powered and unpowered vehicles, for example locomotives, railroad cars, coaches, private railroad cars and wagons.
IfcVehicle.ROLLINGSTOCK.Name: Rolling Stock

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcVehicle.VEHICLE.Definition: A generalisation of a vehicle that interacts with a facility (e.g. as a user/customer) or as a specified operational asset within the facility.
IfcVehicle.VEHICLE.Name: Vehicle

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcVehicle.VEHICLEAIR.Definition: A specialisation of a vehicle that represents powered and unpowered flying vehicles, such as airplanes, helicopters, gliders etc.
IfcVehicle.VEHICLEAIR.Name: Vehicle Air

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcVehicle.VEHICLEMARINE.Definition: A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on water as a marine vessel.
IfcVehicle.VEHICLEMARINE.Name: Vehicle Marine

AboveDeckProjectedWindEnd.Name: Above Deck Projected Wind End
AboveDeckProjectedWindEnd.Definition: End on projected windage area above the main deck

AboveDeckProjectedWindSide.Name: Above Deck Projected Wind Side
AboveDeckProjectedWindSide.Definition: Side on projected windage area above the main deck

Displacement.Name: Displacement
Displacement.Definition: Weight of water displaced by the vessel

LaneMeters.Name: Lane Meters
LaneMeters.Definition: Length of lanes accommodating vehicles on roll-on, roll-off vessels

LengthBetweenPerpendiculars.Name: Length Between Perpendiculars
LengthBetweenPerpendiculars.Definition: Length of vessel from rudder shaft to crossing point of the bow and the loaded waterline.

VesselDepth.Name: Vessel Depth
VesselDepth.Definition: Depth of the vessel from the main deck to the keel.

VesselDraft.Name: Vessel Draft
VesselDraft.Definition: Depth of vessel from the waterline to the keel (LightShip, Ballasted, Maximum)

AllowableHullPressure.Name: Allowable Hull Pressure
AllowableHullPressure.Definition: Allowable contact pressure between fender and hull

SoftnessCoefficient.Name: Softness Coefficient
SoftnessCoefficient.Definition: Vessel flexibility factor - proportion of impact energy absorbed by the hull.

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcVehicle.VEHICLETRACKED.Definition: A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on land tracked (Caterpillar).
IfcVehicle.VEHICLETRACKED.Name: Vehicle Tracked

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcVehicle.VEHICLEWHEELED.Definition: A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on land as a multi wheeled vehicle such as a car, lorry, forklift etc.
IfcVehicle.VEHICLEWHEELED.Name: Vehicle Wheel Ed

IfcVibrationDamper.AXIAL_YIELD.Definition: A displacement dependent type damper in which the resistance force generated is determined by the plastic strain amount utilizing the plastic deformation of the steel material. The axial yield type is a damper that yields energy by absorbing the steel material against deformation in the axial direction, that is, in the direction of expansion and contraction.
IfcVibrationDamper.AXIAL_YIELD.Name: Axial Yield

IfcVibrationDamper.BENDING_YIELD.Definition: A displacement dependent type damper in which the resistance force generated is determined by the plastic strain amount utilizing the plastic deformation of the steel material. The bending yield type is a damper, which yields steel material by bending.
IfcVibrationDamper.BENDING_YIELD.Name: Bending Yield

IfcVibrationDamper.FRICTION.Definition: The friction type is a damper utilizing friction acting on the contact surface of a material.
IfcVibrationDamper.FRICTION.Name: Friction

IfcVibrationDamper.RUBBER.Definition: The rubber mold is a damper that absorbs energy by utilizing deformation of laminated rubber. The difference between the seismic isolation bearing and the rubber type damper is whether or not to support the weight of the upper structures. The rubber damper does not transmit the weight of the upper structures to the sub structure.
IfcVibrationDamper.RUBBER.Name: Rubber

IfcVibrationDamper.SHEAR_YIELD.Definition: A displacement dependent type damper in which the resistance force generated is determined by the plastic strain amount utilizing the plastic deformation of the steel material. The shear yield type is a damper, which causes the steel material to yield for deformation in the direction perpendicular to the member.
IfcVibrationDamper.SHEAR_YIELD.Name: Shear Yield

IfcVibrationDamper.VISCOUS.Definition: The viscous type is a damper that absorbs energy by utilizing the resistance of a viscous body.
IfcVibrationDamper.VISCOUS.Name: Viscous

IfcVirtualElement.BOUNDARY.Definition: An imaginary boundary, such as between two adjacent spaces that are not separated by a physical boundary.
IfcVirtualElement.BOUNDARY.Name: Boundary

IfcVirtualElement.CLEARANCE.Definition: The virtual element denotes a clearance area or volume.
IfcVirtualElement.CLEARANCE.Name: Clearance

IfcVirtualElement.PROVISIONFORVOID.Definition: The virtual element denotes a proposed provision for voids (an proposed opening not applied as void yet).
IfcVirtualElement.PROVISIONFORVOID.Name: Provision for Void

System.Name: System
System.Definition: The building service system that requires the provision for voids, e.g. 'Air Conditioning', 'Plumbing', 'Electro', etc.

VoidShape.Name: Void Shape
VoidShape.Definition: The shape form of the provision for void, the minimum set of agreed values includes 'Rectangle', 'Round', and 'Undefined'.

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcRail.BLADE.Definition: A blade is a machined rail, often of special section, but fixed and/or joined at the heel end to a rail to provide continuity of wheel support. The two switch rails in a set are the two inside rails. A switch rail is described as right or left hand according to whether it is part of a right hand or left hand half-set of switches.; Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.
IfcRail.BLADE.Name: Blade

BladeRadius.Name: Blade Radius
BladeRadius.Definition: The radius of the blade bend defined as design parameter.

IsArticulatedBlade.Name: Is Articulated Blade
IsArticulatedBlade.Definition: Indicates whether the blade is articulated or not.

IsFallbackBlade.Name: Is Fallback Blade
IsFallbackBlade.Definition: Indicates whether the blade always returns to the same position as a trailable turnout or not.

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcRail.CHECKRAIL.Definition: A check rail is a rail laid close to the gauge face of a running rail which takes part in lateral guidance of the wheel and prevents derailment in small radius curved track and switches and crossings.; Note: definition from EN 13481-1.
IfcRail.CHECKRAIL.Name: Check Rail

CheckRailType.Name: Check Rail Type
CheckRailType.Definition: Type of the check rail. Check rail types enumerated in this property are defined based on EN 13674.

InstallationPlan.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InstallationPlan.Name: Installation Plan
InstallationPlan.Definition: Reference to external information source about installation or construction plan of the element.

IfcRail.GUARDRAIL.Definition: A guard rail is a rail that limits risk of train derailment, normally not loaded.
IfcRail.GUARDRAIL.Name: Guard Rail

GuardRailConnection.Name: Guard Rail Connection
GuardRailConnection.Definition: Indicates how the guard rail is connected along its length, when the fasteners are not explicitly modelled.

PositionInTrack.Name: Position In Track
PositionInTrack.Definition: Indicates the relative position of the element in track, which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values.

Values.Description: which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values
which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values

IfcRail.RACKRAIL.Definition: A rack rail is a building module for enhancing traction and break performance.
IfcRail.RACKRAIL.Name: Rack Rail

IfcRail.RAIL.Definition: A rail is a special section bar (usually of steel) ensuring the guidance of the wheel of a rolling stock or other heavy machineries. In railway, two rails are combined to form a track.
IfcRail.RAIL.Name: Rail

DrillOnRail.Name: Drill On Rail
DrillOnRail.Definition: Indicates if the manufactured rail is drilled at its extremities or not. It can have holes on one, both or none of its extremities.

Values.Description: both or none of its extremities

InstallationPlan.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InstallationPlan.Name: Installation Plan
InstallationPlan.Definition: Reference to external information source about installation or construction plan of the element.

IsStainless.Name: Is Stainless
IsStainless.Definition: Indicates whether the rail is stainless or not.

PositionInTrack.Name: Position In Track
PositionInTrack.Definition: Indicates the relative position of the element in track, which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values.

Values.Description: which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values
which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values

RailCondition.Name: Rail Condition
RailCondition.Definition: Assessment of the condition of the rail at point of installation.

RailDeliveryState.Name: Rail Delivery State
RailDeliveryState.Definition: The delivery state of rail, which indicates the final treatment at the end in manufacturing.

RailElementaryLength.Name: Rail Elementary Length
RailElementaryLength.Definition: The standardised length of rail supplied from the manufacturer.

TechnicalStandard.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TechnicalStandard.Name: Technical Standard
TechnicalStandard.Definition: The technical standard which the element should comply with.

IfcRail.STOCKRAIL.Definition: A stock rail is a fixed machined rail, ensuring the continuity on the main or diverging track with the switch in the open position. The machined part of the stock rail supports its switch rail in the closed position, giving continuity of line through this switch rail. The two stock rails in a set of switches are the two outside rails. A stock rail is described as right or left hand according to whether it is part of a right hand or left hand half-set of switches.; Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.
IfcRail.STOCKRAIL.Name: Stock Rail

InstallationPlan.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InstallationPlan.Name: Installation Plan
InstallationPlan.Definition: Reference to external information source about installation or construction plan of the element.

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

StockRailRadius.Name: Stock Rail Radius
StockRailRadius.Definition: The radius of the stock rail bend defined as design parameter.

IfcRailwayPart.ABOVETRACK.Definition: A spatial structure element that contains elements that are positioned above or over the track, for example catenary lines and suspension systems.
IfcRailwayPart.ABOVETRACK.Name: Abovetrack

HasBallastTrack.Name: Has Ballast Track
HasBallastTrack.Definition: Indicates whether the track has ballast or not.

HasCWR.Name: Has Cwr
HasCWR.Definition: Indicates if the track has continuous welded rails.

IsSunExposed.Name: Is Sun Exposed
IsSunExposed.Definition: Indicates if the object is in exposed position to sunshine.

TrackSupportingStructure.Name: Track Supporting Structure
TrackSupportingStructure.Definition: Indicates the supporting structure for track part.

IfcRailwayPart.LINESIDE.Definition: A spatial structure element that contains elements of the railway that are not in or over the tracks, hence line-side.
IfcRailwayPart.LINESIDE.Name: Line Side

IfcRailwayPart.LINESIDEPART.Definition: A spatial structure element to further divide a line-side part. It can be used to distinguish line-side parts into more manageable volumes, for engineering purposes.
IfcRailwayPart.LINESIDEPART.Name: Line Side Part

IfcRailwayPart.PLAINTRACK.Definition: A spatial structure element to further divide a track. It does do not contain any turnout panel or dilatation panel.
IfcRailwayPart.PLAINTRACK.Name: Plaintrack

HasBallastTrack.Name: Has Ballast Track
HasBallastTrack.Definition: Indicates whether the track has ballast or not.

HasCWR.Name: Has Cwr
HasCWR.Definition: Indicates if the track has continuous welded rails.

IsSunExposed.Name: Is Sun Exposed
IsSunExposed.Definition: Indicates if the object is in exposed position to sunshine.

TrackSupportingStructure.Name: Track Supporting Structure
TrackSupportingStructure.Definition: Indicates the supporting structure for track part.

IfcRailwayPart.SUBSTRUCTURE.Definition: A spatial structure element that contains elements that are positioned below the track, for example the earthwork platform, prepared subgrade and embankment. This can be above or below finished ground level.
IfcRailwayPart.SUBSTRUCTURE.Name: Sub Structure

IfcRailwayPart.TRACK.Definition: A spatial structure element that contains track-related elements, for example rails and sleepers.
IfcRailwayPart.TRACK.Name: Track

HasBallastTrack.Name: Has Ballast Track
HasBallastTrack.Definition: Indicates whether the track has ballast or not.

HasCWR.Name: Has Cwr
HasCWR.Definition: Indicates if the track has continuous welded rails.

IsSunExposed.Name: Is Sun Exposed
IsSunExposed.Definition: Indicates if the object is in exposed position to sunshine.

TrackSupportingStructure.Name: Track Supporting Structure
TrackSupportingStructure.Definition: Indicates the supporting structure for track part.

IfcRailwayPart.TRACKPART.Definition: A spatial structure element to further divide a track, for purposes that do not fall into these categories: plain-track, turnout-track, dilatation-track.
IfcRailwayPart.TRACKPART.Name: Trackpart

HasBallastTrack.Name: Has Ballast Track
HasBallastTrack.Definition: Indicates whether the track has ballast or not.

HasCWR.Name: Has Cwr
HasCWR.Definition: Indicates if the track has continuous welded rails.

IsSunExposed.Name: Is Sun Exposed
IsSunExposed.Definition: Indicates if the object is in exposed position to sunshine.

TrackSupportingStructure.Name: Track Supporting Structure
TrackSupportingStructure.Definition: Indicates the supporting structure for track part.

IfcRailwayPart.TURNOUTTRACK.Definition: A spatial structure element to further divide a track. It contains turnouts, and does not contain any plain track or dilatation panel.
IfcRailwayPart.TURNOUTTRACK.Name: Turnouttrack

HasBallastTrack.Name: Has Ballast Track
HasBallastTrack.Definition: Indicates whether the track has ballast or not.

HasCWR.Name: Has Cwr
HasCWR.Definition: Indicates if the track has continuous welded rails.

IsSunExposed.Name: Is Sun Exposed
IsSunExposed.Definition: Indicates if the object is in exposed position to sunshine.

TrackSupportingStructure.Name: Track Supporting Structure
TrackSupportingStructure.Definition: Indicates the supporting structure for track part.

IfcTrackElement.BLOCKINGDEVICE.Definition: A device composed of pneumatic, mechanic or electric components causing the braking of a train in case of emergency.
IfcTrackElement.BLOCKINGDEVICE.Name: Blocking Device

IfcTrackElement.DERAILER.Definition: A fixed device which, when placed on the rail, derails the wheels of a vehicle, and serves to protect a converging line.; Note: definition from IEC 60050-821.
IfcTrackElement.DERAILER.Name: Derailer

IsDerailing.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
IsDerailing.Name: Is Derailing
IsDerailing.Definition: Indicates whether the derailer is on or not.

AppliedLineLoad.Name: Applied Line Load
AppliedLineLoad.Definition: The load of line where the derailer is installed. It is a design parameter and is defined by mass per length.

DerailmentHeight.Name: Derailment Height
DerailmentHeight.Definition: Height of derailment block when derailer in protection state.

DerailmentMaximumSpeedLimit.Name: Derailment Maximum Speed Limit
DerailmentMaximumSpeedLimit.Definition: Indicates the maximum allowable train speed for the derailer.

DerailmentWheelDiameter.Name: Derailment Wheel Diameter
DerailmentWheelDiameter.Definition: Indicates the wheel diameter requirement for the derailer.

IfcTrackElement.FROG.Definition: A frog is an arrangement ensuring the intersection of two opposite running edges of turnouts or diamond crossings and having one crossing vee and two wing rails.; Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.
IfcTrackElement.FROG.Name: Frog

IfcTrackElement.HALF_SET_OF_BLADES.Definition: A half set of blades consists of one stock rail and its switch rail complete with small fittings. It is right or left hand as seen by an observer in the centre of the track facing the switch heel from the switch toe.; Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.
IfcTrackElement.HALF_SET_OF_BLADES.Name: Half Set of Blades

IfcTrackElement.SLEEPER.Definition: A sleeper is a track element that supports running rails, guard rails and check rails usually at right angles to its axis.
IfcTrackElement.SLEEPER.Name: Sleeper

HasSpecialEquipment.Name: Has Special Equipment
HasSpecialEquipment.Definition: Indicates whether the sleeper has any special equipment for fastening components (e.g. Balise, signum magnet) or not.

IsContaminatedSleeper.Name: Is Contaminated Sleeper
IsContaminatedSleeper.Definition: Indicates whether the sleeper is contaminated and requires special disposal or not.

SequenceInTrackPanel.Name: Sequence In Track Panel
SequenceInTrackPanel.Definition: Sequence of the sleeper within the track panel.

UnderSleeperPadStiffness.Name: Under Sleeper Pad Stiffness
UnderSleeperPadStiffness.Definition: Indicates the stiffness of the under-sleeper pad as design reference for the sleeper.

Values.Description: Indicates the stiffness of the under-sleeper pad as design reference for the sleeper

FasteningType.Name: Fastening Type
FasteningType.Definition: Indicates the type of fastening used to generate traction between the foot of the rail and the sleeper. It depends on but is not uniquely identified by the type of sleeper. This property shall only be used when sleeper fastening is not modelled as an element.

HollowSleeperUsage.Name: Hollow Sleeper Usage
HollowSleeperUsage.Definition: Indicates the purpose of using hollow sleeper. The possible value can be eg. cable trenching, protection of turnout mechanism, etc.

InstalledCondition.Name: Installed Condition
InstalledCondition.Definition: Assessment of the condition of the element at point of installation.

IsElectricallyInsulated.Name: Is Electrically Insulated
IsElectricallyInsulated.Definition: Indicates whether the sleeper is electrically insulated due to its design or the running rails or not.

IsHollowSleeper.Name: Is Hollow Sleeper
IsHollowSleeper.Definition: Indicates whether the sleeper is hollowed or not.

NumberOfTrackCenters.Name: Number of Track Centers
NumberOfTrackCenters.Definition: Indicates the number of track centers running over the sleepers.

TechnicalStandard.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TechnicalStandard.Name: Technical Standard
TechnicalStandard.Definition: The technical standard which the element should comply with.

Width.Name: Width
Width.Definition: The width of the object. Only given, if the object has constant thickness (prismatic).

IfcTrackElement.SPEEDREGULATOR.Definition: A device composed of pneumatic, mechanic or electric components causing the breaking of a train in case of emergency.
IfcTrackElement.SPEEDREGULATOR.Name: Speed Regulator

IfcTrackElement.TRACKENDOFALIGNMENT.Definition: A track end of alignment is a special functional installation such as axle-gauge changeover point or transporter wagon loading point.
IfcTrackElement.TRACKENDOFALIGNMENT.Name: Track End of Alignment

IfcTrackElement.VEHICLESTOP.Definition: A fixed installation at the end of the track which stops any vehicle movement (e.g., buffer stop, sand hump, etc.).
IfcTrackElement.VEHICLESTOP.Name: Vehicle Stop

IfcRoadPart.BICYCLECROSSING.Definition: Designated level crossing over a road for cyclists.
IfcRoadPart.BICYCLECROSSING.Name: Bicycle Crossing

Crossfall.Name: Crossfall
Crossfall.Definition: Specifies the nominal crossfall as a ratio measure (slope) at the location of the event.

DesignSpeed.Name: Design Speed
DesignSpeed.Definition: Speed selected in designing a new road or in modernizing, strengthening or rehabilitating an existing road section, to determine the various geometric design features of the carriageway that allow a car to travel safely at that speed, under normal road surface and weather conditions.

DesignTrafficVolume.Name: Design Traffic Volume
DesignTrafficVolume.Definition: The traffic volume used for planning and design purposes specified as the number of vehicles per day . Typically given as AADT - Average Annual Daily Traffic

DesignVehicleClass.Name: Design Vehicle Class
DesignVehicleClass.Definition: A vehicle designator with content according to local standards.

LaneWidth.Name: Lane Width
LaneWidth.Definition: Standard nominal width of one trough lane.

NumberOfThroughLanes.Name: Number of Through Lanes
NumberOfThroughLanes.Definition: The total number of through lanes on the segment. This excludes auxiliary lanes, parking and turning lanes, acceleration/deceleration lanes, toll collection lanes, shoulders etc.

RoadDesignClass.Name: Road Design Class
RoadDesignClass.Definition: A road design class designator with content according to local standards.

IfcRoadPart.BUS_STOP.Definition: Lateral part of Road for stopping buses allowing them to draw out of the traffic lanes and wait for short periods.
IfcRoadPart.BUS_STOP.Name: Bus Stop

IfcRoadPart.CARRIAGEWAY.Definition: Unitary lateral part of Road built for traffic. Carriageway may comprise several kinds of traffic lanes and lay-bys, as well as traffic islands, and in case of dual carriageway road they are separated by central reserve.
IfcRoadPart.CARRIAGEWAY.Name: Carriageway

IfcRoadPart.CENTRALISLAND.Definition: The center of a roundabout not intended for traffic, can be painted or upraised.
IfcRoadPart.CENTRALISLAND.Name: Central Island

IfcRoadPart.CENTRALRESERVE.Definition: Lateral RoadPart separating two carriageways of the same road or separating traffic lanes and sidewalk.
IfcRoadPart.CENTRALRESERVE.Name: Centralreserve

IfcRoadPart.HARDSHOULDER.Definition: A type of Shoulder that is surfaced, providing for safe use by vehicles in distress.
IfcRoadPart.HARDSHOULDER.Name: Hardshoulder

IfcRoadPart.INTERSECTION.Definition: At-grade junction where two or more roads meet or cross. Intersections may be further classified by number of road segments, traffic controls, and/or lane design.
IfcRoadPart.INTERSECTION.Name: Inter Section

Crossfall.Name: Crossfall
Crossfall.Definition: Specifies the nominal crossfall as a ratio measure (slope) at the location of the event.

DesignSpeed.Name: Design Speed
DesignSpeed.Definition: Speed selected in designing a new road or in modernizing, strengthening or rehabilitating an existing road section, to determine the various geometric design features of the carriageway that allow a car to travel safely at that speed, under normal road surface and weather conditions.

DesignTrafficVolume.Name: Design Traffic Volume
DesignTrafficVolume.Definition: The traffic volume used for planning and design purposes specified as the number of vehicles per day . Typically given as AADT - Average Annual Daily Traffic

DesignVehicleClass.Name: Design Vehicle Class
DesignVehicleClass.Definition: A vehicle designator with content according to local standards.

LaneWidth.Name: Lane Width
LaneWidth.Definition: Standard nominal width of one trough lane.

NumberOfThroughLanes.Name: Number of Through Lanes
NumberOfThroughLanes.Definition: The total number of through lanes on the segment. This excludes auxiliary lanes, parking and turning lanes, acceleration/deceleration lanes, toll collection lanes, shoulders etc.

RoadDesignClass.Name: Road Design Class
RoadDesignClass.Definition: A road design class designator with content according to local standards.

IfcRoadPart.LAYBY.Definition: A lateral part of Road where vehicles can divert from ordinary stream of traffic.
IfcRoadPart.LAYBY.Name: Layby

IfcRoadPart.PARKINGBAY.Definition: Lateral part of Road for parking vehicles.
IfcRoadPart.PARKINGBAY.Name: Parkingbay

IfcRoadPart.PASSINGBAY.Definition: A lateral part of Road that is a widening of an otherwise single lane road where a vehicle may move over to enable another vehicle to pass.
IfcRoadPart.PASSINGBAY.Name: Passingbay

IfcRoadPart.PEDESTRIAN_CROSSING.Definition: Designated level crossing over a road for pedestrians.
IfcRoadPart.PEDESTRIAN_CROSSING.Name: Pedestrian Crossing

Crossfall.Name: Crossfall
Crossfall.Definition: Specifies the nominal crossfall as a ratio measure (slope) at the location of the event.

DesignSpeed.Name: Design Speed
DesignSpeed.Definition: Speed selected in designing a new road or in modernizing, strengthening or rehabilitating an existing road section, to determine the various geometric design features of the carriageway that allow a car to travel safely at that speed, under normal road surface and weather conditions.

DesignTrafficVolume.Name: Design Traffic Volume

IfcRoadPart.REFUGEISLAND.Definition: A raised platform or a guarded area so sited in the carriageway as to divide the streams of traffic and to provide a safety area for pedestrians.
IfcRoadPart.REFUGEISLAND.Name: Refuge Island

IfcRoadPart.ROADSEGMENT.Definition: Longitudinal, linear segment of a road, either defined by uniform characteristics, or as a transition segment (e.g. number of lanes changing).
IfcRoadPart.ROADSEGMENT.Name: Road Segment

IfcRoadPart.ROADSIDE.Definition: A lateral RoadPart located along the Road adjoining the outer edges of the Shoulders. A general concept comprising the areas outside RoadwayPlateau not intended for vehicles.
IfcRoadPart.ROADSIDE.Name: Road Side

IfcRoadPart.ROADSIDEPART.Definition: A general concept for various parts of the Roadside.
IfcRoadPart.ROADSIDEPART.Name: Road Side Part

IfcRoadPart.ROADWAYPLATEAU.Definition: Lateral part of Road comprising the carriageway(s), shoulders and medians.
IfcRoadPart.ROADWAYPLATEAU.Name: Roadway Plateau

IfcRoadPart.ROUNDABOUT.Definition: Type of at-grade junction at which traffic streams are directed around a circle.
IfcRoadPart.ROUNDABOUT.Name: Roundabout

RoadDesignClass.Name: Road Design Class
RoadDesignClass.Definition: A road design class designator with content according to local standards.

IfcRoadPart.SHOULDER.Definition: A lateral part of Road adjacent to, and usually at the same level as the Carriageway; not intended for vehicular traffic but may be used in case of emergency.
IfcRoadPart.SHOULDER.Name: Shoulder

IfcRoadPart.SIDEWALK.Definition: A footpath along the side of a road. May accommodate moderate changes in grade (elevation) and is normally separated from the vehicular section by a kerb. There may be a central reserve or road verge between the sidewalk and traffic lanes.
IfcRoadPart.SIDEWALK.Name: Side Walk

IfcRoadPart.SOFTSHOULDER.Definition: A type of Shoulder that is not surfaced.
IfcRoadPart.SOFTSHOULDER.Name: Soft Shoulder

IfcRoadPart.TOLLPLAZA.Definition: A part of road facility where tolls are collected for use of toll road, tunnel or bridge.
IfcRoadPart.TOLLPLAZA.Name: Toll Plaza

Crossfall.Name: Crossfall

RoadDesignClass.Name: Road Design Class
RoadDesignClass.Definition: A road design class designator with content according to local standards.

IfcRoadPart.TRAFFICISLAND.Definition: A central or subsidiary area raised or marked on the carriageway, generally at a road junction or level crossing, shaped and placed so as to direct traffic movement and/or provide refuge for pedestrians.
IfcRoadPart.TRAFFICISLAND.Name: Traffic Island

IfcRoadPart.TRAFFICLANE.Definition: Lateral part of carriageway designated to vehicular traffic for a particular purpose.
IfcRoadPart.TRAFFICLANE.Name: Traffic Lane

IfcBeam.BEAM.Definition: A standard beam usually used horizontally.
IfcBeam.BEAM.Name: Beam

IfcBeam.CORNICE.Definition: A non-loadbearing beam on the longitudinal edge of bridge slab, usually encasing installations.
IfcBeam.CORNICE.Name: Cornice

IfcBeam.DIAPHRAGM.Definition: End portion of a girder transmitting loads to supports and providing moment resistance to adjoining segment.
IfcBeam.DIAPHRAGM.Name: Diaphragm

IfcBeam.EDGEBEAM.Definition: A beam on the longitudinal edge of bridge slab, usually concrete, providing additional stiffening and protection from the elements.
IfcBeam.EDGEBEAM.Name: Edgebeam

IfcBeam.GIRDER_SEGMENT.Definition: A segment of a girder (e.g. each span of a continuous girder).
IfcBeam.GIRDER_SEGMENT.Name: Girder Segment

IfcBeam.HATSTONE.Definition: A beam on top of a retaining wall or a wing wall, preventing earth movement.
IfcBeam.HATSTONE.Name: Hatstone

IfcBeam.HOLLOWCORE.Definition: A wide often prestressed beam with a hollow-core profile that usually serves as a slab component.
IfcBeam.HOLLOWCORE.Name: Hollowcore

IfcBeam.JOIST.Definition: A beam used to support a floor or ceiling.
IfcBeam.JOIST.Name: Joist

IfcBeam.LINTEL.Definition: A beam or horizontal piece of material over an opening (e.g. door, window).
IfcBeam.LINTEL.Name: Lintel

IfcBeam.PIERCAP.Definition: A transversal beam on top of a pier (on a single column or extending from one column of a pier to another column of the same pier).
IfcBeam.PIERCAP.Name: Pier Cap

IfcBeam.SPANDREL.Definition: A tall beam placed on the facade of a building. One tall side is usually finished to provide the exterior of the building. Can be used to support joists or slab elements on its interior side.
IfcBeam.SPANDREL.Name: Spandrel

IfcBeam.T_BEAM.Definition: A beam that forms part of a slab construction and acts together with the slab which it carries. Such beams are often of T-shape (therefore the English name), but may have other shapes as well, e.g. an L-Shape or an Inverted-T-Shape.
IfcBeam.T_BEAM.Name: T Beam

IfcBearing.CYLINDRICAL.Definition: The bearing functionality is provided by cylinder in a concave cylinder.
IfcBearing.CYLINDRICAL.Name: Cylindrical

IfcBearing.DISK.Definition: A disk bearing consist of an elastomeric disc between two metal plates.
IfcBearing.DISK.Name: Disk

IfcBearing.ELASTOMERIC.Definition: A pad bearing which carries vertical load by contact stresses between a sheet of sliding material and a mating surface that permits movements by sliding and accommodates rotation by deformation of the elastomer.
IfcBearing.ELASTOMERIC.Name: Elastomeric

IfcBearing.GUIDE.Definition: A bearing that ensures that the structure maintains the correct location or expansion/contraction path and takes no vertical load. Includes also restraint bearings.
IfcBearing.GUIDE.Name: Guide

IfcBearing.POT.Definition: A bearing which carries vertical load by compression of an (elastomeric) disc confined in a (steel) cylinder and which accommodates rotations by deformations of the disc.
IfcBearing.POT.Name: Pot

IfcBearing.ROCKER.Definition: The bearing functionality is provided by a rocker construction. Includes line rocker and point rocker bearings.
IfcBearing.ROCKER.Name: Rocker

IfcBearing.ROLLER.Definition: The bearing functionality is provided by one or more rollers that are placed between two plates.
IfcBearing.ROLLER.Name: Roller

IfcBearing.SPHERICAL.Definition: The bearing functionality is provided by convex dome in a concave basin.
IfcBearing.SPHERICAL.Name: Spherical

IfcColumn.COLUMN.Definition: A usually vertical member that may be load bearing and requiring resistance to vertical forces by compression but also sometimes to lateral forces.
IfcColumn.COLUMN.Name: Column

IfcColumn.PIERSTEM.Definition: An individual vertical part of a pier, may be a simple column, i.e. no breakdown into segments or separate structural parts such as flanges and web(s), or may be an aggregation of segments and/or parts.
IfcColumn.PIERSTEM.Name: Pier Stem

IfcColumn.PIERSTEM_SEGMENT.Definition: A vertical segment of a pier column.
IfcColumn.PIERSTEM_SEGMENT.Name: Pier Stem Segment

IfcColumn.PILASTER.Definition: A column element embedded within a wall that can be required to be load bearing but may also only be used for decorative purposes.
IfcColumn.PILASTER.Name: Pilaster

IfcColumn.STANDCOLUMN.Definition: A column transmitting vertical loads from a superstructure to an arch below it.
IfcColumn.STANDCOLUMN.Name: Stand Column

IfcCovering.CEILING.Definition: The covering is used to represent a ceiling.
IfcCovering.CEILING.Name: Ceiling

IfcCovering.CLADDING.Definition: The covering is used to represent a cladding.
IfcCovering.CLADDING.Name: Cladding

IfcCovering.COPING.Definition: A protective capping or covering of a wall or a parapet.
IfcCovering.COPING.Name: Coping

IfcCovering.FLOORING.Definition: The covering is used to represent a flooring.
IfcCovering.FLOORING.Name: Flooring

HasAntiStaticSurface.Name: Has Anti Static Surface
HasAntiStaticSurface.Definition: Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent electrostatic charge (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent electrostatic charge (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent electrostatic charge (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

HasNonSkidSurface.Name: Has Non Skid Surface
HasNonSkidSurface.Definition: Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent slippery (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent slippery (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indication whether the surface finish is designed to prevent slippery (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

IfcCovering.INSULATION.Definition: The covering is used to insulate an element for thermal or acoustic purposes.
IfcCovering.INSULATION.Name: Insulation

IfcCovering.MEMBRANE.Definition: An impervious layer that could be used for e.g. roof covering (below tiling - that may be known as sarking etc.) or as a damp proof course membrane; also, waterproofing material on a bridge structure (typically on top of bridge slab).
IfcCovering.MEMBRANE.Name: Membrane

NominalTransverseInclination.Name: Nominal Transverse Inclination
NominalTransverseInclination.Definition: Required nominal angle of transverse slope.

IfcCovering.MOLDING.Definition: The covering is used to represent a molding being a strip of material to cover the transition of surfaces (often between wall cladding and ceiling).
IfcCovering.MOLDING.Name: Molding

IfcCovering.ROOFING.Definition: The covering is used to represent a roof covering.
IfcCovering.ROOFING.Name: Roof Ing

IfcCovering.SKIRTINGBOARD.Definition: The covering is used to represent a skirting board being a strip of material to cover the transition between the wall cladding and the flooring.
IfcCovering.SKIRTINGBOARD.Name: Skirting Board

IfcCovering.SLEEVING.Definition: The covering is used to isolate a distribution element from a space in which it is contained.
IfcCovering.SLEEVING.Name: Sleeving

IfcCovering.TOPPING.Definition: A layer of material used for leveling or flattening a surface.
IfcCovering.TOPPING.Name: Topping

IfcCovering.WRAPPING.Definition: The covering is used for wrapping particularly of distribution elements using tape.
IfcCovering.WRAPPING.Name: Wrapping

IfcDoor.BOOM_BARRIER.Definition: A boom barrier (also known as a boom gate) is a bar, or pole pivoted to allow the boom to block vehicular or pedestrian access through a controlled point.
IfcDoor.BOOM_BARRIER.Name: Boom Barrier

TicketProcessingTime.Name: Ticket Processing Time
TicketProcessingTime.Definition: Indicates the processing time of a ticket.

TicketStuckRatio.Name: Ticket Stuck Ratio
TicketStuckRatio.Definition: Indicates the ratio of tickets being stuck or jammed in the appliance.

IfcDoor.DOOR.Definition: A standard door usually within a wall opening, as a door panel in a curtain wall, or as a "free standing" door.
IfcDoor.DOOR.Name: Door

IfcDoor.GATE.Definition: A gate is a point of entry into a space usually within an opening in a fence. Or as a "free standing" gate.
IfcDoor.GATE.Name: Gate

IfcDoor.TRAPDOOR.Definition: A special door that lies horizonally in a slab opening. Often used for accessing cellar or attic.
IfcDoor.TRAPDOOR.Name: Trapdoor

IfcDoor.TURNSTILE.Definition: A mechanical gate consisting of revolving arms, allowing only one person at a time to pass through.
IfcDoor.TURNSTILE.Name: Turnstile

IsBidirectional.Name: Is Bidirectional
IsBidirectional.Definition: Indicates whether the turnstile is bidirectional.

NarrowChannelWidth.Name: Narrow Channel Width
NarrowChannelWidth.Definition: Indicates the width of the narrow channel.

TurnstileType.Name: Turnstile Type
TurnstileType.Definition: Indicates the type of turnstile gate.

WideChannelWidth.Name: Wide Channel Width
WideChannelWidth.Definition: Indicates the width of the wide channel.

TicketProcessingTime.Name: Ticket Processing Time
TicketProcessingTime.Definition: Indicates the processing time of a ticket.

TicketStuckRatio.Name: Ticket Stuck Ratio
TicketStuckRatio.Definition: Indicates the ratio of tickets being stuck or jammed in the appliance.

IfcMember.ARCH_SEGMENT.Definition: Individual segment of an arch structure.
IfcMember.ARCH_SEGMENT.Name: Arch Segment

IfcMember.BRACE.Definition: A linear element (usually sloped) often used for bracing of a girder or truss.
IfcMember.BRACE.Name: Brace

HasLightningRod.Name: Has Lightning Rod
HasLightningRod.Definition: Indicates whether the element is equipped with a lightning rod (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the element is equipped with a lightning rod (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indicates whether the element is equipped with a lightning rod (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

MechanicalStressType.Name: Mechanical Stress Type
MechanicalStressType.Definition: Indicates which type of stress is applied to the element.

IfcMember.CHORD.Definition: Upper or lower longitudinal member of a truss, used horizontally or sloped.
IfcMember.CHORD.Name: Chord

IfcMember.COLLAR.Definition: A linear element (usually used horizontally) within a roof structure to connect rafters and posts.
IfcMember.COLLAR.Name: Collar

IfcMember.MEMBER.Definition: A linear element within a girder or truss with no further meaning.
IfcMember.MEMBER.Name: Member

AssemblyInstruction.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AssemblyInstruction.Name: Assembly Instruction
AssemblyInstruction.Definition: Instructions to describe how the system / equipment / facility is assembled.

ContactWireStagger.Name: Contact Wire Stagger
ContactWireStagger.Definition: Lateral displacement of the contact wire to opposite sides of the track centre at successive supports.

IfcMember.MULLION.Definition: A linear element within a curtain wall system to connect two (or more) panels.
IfcMember.MULLION.Name: Mullion

IfcMember.PLATE.Definition: A linear continuous horizontal element in wall framing, such as a head piece or a sole plate.
IfcMember.PLATE.Name: Plate

IfcMember.POST.Definition: A linear (usually vertical) member used to support something or to mark a point.
IfcMember.POST.Name: Post

ConicityRatio.Name: Conicity Ratio
ConicityRatio.Definition: The ratio of the diameter of the cone bottom surface to the height of the pole.

LoadBearingCapacity.Name: Load Bearing Capacity
LoadBearingCapacity.Definition: Maximum load bearing capacity of the floor structure throughtout the storey as designed.

NominalHeight.Name: Nominal Height
NominalHeight.Definition: The nominal height of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

WindLoadRating.Name: Wind Load Rating
WindLoadRating.Definition: Wind load resistance rating for this object.; It is provided according to the national building code.

IfcMember.PURLIN.Definition: A linear element (usually used horizontally) within a roof structure to support rafters.
IfcMember.PURLIN.Name: Purlin

IfcMember.RAFTER.Definition: A linear elements used to support roof slabs or roof covering, usually used with slope.
IfcMember.RAFTER.Name: Rafter

IfcMember.STAY_CABLE.Definition: A sloped element suspending a structure (such as bridge deck) from a pylon.
IfcMember.STAY_CABLE.Name: Stay Cable

AssemblyInstruction.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AssemblyInstruction.Name: Assembly Instruction
AssemblyInstruction.Definition: Instructions to describe how the system / equipment / facility is assembled.

CatenaryStayType.Name: Catenary Stay Type
CatenaryStayType.Definition: Indicates the type of catenary stay used.

NominalHeight.Name: Nominal Height
NominalHeight.Definition: The nominal height of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcMember.STIFFENING_RIB.Definition: A linear element added to a flange or a web plate of a girder for local stiffening.
IfcMember.STIFFENING_RIB.Name: Stiffening Rib

IfcMember.STRINGER.Definition: A linear element used to support stair or ramp flights, usually used with slope.
IfcMember.STRINGER.Name: Stringer

IfcMember.STRUCTURALCABLE.Definition: A linear cable element used to secure or stabilise a structure by resisting lateral and longitudinal loading through tension only, but cannot resist compression. usually formed of a flexible cable or wire.
IfcMember.STRUCTURALCABLE.Name: Structural Cable

IfcMember.STRUT.Definition: A linear element often used within a girder or truss.
IfcMember.STRUT.Name: Strut

IfcMember.SUSPENDER.Definition: A vertical element suspending a structure (such as bridge deck) from a suspension cable or an arch.
IfcMember.SUSPENDER.Name: Suspender

IfcMember.SUSPENSION_CABLE.Definition: A suspended element, typically comprising steel wire, sheath, etc.
IfcMember.SUSPENSION_CABLE.Name: Suspension Cable

IfcMember.TIEBAR.Definition: A linear bar element used to secure or stabilise a structure by resisting lateral and longitudinal loading through tension and or compression. usually formed by a solid bar.
IfcMember.TIEBAR.Name: Tiebar

IsTemporaryInstallation.Name: Is Temporary Installation
IsTemporaryInstallation.Definition: Indicates whether the installation (in the construction stage) is permanent (TRUE) or temporary (FALSE)

Values.Description: Indicates whether the installation (in the construction stage) is permanent (TRUE) or temporary (FALSE)
Indicates whether the installation (in the construction stage) is permanent (TRUE) or temporary (FALSE)

IfcPlate.BASE_PLATE.Definition: A plate used to spread load over a surface, such as underneath a bearing or column.
IfcPlate.BASE_PLATE.Name: Base Plate

IfcPlate.COVER_PLATE.Definition: A plate (underneath or above) a flange to provide additional load capacity.
IfcPlate.COVER_PLATE.Name: Cover Plate

IfcPlate.CURTAIN_PANEL.Definition: A planar element within a curtain wall, often consisting of a frame with fixed glazing.
IfcPlate.CURTAIN_PANEL.Name: Curtain Panel

IfcPlate.FLANGE_PLATE.Definition: A flange plate in linear members having box or I-profile (e.g. top or bottom flange plate in box-girder).
IfcPlate.FLANGE_PLATE.Name: Flange Plate

IfcPlate.GUSSET_PLATE.Definition: a plate or bracket for strengthening an angle in framework (as in a building or bridge).
IfcPlate.GUSSET_PLATE.Name: Gusset Plate

IfcPlate.SHEET.Definition: A planar, flat and thin element, comes usually as metal sheet, and is often used as an additional part within an assembly.
IfcPlate.SHEET.Name: Sheet

IfcPlate.SPLICE_PLATE.Definition: A plate connecting two members joined at ends.
IfcPlate.SPLICE_PLATE.Name: Splice Plate

IfcPlate.STIFFENER_PLATE.Definition: A transversal plate added to a flange or a web plate for local stiffening.
IfcPlate.STIFFENER_PLATE.Name: Stiffener Plate

IfcPlate.WEB_PLATE.Definition: A plate connecting flange plates in linear members having box or I-profile.
IfcPlate.WEB_PLATE.Name: Web Plate

IfcRailing.BALUSTRADE.Definition: Guardrail located at the edge of a floor, rather then a stair or ramp. Examples are balustrades at roof-tops or balconies, or along a bridge or on top of a retaining wall.
IfcRailing.BALUSTRADE.Name: Balustrade

IfcRailing.GUARDRAIL.Definition: A type of railing designed to guard human or vehicle occupants from falling off a stair, ramp or landing where there is a vertical drop at the edge of such floors/landings, or to provide restraint to an errant road vehicle, installed on the central reserve of or alongside a road.
IfcRailing.GUARDRAIL.Name: Guard Rail

IsTerminal.Name: Is Terminal
IsTerminal.Definition: True if element is a terminal. See class Terminal.

Values.Description: True if element is a terminal

IsTransition.Name: Is Transition
IsTransition.Definition: True if element is a transition. See class Transition.

Values.Description: True if element is a transition

TerminalType.Name: Terminal Type
TerminalType.Definition: Specifies the kind of terminal if IsTerminal is true.

IfcRailing.HANDRAIL.Definition: A type of railing designed to serve as an optional structural support for loads applied by human occupants (at hand height). Generally located adjacent to ramps and stairs. Generally floor or wall mounted.
IfcRailing.HANDRAIL.Name: Hand Rail

IfcRamp.HALF_TURN_RAMP.Definition: A ramp making a 180 turn, consisting of two straight flights connected; by a halfspace landing. The orientation of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcRamp.HALF_TURN_RAMP.Name: Half Turn Ramp

IfcRamp.QUARTER_TURN_RAMP.Definition: A ramp making a 90 turn, consisting of two straight flights connected by; a quarterspace landing. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcRamp.QUARTER_TURN_RAMP.Name: Quarter Turn Ramp

IfcRamp.SPIRAL_RAMP.Definition: A ramp constructed around a circular or elliptical well without newels and; landings.
IfcRamp.SPIRAL_RAMP.Name: Spiral Ramp

IfcRamp.STRAIGHT_RUN_RAMP.Definition: A ramp - which is a sloping floor, walk, or roadway - connecting two levels.; The straight ramp consists of one straight flight without turns or winders.
IfcRamp.STRAIGHT_RUN_RAMP.Name: Straight Run Ramp

IfcRamp.TWO_QUARTER_TURN_RAMP.Definition: A ramp making a 180 turn, consisting of three straight flights connected; by two quarterspace landings. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcRamp.TWO_QUARTER_TURN_RAMP.Name: Two Quarter Turn Ramp

IfcRamp.TWO_STRAIGHT_RUN_RAMP.Definition: A straight ramp consisting of two straight flights without turns but with one; landing.
IfcRamp.TWO_STRAIGHT_RUN_RAMP.Name: Two Straight Run Ramp

IfcRampFlight.SPIRAL.Definition: A ramp flight with a circular or elliptic walking line.
IfcRampFlight.SPIRAL.Name: Spiral

IfcRampFlight.STRAIGHT.Definition: A ramp flight with a straight walking line.
IfcRampFlight.STRAIGHT.Name: Straight

IfcRoof.BARREL_ROOF.Definition: A roof or ceiling having a semicylindrical form.
IfcRoof.BARREL_ROOF.Name: Barrel Roof

IfcRoof.BUTTERFLY_ROOF.Definition: A roof having two slopes, each descending inward from the eaves.
IfcRoof.BUTTERFLY_ROOF.Name: Butterfly Roof

IfcRoof.FLAT_ROOF.Definition: A roof having no slope, or one with only a slight pitch so as to drain; rainwater.
IfcRoof.FLAT_ROOF.Name: Flat Roof

IfcRoof.GABLE_ROOF.Definition: A roof sloping downward in two parts from a central ridge, so as to form a; gable at each end.
IfcRoof.GABLE_ROOF.Name: Gable Roof

IfcRoof.GAMBREL_ROOF.Definition: A roof sloping downward in two parts from a central ridge, so as to form a; gable at each end.
IfcRoof.GAMBREL_ROOF.Name: Gambrel Roof

IfcRoof.HIPPED_GABLE_ROOF.Definition: A roof having a hipped end truncating a gable.
IfcRoof.HIPPED_GABLE_ROOF.Name: Hipped Gable Roof

IfcRoof.HIP_ROOF.Definition: A roof having sloping ends and sides meeting at an inclined projecting; angle.
IfcRoof.HIP_ROOF.Name: Hip Roof

IfcRoof.MANSARD_ROOF.Definition: A roof having on each side a steeper lower part and a shallower upper; part.
IfcRoof.MANSARD_ROOF.Name: Mansard Roof

IfcRoof.RAINBOW_ROOF.Definition: A gable roof in the form of a broad Gothic arch, with gently sloping convex; surfaces.
IfcRoof.RAINBOW_ROOF.Name: Rainbow Roof

IfcRoof.SHED_ROOF.Definition: A roof having a single slope.
IfcRoof.SHED_ROOF.Name: Shed Roof

IfcShadingDevice.AWNING.Definition: A rooflike shelter of canvas or other material extending over a doorway, from the top of a window, over a deck, or similar, in order to provide protection, as from the sun.
IfcShadingDevice.AWNING.Name: Awning

IfcShadingDevice.JALOUSIE.Definition: A blind with adjustable horizontal slats for admitting light and air while excluding direct sun and rain.
IfcShadingDevice.JALOUSIE.Name: Jalousie

IfcShadingDevice.SHUTTER.Definition: A mechanical device that limits the passage of light. Often used as a a solid or louvered movable cover for a window.
IfcShadingDevice.SHUTTER.Name: Shutter

IfcSlab.APPROACH_SLAB.Definition: Iis part of bridge abutment providing transition from embankment to the bridge
IfcSlab.APPROACH_SLAB.Name: Approach Slab

IfcSlab.BASESLAB.Definition: The slab is used to represent a floor slab against the ground (and thereby being a part of the foundation). Another name is mat foundation.
IfcSlab.BASESLAB.Name: Baseslab

IsSurfaceGalling.Name: Is Surface Galling
IsSurfaceGalling.Definition: Indicates whether the surface is galling or not.

SurfaceGallingArea.Name: Surface Galling Area
SurfaceGallingArea.Definition: The galling area of the object surface.

IfcSlab.FLOOR.Definition: The slab is used to represent a floor slab or a bridge deck.
IfcSlab.FLOOR.Name: Floor

IfcSlab.LANDING.Definition: The slab is used to represent a landing within a stair or ramp.
IfcSlab.LANDING.Name: Landing

IfcSlab.PAVING.Definition: Rigid pavement course of a road or other paved area, usually concrete.
IfcSlab.PAVING.Name: Paving

IfcSlab.ROOF.Definition: The slab is used to represent a roof slab (either flat or sloped).
IfcSlab.ROOF.Name: Roof

IfcSlab.SIDEWALK.Definition: The slab is used to represent a sidewalk.
IfcSlab.SIDEWALK.Name: Side Walk

IfcSlab.TRACKSLAB.Definition: A track slab is a reinforced concrete slab or prestressed reinforced concrete slab, which is a main element of slab track. It can be prefabricated or cast on site and may have sleepers embedded.
IfcSlab.TRACKSLAB.Name: Trackslab

CheckRailType.Name: Check Rail Type
CheckRailType.Definition: Type of the check rail. Check rail types enumerated in this property are defined based on EN 13674.

JointRelativePosition.Name: Joint Relative Position
JointRelativePosition.Definition: Indicates the relative position of the joint, which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle, or in combination. The left rail is to the left as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values, and the right rail is to the right.

Values.Description: which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle
which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle
which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle

LoadCapacity.Name: Load Capacity
LoadCapacity.Definition: Indicates the highest permissible load capacity.

UsagePurpose.Name: Usage Purpose
UsagePurpose.Definition: The purpose of usage of the cess between rails, e.g. maintenance, rescue services.

HasDrainage.Name: Has Drainage
HasDrainage.Definition: Indicates whether the infrastructure element has drainage embedded or not.

IsAccessibleByVehicle.Name: Is Accessible By Vehicle
IsAccessibleByVehicle.Definition: Indicates whether the element is accessible by a vehicle or not.

PermissibleRoadLoad.Name: Permissible Road Load
PermissibleRoadLoad.Definition: Permissible traffic load for the road design.

TechnicalStandard.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TechnicalStandard.Name: Technical Standard
TechnicalStandard.Definition: The technical standard which the element should comply with.

IfcSlab.WEARING.Definition: The slab is used to represent a wearing surface.
IfcSlab.WEARING.Name: Wearing

IfcStair.CURVED_RUN_STAIR.Definition: A stair extending from one level to another without turns or winders. The stair is consisting of one curved flight.
IfcStair.CURVED_RUN_STAIR.Name: Curved Run Stair

IfcStair.DOUBLE_RETURN_STAIR.Definition: A stair having one straight flight to a wide quarterspace landing, and two side flights from that landing into opposite directions. The stair is making a 90 turn. The direction of traffic is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.DOUBLE_RETURN_STAIR.Name: Double Return Stair

IfcStair.HALF_TURN_STAIR.Definition: A stair making a 180 turn, consisting of two straight flights connectedby a halfspace landing. The orientation of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.HALF_TURN_STAIR.Name: Half Turn Stair

IfcStair.HALF_WINDING_STAIR.Definition: A stair consisting of one flight with one half winder, which makes a 180 turn. The orientation of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.HALF_WINDING_STAIR.Name: Half Winding Stair

IfcStair.LADDER.Definition: a piece of equipment consisting of a series of bars or steps between two upright elements used for climbing up or down something
IfcStair.LADDER.Name: Ladder

IfcStair.QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Definition: A stair making a 90 turn, consisting of two straight flights connected by a quarterspace landing. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Name: Quarter Turn Stair

IfcStair.QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Definition: A stair consisting of one flight with a quarter winder, which is making a 90 turn. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Name: Quarter Winding Stair

IfcStair.SPIRAL_STAIR.Definition: A stair constructed with winders around a circular newel often without landings. Depending on outer boundary it can be either a circular, elliptical or rectangular spiral stair. The orientation of the winding stairs is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.SPIRAL_STAIR.Name: Spiral Stair

IfcStair.STRAIGHT_RUN_STAIR.Definition: A stair extending from one level to another without turns or winders. The stair consists of one straight flight.
IfcStair.STRAIGHT_RUN_STAIR.Name: Straight Run Stair

IfcStair.THREE_QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Definition: A stair making a 270 turn, consisting of four straight flights connected; by three quarterspace landings. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.THREE_QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Name: Three Quarter Turn Stair

IfcStair.THREE_QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Definition: A stair consisting of one flight with three quarter winders, which make a; 90 turn. The stair makes a 270 turn. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.THREE_QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Name: Three Quarter Winding Stair

IfcStair.TWO_CURVED_RUN_STAIR.Definition: A curved stair consisting of two curved flights without turns but with one landing.
IfcStair.TWO_CURVED_RUN_STAIR.Name: Two Curved Run Stair

IfcStair.TWO_QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Definition: A stair making a 180 turn, consisting of three straight flights connected by two quarterspace landings. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.TWO_QUARTER_TURN_STAIR.Name: Two Quarter Turn Stair

IfcStair.TWO_QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Definition: A stair consisting of one flight with two quarter winders, which make a; 90 turn. The stair makes a 180 turn. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
IfcStair.TWO_QUARTER_WINDING_STAIR.Name: Two Quarter Winding Stair

IfcStair.TWO_STRAIGHT_RUN_STAIR.Definition: A straight stair consisting of two straight flights without turns but with one landing.
IfcStair.TWO_STRAIGHT_RUN_STAIR.Name: Two Straight Run Stair

IfcStairFlight.CURVED.Definition: A stair flight with a curved walking line.
IfcStairFlight.CURVED.Name: Curved

IfcStairFlight.FREEFORM.Definition: A stair flight with a free form walking line (and outer boundaries).
IfcStairFlight.FREEFORM.Name: Freeform

IfcStairFlight.SPIRAL.Definition: A stair flight with a circular or elliptic walking line.
IfcStairFlight.SPIRAL.Name: Spiral

IfcStairFlight.STRAIGHT.Definition: A stair flight with a straight walking line.
IfcStairFlight.STRAIGHT.Name: Straight

IfcStairFlight.WINDER.Definition: A stair flight with a walking line including straight and curved sections.
IfcStairFlight.WINDER.Name: Winder

IfcWall.ELEMENTEDWALL.Definition: A stud wall framed with studs and faced with sheetings, sidings, wallboard, or plasterwork.
IfcWall.ELEMENTEDWALL.Name: Elemented Wall

IfcWall.MOVABLE.Definition: A movable wall that is either movable, such as folding wall or a sliding wall, or can be easily removed as a removable partitioning or mounting wall. Movable walls do normally not define space boundaries and often belong to the furnishing system.
IfcWall.MOVABLE.Name: Movable

IfcWall.PARAPET.Definition: A wall-like barrier to protect human or vehicle from falling, or to prevent the spread of fires. Often designed at the edge of balconies, terraces or roofs, or along edges of bridges.
IfcWall.PARAPET.Name: Parapet

IsTerminal.Name: Is Terminal
IsTerminal.Definition: True if element is a terminal. See class Terminal.

Values.Description: True if element is a terminal

IsTransition.Name: Is Transition
IsTransition.Definition: True if element is a transition. See class Transition.

Values.Description: True if element is a transition

TerminalType.Name: Terminal Type
TerminalType.Definition: Specifies the kind of terminal if IsTerminal is true.

IfcWall.PARTITIONING.Definition: A wall designed to partition spaces that often has a light-weight, sandwich-like construction (e.g. using gypsum board). Partitioning walls are normally non load bearing.
IfcWall.PARTITIONING.Name: Partitioning

IfcWall.PLUMBINGWALL.Definition: A pier, or enclosure, or encasement, normally used to enclose plumbing in sanitary rooms. Such walls often do not extend to the ceiling.
IfcWall.PLUMBINGWALL.Name: Plumbing Wall

IfcWall.POLYGONAL.Definition: A polygonal wall, extruded vertically, where the wall thickness varies along the wall path.
IfcWall.POLYGONAL.Name: Polygonal

IfcWall.RETAININGWALL.Definition: A supporting wall used to protect against soil layers behind. Special types of a retaining wall may be e.g. Gabion wall and Grib wall. Examples of retaining walls are wing wall, headwall, stem wall, pierwall and protecting wall.
IfcWall.RETAININGWALL.Name: Retaining Wall

IfcWall.SHEAR.Definition: A wall designed to withstand shear loads. Examples of shear wall are diaphragms inside a box girder, typically on a pier, to resist lateral forces and transfer them to the support.
IfcWall.SHEAR.Name: Shear

IfcWall.SOLIDWALL.Definition: A massive wall construction for the wall core being the single layer or having multiple layers attached. Such walls are often masonry or concrete walls (both cast in-situ or precast) that are load bearing and fire protecting.
IfcWall.SOLIDWALL.Name: Solid Wall

IfcWall.STANDARD.Definition: A standard wall, extruded vertically with a constant thickness along the wall path.;
IfcWall.STANDARD.Name: Standard

IfcWall.WAVEWALL.Definition: Protective wall or screen to block overtopping and impact of waves across a breakwater
IfcWall.WAVEWALL.Name: Wave Wall

IfcWindow.LIGHTDOME.Definition: A special window that lies horizonally in a roof slab opening.
IfcWindow.LIGHTDOME.Name: Light Dome

IfcWindow.SKYLIGHT.Definition: A window within a sloped building element, usually a roof slab.
IfcWindow.SKYLIGHT.Name: Sky Light

IfcWindow.WINDOW.Definition: A standard window usually within a wall opening, as a window panel in a curtain wall, or as a "free standing" window.
IfcWindow.WINDOW.Name: Window

IfcDistributionChamberElement.FORMEDDUCT.Definition: Space formed in the ground for the passage of pipes, cables, ducts.
IfcDistributionChamberElement.FORMEDDUCT.Name: Formed Duct

AccessCoverLoadRating.Definition: The load rating of the access cover (which may be a value or an alphanumerically defined class rating).

CableDuctOccupancyRatio.Definition: Indicates the ratio between the number of cables in the duct and the maximum number of cables that the duct can contain.

WallThickness.Definition: The thickness of the wall construction.;

IfcDistributionChamberElement.INSPECTION.Name: Inspection Chamber

ConductorFunction.Name: Conductor Function
ConductorFunction.Definition: Indicates function of the conductors to which the load is connected. Where L1, L2 and L3 represent the phase lines according to IEC 60446 notation (sometimes phase lines may be referenced by color [Red, Blue, Yellow] or by number [1, 2, 3] etc). Protective Earth is sometimes also known as CPC or common protective conductor. Note that for an electrical device, a set of line conductor functions may be applied.

ElectricalSystemType.Name: Electrical System Type
ElectricalSystemType.Definition: For certain purposes of electrical regulations, IEC 60364 defines types of system using type identifiers. Assignment of identifiers depends upon the relationship of the source, and of exposed conductive parts of the installation, to Ground (Earth). Identifiers that may be assigned through IEC 60364 are: TN type system, a system having one or more points of the source of energy directly earthed, the exposed conductive parts of the installation being connected to that point by protective conductors,; TN C type system, a TN type system in which neutral and protective functions are combined in a single conductor throughout the system,; TN S type system, a TN type system having separate neutral and protective conductors throughout the system,; TN C S type system, a TN type system in which neutral and protective functions are combined in a single conductor in part of the system,; TT type system, a system having one point of the source of energy directly earthed, the exposed conductive parts of the installation being connected to earth electrodes electrically independent of the earth electrodes of the source,; IT type system, a system having no direct connection between live parts and Earth, the exposed conductive parts of the electrical installation being earthed.

Values.Description: Identifiers that may be assigned through IEC 60364 are:TN type system

The settings should limit the overall voltage drop to the required level. Default settings of 1.5% for sub-main circuits and 2.5% for final circuits, giving an overall limit of 4% may be applied.;
