NumberOfWires.Name: Number of Wires
NumberOfWires.Definition: The number of wires used in the element.

TensileStrength.Name: Tensile Strength
TensileStrength.Definition: Indicates the ability to withstand breakage apart under applied force.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.LOCK.Definition: A lock is a mechanical or electronic fastening device that is released either by a physical object (e.g., key, fingerprint, RFID card, security token etc.), by supplying secret information (e.g., number permutation, password), or by a combination thereof.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.LOCK.Name: Lock

InstallationPlan.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
InstallationPlan.Name: Installation Plan
InstallationPlan.Definition: Reference to external information source about installation or construction plan of the element.

RequiredClosureSpacing.Name: Required Closure Spacing
RequiredClosureSpacing.Definition: Required length of the closure spacing.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.PANEL_STRENGTHENING.Definition: A component that minimizes pump effects of the substructure.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.PANEL_STRENGTHENING.Name: Panel Strengthening

IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAILBRACE.Definition: A rail component that prevents rails from tipping and twisting.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAILBRACE.Name: Rail Brace

IsTemporary.Name: Is Temporary
IsTemporary.Definition: Indicates if the installation of the element is temporary or not.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAILPAD.Definition: A non-metallic pad placed between rail and baseplate or rail and sleeper, bearer or slab.; Note: definition from EN 13481-1.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAILPAD.Name: Rail Pad

RailPadStiffness.Name: Rail Pad Stiffness
RailPadStiffness.Definition: Indicates the stiffness of a rail pad.

Values.Description: Indicates the stiffness of a rail pad

IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAIL_LUBRICATION.Definition: A device that prevents wearing of the rails throughout the flange of wheel to reduce noise emissions. It is often located at inner side of the outer rail in a curve or near turnouts (depends on function wearing or noise reduction).
IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAIL_LUBRICATION.Name: Rail Lubrication

LubricationPowerSupplyType.Name: Lubrication Power Supply Type
LubricationPowerSupplyType.Definition: Type of power supply method used by the rail lubrication.

LubricationSystemType.Name: Lubrication System Type
LubricationSystemType.Definition: Design and type of lubricating system e.g. active, passive.

MaximumNoiseEmissions.Name: Maximum Noise Emissions
MaximumNoiseEmissions.Definition: Maximum noise emissions limit at this location.

PositionInTrack.Name: Position In Track
PositionInTrack.Definition: Indicates the relative position of the element in track, which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values.

Values.Description: which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values
which lies to the left or right as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values

IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAIL_MECHANICAL_EQU.Definition: A rail mechanical equipment is a mechnical equipment installed at railside, like blocking device, speed regulator, bias loaded inspector, track scale or controllable retarder.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.RAIL_MECHANICAL_EQU.Name: Rail Mechanical Equipment

IfcDiscreteAccessory.SHOE.Definition: A column shoe or a beam shoe (beam hanger) used to support or secure an element.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.SHOE.Name: Shoe

ColumnShoeBasePlateDepth.Name: Column Shoe Base Plate Depth
ColumnShoeBasePlateDepth.Definition: The depth of the column shoe base plate.

ColumnShoeBasePlateThickness.Name: Column Shoe Base Plate Thickness
ColumnShoeBasePlateThickness.Definition: The thickness of the column shoe base plate.

ColumnShoeBasePlateWidth.Name: Column Shoe Base Plate Width
ColumnShoeBasePlateWidth.Definition: The width of the column shoe base plate.

ColumnShoeCasingDepth.Name: Column Shoe Casing Depth
ColumnShoeCasingDepth.Definition: The depth of the column shoe casing.

ColumnShoeCasingHeight.Name: Column Shoe Casing Height
ColumnShoeCasingHeight.Definition: The height of the column shoe casing.

ColumnShoeCasingWidth.Name: Column Shoe Casing Width
ColumnShoeCasingWidth.Definition: The width of the column shoe casing.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.SLIDINGCHAIR.Definition: A component which supports and retains the stock rail and a flat surface upon which the foot of the switch rail slides.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.SLIDINGCHAIR.Name: Sliding Chair

IsSelfLubricated.Name: Is Self Lubricated
IsSelfLubricated.Definition: Indicates whether the element is self lubricated or not.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.SOUNDABSORPTION.Definition: A component in the track for sound absorption and may also absorb vibrations. It is often used in combination with slab tracks.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.SOUNDABSORPTION.Name: Sound Absorption

SoundAbsorptionLimit.Name: Sound Absorption Limit
SoundAbsorptionLimit.Definition: Mandatory limit values in sound absorption.

IfcDiscreteAccessory.TENSIONINGEQUIPMENT.Definition: An equipment used to maintain the tension of conductors or cables.
IfcDiscreteAccessory.TENSIONINGEQUIPMENT.Name: Tensioning Equipment

ReferenceDistanceRopeToPulley.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceDistanceRopeToPulley.Name: Reference Distance Rope to Pulley
ReferenceDistanceRopeToPulley.Definition: The reference design criteria for distance from the end of the rope to the fixed pulley.It defines the nominal distance in relation to temperature.

ReferenceDistanceTensionerToGround.Description: This property in IFC takes a table as its value. That table has two columns (two lists), one for defining and other for defined values. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceDistanceTensionerToGround.Name: Reference Distance Tensioner to Ground
ReferenceDistanceTensionerToGround.Definition: The reference design criteria distance from the last tensioner to the ground or the base surface (B value). It defines the nominal distance in relation to temperature.

AssemblyInstruction.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
AssemblyInstruction.Name: Assembly Instruction
AssemblyInstruction.Definition: Instructions to describe how the system / equipment / facility is assembled.

HasBreakLineLock.Name: Has Break Line Lock
HasBreakLineLock.Definition: Indicates whether the equipment has the function of brake line lock or not.

RatioOfWireTension.Name: Ratio of Wire Tension
RatioOfWireTension.Definition: The ratio of wire tension to tensioner weight.

ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
ReferenceEnvironmentTemperature.Name: Reference Environment Temperature

TensileStrength.Name: Tensile Strength
TensileStrength.Definition: Indicates the ability to withstand breakage apart under applied force.

TransmissionEfficiency.Name: Transmission Efficiency
TransmissionEfficiency.Definition: Transmission efficiency of the tensioning equipment.

TensileStrength.Name: Tensile Strength
TensileStrength.Definition: Indicates the ability to withstand breakage apart under applied force.

TensioningWorkingRange.Description: This property in IFC stores a bounded value, meaning it has a maximum of two (numeric or descriptive) values assigned, the first value specifying the upper bound and the second value specifying the lower bound. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TensioningWorkingRange.Name: Tensioning Working Range
TensioningWorkingRange.Definition: The working range of the tensioning equipment under normal operation.

IfcFastener.GLUE.Definition: A fastening connection where glue is used to join together elements.
IfcFastener.GLUE.Name: Glue

IfcFastener.MORTAR.Definition: A composition of mineralic or other materials used to fill jointing gaps and possibly fulfilling a load carrying role.
IfcFastener.MORTAR.Name: Mortar

IfcFastener.WELD.Definition: A weld seam between parts of metallic material or other suitable materials.
IfcFastener.WELD.Name: Weld

AssemblyPlace.Name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

Values.Description: other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site

IsLiftingBracket.Name: Is Lifting Bracket
IsLiftingBracket.Definition: Indicates whether the connection is done between rail with different height (TRUE) or with same height (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the connection is done between rail with different height (TRUE) or with same height (FALSE)
Indicates whether the connection is done between rail with different height (TRUE) or with same height (FALSE)

JointRelativePosition.Name: Joint Relative Position
JointRelativePosition.Definition: Indicates the relative position of the joint, which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle, or in combination. The left rail is to the left as facing in the direction of increasing stationing values, and the right rail is to the right.

Values.Description: which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle
which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle
which lies in the left or right rail or in the middle

DeepPenetrationThroatThickness.Name: Deep Penetration Throat Thickness
DeepPenetrationThroatThickness.Definition: Nominal throat thickness or effective throat thickness to which a certain amount of fusion penetration is added.REFERENCE Symbol s according to ISO 2553: 2019.

Intermittent.Name: Intermittent
Intermittent.Definition: If fillet weld, intermittent or not

NominalThroatThickness.Name: Nominal Throat Thickness
NominalThroatThickness.Definition: Design value of the height of the largest isosceles triangle that can be inscribed in the section of a fillet weld.REFERENCE Symbol a according to ISO 2553: 2019.

NumberOfWeldElements.Name: Number of Weld Elements
NumberOfWeldElements.Definition: Number of weld elements.REFERENCE Symbol n according to ISO 2553: 2019.

Process.Name: Process
Process.Definition: Reference number of the welding process according to ISO 4063, an up to three digits long code

ProcessName.Name: Process Name
ProcessName.Definition: Name of the welding process. Alternative to the numeric Process property.

Staggered.Name: Staggered
Staggered.Definition: If intermittent weld, staggered or not

Surface1.Name: Surface1
Surface1.Definition: Aspect of weld seam surface, i.e. 'plane', 'curved' or 'hollow'. Combined welds are given by two corresponding symbols analogous to Type1 and Type2.

Type1.Name: Type1
Type1.Definition: Type of weld seam according to ISO 2553. Note, combined welds are given by two corresponding symbols in the direction of the normal axis of the coordinate system. For example, an X weld is specified by Type1 = 'V' and Type2 = 'V'.

WeldDiameter.Name: Weld Diameter
WeldDiameter.Definition: Dimension of the required hole diameter at the faying surface, or required spot weld diameter at the faying surface, or required stud diameter.REFERENCE Symbol d according to ISO 2553: 2019.

WeldElementLength.Name: Weld Element Length
WeldElementLength.Definition: Length of each weld element.REFERENCE Symbol l according to ISO 2553: 2019.

WeldElementSpacing.Name: Weld Element Spacing
WeldElementSpacing.Definition: Spacing between weld elements (centre to centre)REFERENCE Symbol e according to ISO 2553: 2019.

WeldLegLength.Name: Weld Leg Length
WeldLegLength.Definition: Distance from the actual or projected intersection of the fusion faces and the toe of a fillet weld, measured across the fusion face.REFERENCE Symbol z according to ISO 2553: 2019.

WeldWidth.Name: Weld Width
WeldWidth.Definition: Required elongated hole width at the faying surface or seam weld width at the faying surface.REFERENCE Symbol c according to ISO 2553: 2019.

IfcMechanicalFastener.ANCHORBOLT.Definition: A special bolt which is anchored into concrete, stone, or brickwork.
IfcMechanicalFastener.ANCHORBOLT.Name: Anchorbolt

AnchorBoltDiameter.Name: Anchor Bolt Diameter
AnchorBoltDiameter.Definition: The nominal diameter of the anchor bolt bar(s).

AnchorBoltLength.Name: Anchor Bolt Length
AnchorBoltLength.Definition: The length of the anchor bolt.

AnchorBoltProtrusionLength.Name: Anchor Bolt Protrusion Length
AnchorBoltProtrusionLength.Definition: The length of the protruding part of the anchor bolt.

AnchorBoltThreadLength.Name: Anchor Bolt Thread Length
AnchorBoltThreadLength.Definition: The length of the threaded part of the anchor bolt.

IfcMechanicalFastener.BOLT.Definition: A threaded cylindrical rod that engages with a similarly threaded hole in a nut or any other part to form a fastener. The mechanical fastener often also includes one or more washers and one or more nuts.
IfcMechanicalFastener.BOLT.Name: Bolt

HeadShape.Name: Head Shape
HeadShape.Definition: Shape of the bolt's head, e.g. 'Hexagon', 'Countersunk', 'Cheese'

KeyShape.Name: Key Shape
KeyShape.Definition: If applicable, shape of the head's slot, e.g. 'Slot', 'Allen'

NutsCount.Name: Nuts Count
NutsCount.Definition: Count of nuts to be mounted on one bolt

ThreadDiameter.Name: Thread Diameter
ThreadDiameter.Definition: Nominal diameter of the thread, if different from the bolt's overall nominal diameter

WashersCount.Name: Washers Count
WashersCount.Definition: Count of washers to be mounted on one bolt

IfcMechanicalFastener.CHAIN.Definition: a series of linked metal rings used for fastening or securing something, or for pulling loads.
IfcMechanicalFastener.CHAIN.Name: Chain

IfcMechanicalFastener.COUPLER.Definition: A part connecting two rod or bars, such as reinforcement bars.
IfcMechanicalFastener.COUPLER.Name: Coupler

ManufacturingTechnology.Name: Manufacturing Technology
ManufacturingTechnology.Definition: The method / technology used to produce the equipment.

OCSFasteningType.Name: Ocsfastening Type
OCSFasteningType.Definition: Indicates the type of the overhead contact system (OCS) mechanical fastener.

IfcMechanicalFastener.DOWEL.Definition: A cylindrical rod that is driven into holes of the connected pieces.
IfcMechanicalFastener.DOWEL.Name: Dowel

IfcMechanicalFastener.NAIL.Definition: A thin pointed piece of metal that is hammered into materials as a fastener.
IfcMechanicalFastener.NAIL.Name: Nail

IfcMechanicalFastener.NAILPLATE.Definition: A piece of sheet metal with punched points that overlaps the connected pieces and is pressed into their material.
IfcMechanicalFastener.NAILPLATE.Name: Nail Plate

IfcMechanicalFastener.RAILFASTENING.Definition: An assembly of components which secures a rail to the supporting structure and retains it in the required position whilst permitting any necessary vertical, lateral and longitudinal movement.; Note: definition from EN 13481-1.
IfcMechanicalFastener.RAILFASTENING.Name: Rail Fastening

IsReducedResistanceFastening.Name: Is Reduced Resistance Fastening
IsReducedResistanceFastening.Definition: Indicates whether the rail fastening is a reduced resistance fastening (YES) or not (NO).

TechnicalStandard.Description: This property in IFC takes as its value a reference to one of: IfcAddress, IfcAppliedValue, IfcExternalReference, IfcMaterialDefinition, IfcOrganization, IfcPerson, IfcPersonAndOrganization, IfcTable, IfcTimeSeries. Read the IFC documentation for more information.
TechnicalStandard.Name: Technical Standard
TechnicalStandard.Definition: The technical standard which the element should comply with.

IfcMechanicalFastener.RAILJOINT.Definition: A mechanical assembly with e.g. fishplates to join two rail ends with optional functions (insulation or expansion capacity).
IfcMechanicalFastener.RAILJOINT.Name: Rail Joint

AssemblyPlace.Name: Assembly Place
AssemblyPlace.Definition: Enumeration defining where the assembly is intended to take place, either in a factory, other offsite location or on the building site.

Values.Description: other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site
other offsite location or on the building site

IsCWRJoint.Name: Is Cwrjoint
IsCWRJoint.Definition: Indicates if the rail joint is associated to a continuous welded rail.

IsJointControlEquipment.Name: Is Joint Control Equipment
IsJointControlEquipment.Definition: Indicates whether security equipment is checking the mechanical functionality of the rail joint.

IsJointInsulated.Name: Is Joint Insulated
IsJointInsulated.Definition: Indicates if the rail joint is insulated.

IsLiftingBracketConnection.Name: Is Lifting Bracket Connection
IsLiftingBracketConnection.Definition: Indicates if the connection is between two different heights (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates if the connection is between two different heights (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indicates if the connection is between two different heights (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

RailGap.Name: Rail Gap
RailGap.Definition: The gap between the rail profiles.

SleeperArrangement.Name: Sleeper Arrangement
SleeperArrangement.Definition: Define the rail joint sleeper method of assembly ("twin sleeper" type or "between sleepers" type).

IfcMechanicalFastener.RIVET.Definition: A fastening part having a head at one end and the other end being hammered flat after being passed through holes in the pieces that are fastened together.
IfcMechanicalFastener.RIVET.Name: Rivet

IfcMechanicalFastener.ROPE.Definition: a length of thick strong cord made by twisting together strands of hemp, sisal, nylon, or similar material. used primarily for mooring vessels
IfcMechanicalFastener.ROPE.Name: Rope

CentreLineToFairlead.Name: Centre Line to Fairlead
CentreLineToFairlead.Definition: Distance from the vessel centreline to the fairlead for the line

FairleadToTermination.Name: Fairlead to Termination
FairleadToTermination.Definition: Distance from the fairlead to the bitt or winch on the vessel where the line terminates

HeightAboveMainDeck.Name: Height Above Main Deck
HeightAboveMainDeck.Definition: Height of the fairlead above the main deck of the vessel

LineIdentifier.Name: Line Identifier
LineIdentifier.Definition: Reference ID relative to a design vessel in the project

LineStrength.Name: Line Strength
LineStrength.Definition: Breaking load of the line (note that ultimate stress is not part of any of the material Psets)

MidshipToFairLead.Name: Midship to Fair Lead
MidshipToFairLead.Definition: Distance from the vessel midship to the fairlead for the line

PreTensionAim.Name: Pre Tension Aim
PreTensionAim.Definition: Line force that the winch is set to maintain (minimum load)

TailStrength.Name: Tail Strength
TailStrength.Definition: Breaking load of the tail (note that ultimate stress is not part of any of the material Psets)

WinchBreakLimit.Name: Winch Break Limit
WinchBreakLimit.Definition: Line force at which the winch starts to release the line (maximum load)

IfcMechanicalFastener.SCREW.Definition: A fastener with a tapered threaded shank and a slotted head.
IfcMechanicalFastener.SCREW.Name: Screw

IfcMechanicalFastener.SHEARCONNECTOR.Definition: A ring connector that is accepted by ring keyways in the connected pieces; or a toothed circular or square connector that is pressed into the connected pieces.
IfcMechanicalFastener.SHEARCONNECTOR.Name: Shear Connector

IfcMechanicalFastener.STAPLE.Definition: A doubly pointed piece of metal that is hammered into materials as a fastener.
IfcMechanicalFastener.STAPLE.Name: Staple

IfcMechanicalFastener.STUDSHEARCONNECTOR.Definition: Stud shear connectors are cylindrical fastening parts with a head on one side. On the other side they are welded on steel members for the use in composite steel and concrete structures.
IfcMechanicalFastener.STUDSHEARCONNECTOR.Name: Stud Shear Connector

IfcFurniture.CHAIR.Definition: Furniture for seating a single person.
IfcFurniture.CHAIR.Name: Chair

HighestSeatingHeight.Name: Highest Seating Height
HighestSeatingHeight.Definition: The value of seating height of high level if the chair height is adjustable.

LowestSeatingHeight.Name: Lowest Seating Height
LowestSeatingHeight.Definition: The value of seating height of low level if the chair height is adjustable.

SeatingHeight.Name: Seating Height
SeatingHeight.Definition: The value of seating height if the chair height is not adjustable.

IfcFurniture.DESK.Definition: Furniture with a countertop and optional drawers for a single person.
IfcFurniture.DESK.Name: Desk

WorksurfaceArea.Name: Worksurface Area
WorksurfaceArea.Definition: The value of the work surface area of the desk.

IfcFurniture.FILECABINET.Definition: Furniture with sliding drawers for storing files.
IfcFurniture.FILECABINET.Name: File Cabinet

WithLock.Name: with Lock
WithLock.Definition: Indicates whether the file cabinet is lockable (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the file cabinet is lockable (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)
Indicates whether the file cabinet is lockable (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)

IfcFurniture.SHELF.Definition: Furniture for storing books or other items.
IfcFurniture.SHELF.Name: Shelf

IfcFurniture.TABLE.Definition: Furniture with a countertop for multiple people.
IfcFurniture.TABLE.Name: Table

NumberOfChairs.Name: Number of Chairs
NumberOfChairs.Definition: Maximum number of chairs that can fit with the table for normal use.

WorksurfaceArea.Name: Worksurface Area
WorksurfaceArea.Definition: The value of the work surface area of the desk.

IfcFurniture.TECHNICALCABINET.Definition: A technical cabinet is a piece of furniture for holding, displaying and protecting technical appliances, usually organized in shelves, drawers or racks.
IfcFurniture.TECHNICALCABINET.Name: Technical Cabinet

IfcInventory.ASSETINVENTORY.Definition: A collection of asset instances of type IfcAsset.
IfcInventory.ASSETINVENTORY.Name: Asset Inventory

IfcInventory.FURNITUREINVENTORY.Definition: A collection of furniture instances of type IfcFurnishingElement.
IfcInventory.FURNITUREINVENTORY.Name: Furniture Inventory

IfcInventory.SPACEINVENTORY.Definition: A collection of space instances of type IfcSpace.
IfcInventory.SPACEINVENTORY.Name: Space Inventory

IfcOccupant.ASSIGNEE.Definition: Actor receiving the assignment of a property agreement from an assignor.
IfcOccupant.ASSIGNEE.Name: Assignee

IfcOccupant.ASSIGNOR.Definition: Actor assigning a property agreement to an assignor.
IfcOccupant.ASSIGNOR.Name: Assignor

IfcOccupant.LESSEE.Definition: Actor receiving the lease of a property from a lessor.
IfcOccupant.LESSEE.Name: Lessee

IfcOccupant.LESSOR.Definition: Actor leasing a property to a lessee.
IfcOccupant.LESSOR.Name: Lessor

IfcOccupant.LETTINGAGENT.Definition: Actor participating in a property agreement on behalf of an owner, lessor or assignor.
IfcOccupant.LETTINGAGENT.Name: Letting Agent

IfcOccupant.TENANT.Definition: Actor renting the use of a property fro a period of time.
IfcOccupant.TENANT.Name: Tenant

IfcSystemFurnitureElement.PANEL.Definition: Vertical panel used to divide work spaces.
IfcSystemFurnitureElement.PANEL.Name: Panel

FurniturePanelType.Name: Furniture Panel Type
FurniturePanelType.Definition: Available panel types from which that required may be selected.

HasOpening.Name: Has Opening
HasOpening.Definition: indicates whether the panel has an opening (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE).

Values.Description: indicates whether the panel has an opening (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)
indicates whether the panel has an opening (= TRUE) or not (= FALSE)

NominalThickness.Name: Nominal Thickness
NominalThickness.Definition: The nominal thickness of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcSystemFurnitureElement.SUBRACK.Definition: A subrack is a part of technical cabinet which is used to store and mount pluggable electric subunits.
IfcSystemFurnitureElement.SUBRACK.Name: Subrack

NumberOfOccupiedUnits.Name: Number of Occupied Units
NumberOfOccupiedUnits.Definition: Indicates the number of vertical units occupied by the equipment.

NumberOfUnits.Name: Number of Units
NumberOfUnits.Definition: Indicates the number of vertical units.

HangingHeight.Name: Hanging Height
HangingHeight.Definition: The hanging height of the worksurface.

NominalThickness.Name: Nominal Thickness
NominalThickness.Definition: The nominal thickness of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

ShapeDescription.Name: Shape Description
ShapeDescription.Definition: A description of the shape of the work surface e.g. corner square, rectangle, etc.

SupportType.Name: Support Type
SupportType.Definition: Available support types from which that required may be selected.

UsePurpose.Name: Use Purpose
UsePurpose.Definition: The principal purpose for which the work surface is intended to be used e.g. writing/reading, computer, meeting, printer, reference files, etc.

IfcCourse.ARMOUR.Definition: An Aggregate layer whose primary function is to protect against erosion of the underlying material by water e.g. riprap.
IfcCourse.ARMOUR.Name: Armour

IfcCourse.BALLASTBED.Definition: Layer composed of broken stones under the sleepers.
IfcCourse.BALLASTBED.Name: Ballastbed

IfcCourse.CORE.Definition: A core course is the bulk internal structure of aggregate structures.
IfcCourse.CORE.Name: Core

IfcCourse.FILTER.Definition: An Intermediate layer whose primary function is to prevent the washing through of fine materials.
IfcCourse.FILTER.Name: Filter

IfcCourse.PAVEMENT.Definition: A layer within a pavement structure that forms a paved area or road.
IfcCourse.PAVEMENT.Name: Pavement

IfcCourse.PROTECTION.Definition: Layer with the primary task to provide protection against erosion and scour.
IfcCourse.PROTECTION.Name: Protection

IfcEarthworksCut.BASE_EXCAVATION.Definition: Excavation for basements of buildings, abutments of bridges or similar structures either partially or completely below ground level.
IfcEarthworksCut.BASE_EXCAVATION.Name: Base Excavation

IfcEarthworksCut.CUT.Definition: Excavation where soil or rock below topsoil is cut to the depth required for the construction of facilities such as roads and railways. The removed material can be used as fill (IfcEarthworksElement) for embankments or to form a level surface on which to build.
IfcEarthworksCut.CUT.Name: Cut

IfcEarthworksCut.DREDGING.Definition: Underwater excavation to recover material or to create a greater depth of water.
IfcEarthworksCut.DREDGING.Name: Dredging

IfcEarthworksCut.EXCAVATION.Definition: General type of excavation when more accurate type is not specified.
IfcEarthworksCut.EXCAVATION.Name: Excavation

IfcEarthworksCut.OVEREXCAVATION.Definition: Excavation that goes beyond the depth required for construction, in order to replace unsuitable material.
IfcEarthworksCut.OVEREXCAVATION.Name: Over Excavation

IfcEarthworksCut.PAVEMENTMILLING.Definition: Removal of expired material from top of pavement to be replaced by new material.
IfcEarthworksCut.PAVEMENTMILLING.Name: Pavement Milling

NominalWidth.Name: Nominal Width
NominalWidth.Definition: The nominal overall width of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcEarthworksCut.STEPEXCAVATION.Definition: Removal of the soft part of the existing road slope, where it is dug into steps, when widening a road.
IfcEarthworksCut.STEPEXCAVATION.Name: Step Excavation

IfcEarthworksCut.TOPSOILREMOVAL.Definition: Excavation where the topmost layer of soil containing organic material is cut or stripped. The removed topsoil can be used as fill (EarthworksElement) e.g. where planting is planned.
IfcEarthworksCut.TOPSOILREMOVAL.Name: Top Soil Removal

IfcEarthworksCut.TRENCH.Definition: Excavation whose length greatly exceeds the depth and width. Trench is typically excavated for strip foundations or for buried services such as drainage or cabling.
IfcEarthworksCut.TRENCH.Name: Trench

NominalWidth.Name: Nominal Width
NominalWidth.Definition: The nominal overall width of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In cases of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcEarthworksFill.BACKFILL.Definition: Fill behind retaining walls or other structures such as quays, behind abutments and bridges.
IfcEarthworksFill.BACKFILL.Name: Backfill

IfcEarthworksFill.COUNTERWEIGHT.Definition: Embankment built on the side of the main road structure to reduce the settlement of the road.
IfcEarthworksFill.COUNTERWEIGHT.Name: Counterweight

IfcEarthworksFill.EMBANKMENT.Definition: Predominantly longitudinal type of earthworks element with no other particular assigned type according to its role in Pavement or Subgrade.;
IfcEarthworksFill.EMBANKMENT.Name: Embankment

IfcEarthworksFill.SLOPEFILL.Definition: Side slope (batter) fill abutting the road structure or back slope fill.
IfcEarthworksFill.SLOPEFILL.Name: Slopefill

IfcEarthworksFill.SUBGRADE.Definition: Type of earthworks element forming the structure below pavement and above natural soil.;
IfcEarthworksFill.SUBGRADE.Name: Subgrade

IfcEarthworksFill.SUBGRADEBED.Definition: Upper part of the soil, natural or constructed, that supports the loads transmitted by the overlying structure of a road, runway, or similar hard surface.
IfcEarthworksFill.SUBGRADEBED.Name: Subgradebed

IfcEarthworksFill.TRANSITIONSECTION.Definition: Section of subgrade to ensure the consistency of stiffness and prevent uneven settlement. Transition section may appear e.g. between: embankment and bridge abutment; embankment and transverse structure; cutting and tunnel; embankment and cutting.
IfcEarthworksFill.TRANSITIONSECTION.Name: Transition Section

NominalLength.Name: Nominal Length
NominalLength.Definition: The nominal overall length of the object. The size information is provided in addition to the shape representation and the geometric parameters used within. In case of inconsistency between the geometric parameters and the size properties, provided in the attached property set, the geometric parameters take precedence.

IfcGeotechnicalStratum.SOLID.Definition: Representation of the concept of an identified discrete almost homogenous solid geological or surface feature, including discontinuities such as faults, fractures, boundaries and interfaces that are not explicitly modelled.
IfcGeotechnicalStratum.SOLID.Name: Solid

CohesionBehaviour.Name: Cohesion Behaviour
CohesionBehaviour.Definition: Cohesive shear strength of a rock or soil that is independent of interparticle friction.

FrictionAngle.Name: Friction Angle
FrictionAngle.Definition: Friction angle is the tested inclination angle from horizontal.

FrictionBehaviour.Name: Friction Behaviour
FrictionBehaviour.Definition: Friction shear strength of a rock or soil that is dependent on interparticle friction.

HydraulicConductivity.Name: Hydraulic Conductivity
HydraulicConductivity.Definition: Hydraulic Conductivity (permeability) of soil for water, given with the K or Kf value in m/s

LoadBearingCapacity.Name: Load Bearing Capacity
LoadBearingCapacity.Definition: Maximum load bearing capacity of the floor structure throughtout the storey as designed.

NValue.Name: Nvalue
NValue.Definition: Blow count from standard penetration testing, to ISO 22476-3, ASTM D1586[1] and Australian Standards AS 1289.6.3.1, which correlates to other engineering properties of soils.

PermeabilityBehaviour.Name: Permeability Behaviour
PermeabilityBehaviour.Definition: Proportionality constant in Darcy's law which relates flow rate and viscosity to a pressure gradient applied to the porous media.

PoisonsRatio.Name: Poisons Ratio
PoisonsRatio.Definition: Ratio of transverse contraction strain to longitudinal extension strain in the direction of stretching force.

PwaveVelocity.Name: Pwave Velocity
PwaveVelocity.Definition: P-wave velocity of a rock or soil.

Resistivity.Name: Resistivity
Resistivity.Definition: Electrical resistivity of a rock or soil (Ohm-m).

SettlementBehaviour.Name: Settlement Behaviour
SettlementBehaviour.Definition: Estimate of the settlement/compaction behaviour of the stratum.

SwaveVelocity.Name: Swave Velocity
SwaveVelocity.Definition: S-wave velocity of a rock or soil.

AirVolume.Name: Air Volume
AirVolume.Definition: Relative volume of air stratum constituents.

BouldersVolume.Name: Boulders Volume
BouldersVolume.Definition: Relative volume of boulders (typically larger than 200mm) stratum constituents.

ClayVolume.Name: Clay Volume
ClayVolume.Definition: Relative volume of clay (typically smaller than 0.002mm) stratum constituents.

CobblesVolume.Name: Cobbles Volume
CobblesVolume.Definition: Relative volume of cobbles (typically larger than 63mm) stratum constituents.

CompositeFractions.Name: Composite Fractions
CompositeFractions.Definition: Denomination into soil groups by composite fractions

ContaminantVolume.Name: Contaminant Volume
ContaminantVolume.Definition: Relative volume of contaminant stratum constituents.

FillVolume.Name: Fill Volume
FillVolume.Definition: Relative volume of fill (controlled placement of anthropogenic soil) stratum constituents.

GravelVolume.Name: Gravel Volume
GravelVolume.Definition: Relative volume of gravel (typically larger than 2mm) stratum constituents.

OrganicVolume.Name: Organic Volume
OrganicVolume.Definition: Relative volume of organic (peat/humus) stratum constituents especially soil.

RockVolume.Name: Rock Volume
RockVolume.Definition: Relative volume of rock stratum constituents.

SandVolume.Name: Sand Volume
SandVolume.Definition: Relative volume of sand (typically smaller than 2mm) stratum constituents.

SiltVolume.Name: Silt Volume
SiltVolume.Definition: Relative volume of silt (typically smaller than 0.063mm) stratum constituents.

WaterVolume.Name: Water Volume
WaterVolume.Definition: Relative volume of water stratum constituents.

IfcGeotechnicalStratum.VOID.Definition: Representation of the concept of an identified discrete air filled geological feature, including caves and other voids.
IfcGeotechnicalStratum.VOID.Name: Void

IfcGeotechnicalStratum.WATER.Definition: Representation of the concept of an identified discrete water filled geological or surface feature including lakes, rivers and seas.
IfcGeotechnicalStratum.WATER.Name: Water

SeicheRange.Name: Seiche Range
SeicheRange.Definition: Indicative (95%-100%) range between peaks and troughts of seiche (resonant) waves.

TidalRange.Name: Tidal Range
TidalRange.Definition: Indicative (95%-100%) range between high and low tide levels.

WaveRange.Name: Wave Range
WaveRange.Definition: Indicative (95%-100%) range between peaks and troughs of waves

IfcPavement.FLEXIBLE.Definition: Pavement with a bituminous surfacing and with a base layer with or without a hydrocarbon binder.
IfcPavement.FLEXIBLE.Name: Flexible

IfcPavement.RIGID.Definition: Pavement substantially constructed of cement concrete.
IfcPavement.RIGID.Name: Rigid

IfcReinforcedSoil.DYNAMICALLYCOMPACTED.Definition: The method of using dynamic tamping machine usually free falling a heavy hammer from the height, compacting the soil and quickly improving the bearing capacity of the foundation.
IfcReinforcedSoil.DYNAMICALLYCOMPACTED.Name: Dynamically Compacted

IfcReinforcedSoil.GROUTED.Definition: A method of injecting curable slurry into cracks or pores of a geotechnical foundation to improve its physical and mechanical properties.
IfcReinforcedSoil.GROUTED.Name: Grouted

IfcReinforcedSoil.REPLACED.Definition: Dig out the soft soil in a certain range below the foundation ground and then backfill the area with high strength, low compressibility and no corrosive materials.
IfcReinforcedSoil.REPLACED.Name: Replaced

IfcReinforcedSoil.ROLLERCOMPACTED.Definition: A kind of compacting method that adopts rolling machinery, repeated rolling and vibration compacts the foundation soil, increasing strength and descreasing compressibility.
IfcReinforcedSoil.ROLLERCOMPACTED.Name: Roller Compacted

IfcReinforcedSoil.SURCHARGEPRELOADED.Definition: A method that applies load to the foundation to discharge pore water, and the foundation is consolidated to improve the foundation strength. Unloading when the carrying capacity reaches the required level.
IfcReinforcedSoil.SURCHARGEPRELOADED.Name: Surcharge Preloaded

IfcReinforcedSoil.VERTICALLYDRAINED.Definition: A method to set vertical drainage measures in the foundation, so that pore water in the soil is discharged and the foundation strength is improved.
IfcReinforcedSoil.VERTICALLYDRAINED.Name: Vertically Drained

IfcSign.MARKER.Definition: A Sign type formed of a vertical post (possibly with some lettering or symbols) usually used to delimitate distance or the location of some equipment.
IfcSign.MARKER.Name: Marker

IfcSign.MIRROR.Definition: A sign type that provides information via a reflective mirror surface.
IfcSign.MIRROR.Name: Mirror

IfcSign.PICTORAL.Definition: A sign type formed of a flat plate with some written or symbolic images on it.
IfcSign.PICTORAL.Name: Pictoral

IfcSignal.AUDIO.Definition: A signal type formed of an active device conveying information by emitting an audio signal such as a beep, ring, horn or explosive sound.
IfcSignal.AUDIO.Name: Audio

IfcSignal.MIXED.Definition: A signal type formed of an active device conveying information in both a visual and audio manner.
IfcSignal.MIXED.Name: Mixed

IfcSignal.VISUAL.Definition: A signal type formed of an active device conveying information in a visual manner such as a light, cluster of lights, or mechanical moving shapes.
IfcSignal.VISUAL.Name: Visual

IfcActionRequest.PHONE.Definition: Request was made verbally over a telephone.
IfcActionRequest.PHONE.Name: Phone

IfcActionRequest.POST.Definition: Request was made through postal mail.
IfcActionRequest.POST.Name: Post

IfcActionRequest.VERBAL.Definition: Request was made verbally in person.
IfcActionRequest.VERBAL.Name: Verbal

IfcCostSchedule.BUDGET.Definition: An allocation of money for a particular purpose.
IfcCostSchedule.BUDGET.Name: Budget

IfcCostSchedule.COSTPLAN.Definition: An assessment of the amount of money needing to be expended for a defined purpose based on incomplete information about the goods and services required for a construction or installation.
IfcCostSchedule.COSTPLAN.Name: Cost Plan

IfcCostSchedule.ESTIMATE.Definition: An assessment of the amount of money needing to be expended for a defined purpose based on actual information about the goods and services required for a construction or installation.
IfcCostSchedule.ESTIMATE.Name: Estimate

IfcCostSchedule.PRICEDBILLOFQUANTITIES.Definition: A complete listing of all work items forming construction or installation works in which costs have been allocated to work items.
IfcCostSchedule.PRICEDBILLOFQUANTITIES.Name: Priced Bill of Quantities

IfcCostSchedule.SCHEDULEOFRATES.Definition: A listing of each type of goods forming construction or installation works with the cost of purchase, construction/installation, overheads and profit assigned so that additional items of that type can be costed.
IfcCostSchedule.SCHEDULEOFRATES.Name: Schedule of Rates

IfcCostSchedule.TENDER.Definition: An offer to provide goods and services.
IfcCostSchedule.TENDER.Name: Tender

IfcCostSchedule.UNPRICEDBILLOFQUANTITIES.Definition: A complete listing of all work items forming construction or installation works in which costs have not yet been allocated to work items.
IfcCostSchedule.UNPRICEDBILLOFQUANTITIES.Name: Unpriced Bill of Quantities

IfcPermit.ACCESS.Definition: Enables access to an identified area.
IfcPermit.ACCESS.Name: Access

IfcPermit.BUILDING.Definition: Enables work to proceed by getting regulatory permissions.
IfcPermit.BUILDING.Name: Building

IfcPermit.WORK.Definition: Enables work to be carried out in an identified area.
IfcPermit.WORK.Name: Work

IfcProjectOrder.CHANGEORDER.Definition: An instruction to make a change to a product or work being undertaken and a description of the work that is to be performed.
IfcProjectOrder.CHANGEORDER.Name: Change Order

ReasonForChange.Name: Reason for Change
ReasonForChange.Definition: A description of the problem for why a change is needed.

IfcProjectOrder.MAINTENANCEWORKORDER.Definition: An instruction to carry out maintenance work and a description of the work that is to be performed.
IfcProjectOrder.MAINTENANCEWORKORDER.Name: Maintenance Work Order

ContractualType.Name: Contractual Type
ContractualType.Definition: The contractual type of the work.

FaultPriorityType.Name: Fault Priority Type
FaultPriorityType.Definition: Identifies the predefined types of priority that can be assigned from which the type may be set where: High: action is required urgently.; Medium: action can occur within a reasonable period of time.; Low: action can occur when convenient.

Values.Description: Identifies the predefined types of priority that can be assigned from which the type may be set where:High: action is required urgently
Low: action can occur when convenient
Medium: action can occur within a reasonable period of time

IfNotAccomplished.Name: If Not Accomplished
IfNotAccomplished.Definition: Comments if the job is not accomplished.

LocationPriorityType.Name: Location Priority Type
LocationPriorityType.Definition: Identifies the predefined types of priority that can be assigned from which the type may be set where: High: action is required urgently.; Medium: action can occur within a reasonable period of time.; Low: action can occur when convenient.

Values.Description: Identifies the predefined types of priority that can be assigned from which the type may be set where:High: action is required urgently
Low: action can occur when convenient
Medium: action can occur within a reasonable period of time

MaintenanceType.Name: Maintenance Type
MaintenanceType.Definition: Identifies the predefined types of maintenance that can be done from which the type that generates the maintenance work order may be set where: ConditionBased: generated as a result of the condition of an asset or artefact being less than a determined value.; Corrective: generated as a result of an immediate and urgent need for maintenance action.; PlannedCorrective: generated as a result of immediate corrective action being needed but with sufficient time available for the work order to be included in maintenance planning.; Scheduled: generated as a result of a fixed, periodic maintenance requirement.

Values.Description: Identifies the predefined types of maintenance that can be done from which the type that generates the maintenance work order may be set where:ConditionBased: generated as a result of the condition of an asset or artefact being less than a determined value
Corrective: generated as a result of an immediate and urgent need for maintenance action
PlannedCorrective: generated as a result of immediate corrective action being needed but with sufficient time available for the work order to be included in maintenance planning
Scheduled: generated as a result of a fixed

ProductDescription.Name: Product Description
ProductDescription.Definition: A textual description of the products that require the work.

ScheduledFrequency.Name: Scheduled Frequency
ScheduledFrequency.Definition: The period of time between expected instantiations of a work order that may have been predefined.

WorkTypeRequested.Name: Work Type Requested
WorkTypeRequested.Definition: Work type requested in circumstances where there are categorizations of types of work task. It could be used to identify a remedial task, minor work task, electrical task etc.

IfcProjectOrder.MOVEORDER.Definition: An instruction to move persons and artefacts and a description of the move locations, objects to be moved, etc.
IfcProjectOrder.MOVEORDER.Name: Move Order

IfcProjectOrder.PURCHASEORDER.Definition: An instruction to purchase goods and/or services and a description of the goods and/or services to be purchased that is to be performed.
IfcProjectOrder.PURCHASEORDER.Name: Purchase Order

IsFOB.Name: Is Fob
IsFOB.Definition: Indication of whether contents of the purchase order are delivered 'Free on Board' (= True) or not (= False). FOB is a shipping term which indicates that the supplier pays the shipping costs (and usually also the insurance costs) from the point of manufacture to a specified destination, at which point the buyer takes responsibility.

Values.Description: Indication of whether contents of the purchase order are delivered 'Free on Board' (= True) or not (= False)
Indication of whether contents of the purchase order are delivered 'Free on Board' (= True) or not (= False)

ShipMethod.Name: Ship Method
ShipMethod.Definition: Method of shipping that will be used for goods or services.

IfcProjectOrder.WORKORDER.Definition: A general instruction to carry out work and a description of the work to be done. Note the difference between a work order generally and a maintenance work order.
IfcProjectOrder.WORKORDER.Name: Work Order

ContractualType.Name: Contractual Type
ContractualType.Definition: The contractual type of the work.

IfNotAccomplished.Name: If Not Accomplished
IfNotAccomplished.Definition: Comments if the job is not accomplished.

ProductDescription.Name: Product Description
ProductDescription.Definition: A textual description of the products that require the work.

WorkTypeRequested.Name: Work Type Requested
WorkTypeRequested.Definition: Work type requested in circumstances where there are categorizations of types of work task. It could be used to identify a remedial task, minor work task, electrical task etc.

IfcStructuralCurveAction.CONST.Definition: The load has a constant value over its entire extent.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.CONST.Name: Const

IfcStructuralCurveAction.DISCRETE.Definition: The load is specified as a series of discrete load points.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.DISCRETE.Name: Discrete

IfcStructuralCurveAction.EQUIDISTANT.Definition: The load consists of n consecutive sections of same length and is specified by n+1 load samples. The interpolation type over the segments is not defined by this distribution type but may be qualified in IfcObject.ObjectType based on additional agreements.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.EQUIDISTANT.Name: Equidistant

IfcStructuralCurveAction.LINEAR.Definition: The load value is linearly distributed over the load's extent.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.LINEAR.Name: Linear

IfcStructuralCurveAction.PARABOLA.Definition: The load value is distributed as a half wave described by a symmetric quadratic parabola.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.PARABOLA.Name: Parabola

IfcStructuralCurveAction.POLYGONAL.Definition: The load consists of several consecutive linear sections.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.POLYGONAL.Name: Polygonal

IfcStructuralCurveAction.SINUS.Definition: The load value is distributed as a sinus half wave.
IfcStructuralCurveAction.SINUS.Name: Sinus

IfcStructuralCurveMember.CABLE.Definition: A tension member which is able to carry transverse loads only under large deflection.
IfcStructuralCurveMember.CABLE.Name: Cable

IfcStructuralCurveMember.PIN_JOINED_MEMB.Definition: A member with capacity to carry axial loads only, i.e. a link. Typically used in trusses.
IfcStructuralCurveMember.PIN_JOINED_MEMB.Name: Pin Joined Member

IfcStructuralCurveMember.RIGID_JOINED_ME.Definition: A member with capacity to carry transverse and axial loads, i.e. a beam. Its actual joints may be rigid or pinned. Typically used in rigid frames.
IfcStructuralCurveMember.RIGID_JOINED_ME.Name: Rigid Joined Member

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.CONST.Definition: The load has a constant value over its entire extent.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.CONST.Name: Const

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.DISCRETE.Definition: The load is specified as a series of discrete load points.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.DISCRETE.Name: Discrete

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.EQUIDISTANT.Definition: The load consists of n consecutive sections of same length and is specified by n+1 load samples. The interpolation type over the segments is not defined by this distribution type but may be qualified in IfcObject.ObjectType based on additional agreements.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.EQUIDISTANT.Name: Equidistant

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.LINEAR.Definition: The load value is linearly distributed over the load's extent.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.LINEAR.Name: Linear

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.PARABOLA.Definition: The load value is distributed as a half wave described by a symmetric quadratic parabola.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.PARABOLA.Name: Parabola

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.POLYGONAL.Definition: The load consists of several consecutive linear sections.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.POLYGONAL.Name: Polygonal

IfcStructuralCurveReaction.SINUS.Definition: The load value is distributed as a sinus half wave.
IfcStructuralCurveReaction.SINUS.Name: Sinus

IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_CASE.Definition: Groups LOAD_GROUPs and instances of subtypes of IfcStructuralAction.; It should be used as a container for loads with the same origin.
IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_CASE.Name: Load Case

IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_COMBINATION.Definition: An intermediate level between LOAD_CASE and LOAD_COMBINATION. This level is obsolete and deprecated. Before the introduction of IfcRelAssignsToGroupByFactor, the purpose of this level was to provide a factor with which one or more LOAD_CASEs occur in a LOAD_COMBINATION.
IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_COMBINATION.Name: Load Combination

IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_GROUP.Definition: Groups instances of subtypes of IfcStructuralAction. It shall be used as a container for loads grouped together for specific purposes, such as loads which are part of a special load pattern.
IfcStructuralLoadGroup.LOAD_GROUP.Name: Load Group

IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.BILINEAR.Definition: The load value is bilinearly distributed over the load's extent.
IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.BILINEAR.Name: Bilinear

IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.CONST.Definition: The load has a constant value over its entire extent.
IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.CONST.Name: Const

IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.DISCRETE.Definition: The load is specified as a series of discrete load points.
IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.DISCRETE.Name: Discrete

IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.ISOCONTOUR.Definition: The load is specified by a series of iso-curves (level sets), i.e. curves at which the load value is constant. These curves run perpendicularly to the load gradient.
IfcStructuralSurfaceAction.ISOCONTOUR.Name: Isocontour

IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.BENDING_ELEME.Definition: A member with capacity to carry out-of-plane loads, i.e. a plate.
IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.BENDING_ELEME.Name: Bending Element

IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.MEMBRANE_ELEM.Definition: A member with capacity to carry in-plane loads, for example a shear wall.
IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.MEMBRANE_ELEM.Name: Membrane Element

IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.SHELL.Definition: A member with capacity to carry in-plane and out-of-plane loads, i.e. a combination of bending element and membrane element.
IfcStructuralSurfaceMember.SHELL.Name: Shell

IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.BILINEAR.Definition: The load value is bilinearly distributed over the load's extent.
IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.BILINEAR.Name: Bilinear

IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.CONST.Definition: The load has a constant value over its entire extent.
IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.CONST.Name: Const

IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.DISCRETE.Definition: The load is specified as a series of discrete load points.
IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.DISCRETE.Name: Discrete

IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.ISOCONTOUR.Definition: The load is specified by a series of iso-curves (level sets), i.e. curves at which the load value is constant. These curves run perpendicularly to the load gradient.
IfcStructuralSurfaceReaction.ISOCONTOUR.Name: Isocontour

IfcFooting.CAISSON_FOUNDATION.Definition: A foundation construction type used in underwater construction.
IfcFooting.CAISSON_FOUNDATION.Name: Caisson Foundation

IfcFooting.FOOTING_BEAM.Definition: Footing elements that are in bending and are supported clear of the ground. They will normally span between piers, piles or pile caps. They are distinguished from beams in the building superstructure since they will normally require a lower grade of finish. They are distinguished from STRIP_FOOTING since they are clear of the ground surface and hence require support to the lower face while the concrete is curing.
IfcFooting.FOOTING_BEAM.Name: Footing Beam

IfcFooting.PAD_FOOTING.Definition: An element that transfers the load of a single column (possibly two) to the ground.
IfcFooting.PAD_FOOTING.Name: Pad Footing

IsReinforced.Name: Is Reinforced
IsReinforced.Definition: Indicates whether the foundation is reinforced (TRUE) or not (FALSE).

Values.Description: Indicates whether the foundation is reinforced (TRUE) or not (FALSE)
Indicates whether the foundation is reinforced (TRUE) or not (FALSE)

LoadBearingCapacity.Name: Load Bearing Capacity
LoadBearingCapacity.Definition: Maximum load bearing capacity of the floor structure throughtout the storey as designed.

IfcFooting.PILE_CAP.Definition: An element that transfers the load from a column or group of columns to a pier or pile or group of piers or piles.
IfcFooting.PILE_CAP.Name: Pile Cap

IfcFooting.STRIP_FOOTING.Definition: A linear element that transfers loads into the ground from either a continuous element, such as a wall, or from a series of elements, such as columns.
IfcFooting.STRIP_FOOTING.Name: Strip Footing

IfcPile.DRIVEN.Definition: A rammed, vibrated, or otherwise driven pile.
IfcPile.DRIVEN.Name: Driven

IfcReinforcingBar.LIGATURE.Definition: The reinforcing bar is a ligature (link, stirrup).
IfcReinforcingBar.LIGATURE.Name: Ligature

IfcReinforcingBar.MAIN.Definition: The reinforcing bar is a main bar.
IfcReinforcingBar.MAIN.Name: Main

IfcReinforcingBar.SHEAR.Definition: The reinforcing bar is a shear bar.
IfcReinforcingBar.SHEAR.Name: Shear

IfcReinforcingBar.SPACEBAR.Definition: A stirrup in pre-stressing system to position TendonConduit.
IfcReinforcingBar.SPACEBAR.Name: Space Bar

IfcReinforcingBar.STUD.Definition: The reinforcing bar is a stud.
IfcReinforcingBar.STUD.Name: Stud

IfcSurfaceFeature.DEFECT.Definition: Detected defect on the surface of an element, such as corroded or eroded area.
IfcSurfaceFeature.DEFECT.Name: Defect

IfcSurfaceFeature.HATCHMARKING.Definition: surface markings defined by enclosed 2d shape with defined hatch fillings.
IfcSurfaceFeature.HATCHMARKING.Name: Hatch Marking

IfcSurfaceFeature.RUMBLESTRIP.Name: Rumble Strip

IfcSurfaceFeature.TAG.Definition: A name tag, which allows to identify an element during production, delivery and assembly. May be manufactured in different ways, e.g. by printing or punching the tracking code onto the element or by attaching an actual tag.
IfcSurfaceFeature.TAG.Name: Tag

IfcSurfaceFeature.TRANSVERSERUMBLESTRIP.Definition: Type of rumble strip running across lane(s).
IfcSurfaceFeature.TRANSVERSERUMBLESTRIP.Name: Transverse Rumble Strip

IfcSurfaceFeature.TREATMENT.Definition: A subtractive surface feature, e.g. grinding, or an additive surface feature, e.g. coating, or an impregnating treatment, or a series of any of these kinds of treatments.
IfcSurfaceFeature.TREATMENT.Name: Treatment

IfcTendon.BAR.Definition: The tendon is configured as a bar.
IfcTendon.BAR.Name: Bar

IfcTendonAnchor.COUPLER.Definition: The anchor is an intermediate device which connects two tendons.
IfcTendonAnchor.COUPLER.Name: Coupler

IfcTendonAnchor.FIXED_END.Definition: The anchor fixes the end of a tendon.
IfcTendonAnchor.FIXED_END.Name: Fixed End

IfcTendonAnchor.TENSIONING_END.Definition: The anchor is used or can be used to prestress the tendon.
IfcTendonAnchor.TENSIONING_END.Name: Tensioning End

IfcTendonConduit.COUPLER.Definition: A part to connect the conduits located in two different deck segments and related to the same tendon.
IfcTendonConduit.COUPLER.Name: Coupler

IfcTendonConduit.DIABOLO.Definition: A part of tendon conduit associated to deviator.
IfcTendonConduit.DIABOLO.Name: Diabolo

IfcTendonConduit.DUCT.Definition: A Sleeve or duct is related to the thickness of the conduit depending on the conduit, either cast into the concrete structure or placed adjacent to it.
IfcTendonConduit.DUCT.Name: Duct

IfcTendonConduit.GROUTING_DUCT.Definition: An additional small conduit connected to the main conduit to allow grouting in case of bonded post-tensioning, such as Grout inlet, Grout outlet and Grout vent.
IfcTendonConduit.GROUTING_DUCT.Name: Grouting Duct

IfcTendonConduit.TRUMPET.Definition: A specific part of conduit which has to be widened when reaching the tendon anchor because the strands are connected individually on the anchor.
IfcTendonConduit.TRUMPET.Name: Trumpet

IfcVoidingFeature.CHAMFER.Definition: A skewed plane end cut, removing material only across a part of the profile of the voided element.
IfcVoidingFeature.CHAMFER.Name: Chamfer

IfcVoidingFeature.CUTOUT.Definition: An internal cutout (creating an opening) or external cutout (creating a recess) of arbitrary shape. The edges between cutting planes may be overcut or undercut, i.e. rounded.
IfcVoidingFeature.CUTOUT.Name: Cutout

IfcVoidingFeature.EDGE.Definition: A shape modification along an edge of the element with the edge length as the predominant dimension of the feature, and feature profile dimensions which are typically much smaller than the edge length. Can for example be a chamfer edge (differentiated from a chamfer by its ratio of dimensions and thus usually manufactured differently), rounded edge (a convex edge feature), or fillet edge (a concave edge feature).
IfcVoidingFeature.EDGE.Name: Edge

IfcVoidingFeature.HOLE.Definition: A circular or slotted or threaded hole, typically but not necessarily of smaller dimension than what would be considered a cutout.
IfcVoidingFeature.HOLE.Name: Hole

IfcVoidingFeature.MITER.Definition: A skewed plane end cut, removing material across the entire profile of the voided element.
IfcVoidingFeature.MITER.Name: Miter

IfcVoidingFeature.NOTCH.Definition: An external cutout of with a mostly rectangular cutting profile. The edges between cutting planes may be overcut or undercut, i.e. rounded.
IfcVoidingFeature.NOTCH.Name: Notch
